REPLACE INTO `questions` (`id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`, `scene_id`, `question_type_id`, `order`, `head`, `text`, `explanation`, `points`, `answer_count`, `old_question_id`) VALUES
	(1, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You are tasked with setting up the devices running Windows 10 for the IT department.<br /><br />All IT devices include Trusted Platform Module (TPM) version 1.2. All Development devices include TPM version 2.0.<br /><br />You need to decide on a path to meet the Windows 10 requirements and recommend how many, if any, new devices are needed.<br /><br />Which two actions should you perform? Each correct answer presents part of the solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>The IT department needs 75 devices that support both Hyper-V and virtual smart cards. Requirements for Windows Hyper-V state that you need a 64-bit processor platform with Second Level Address Translation (SLAT), and only 50 machines in the existing pool meets that requirement. The devices also meet the requirement of at least 4 GB RAM. You should upgrade the 50 Windows 8.1 Enterprise IT devices to Windows 10 Enterprise and purchase 25 new devices.<br><br>Virtual smart care support requires TPM 1.2 or later, so the IT devices meet this requirement.<br><br>You should not purchase 75 or 50 new devices: One of the scenario requirements is to minimize the number of new devices purchased. Since you already have 50 machines that meet the goal, you would have an additional 25 or 50 machines that are not needed.<br><br>You should not upgrade the Windows 8.1 Professional IT devices to Windows 10 Professional. Windows 10 Professional can run Hyper-V, but Hyper-V requires a 64-bit platform and those devices all have 32-bit processors.<br><br>You should not upgrade the Windows 8 Professional devices in the Development department to Windows 10 Professional. While 25 devices from the Development department are 64-bit, they do not have SLAT, which is a requirement for Hyper-V.<br><br>You should not perform a fresh install on all devices. Since 50 machines meet the Windows 10 upgrade pre-requisites, and you have a requirement to not do a fresh install if not needed as well as the time requirement to minimize downtime, this option does not meet your requirements.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Windows 10 Hyper-V System Requirements" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/virtualization/hyper-v-on-windows/reference/hyper-v-requirements" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 Hyper-V System Requirements<br></a><br><a title="Use Virtual Smart Cards" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/identity-protection/virtual-smart-cards/virtual-smart-card-use-virtual-smart-cards" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Use Virtual Smart Cards</a><br><br><br><br></p></p>', 10, 7, 1),
	(2, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You are tasked with setting up the devices running Windows 10 for the Sales department.<br><br>You need to decide on a path to meet the Windows 10 and recommend how many, if any, new devices are needed.<br><br>Which action should you perform?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should upgrade the Windows 8 Professional Development devices to Windows 10 Enterprise. Secure Boot requires UEFI Class 2 or higher PCs, and 25 machines in the existing development department pool meets that requirement, so no new devices are required. You are authorized to move devices between departments as needed. You know that the devices will not be used in the Development department because the development Department has a Hyper-V requirement and the devices\' processors do not support Second Level Address Translation (SLAT), which is necessary to support Hyper-V.<br><br>You should not purchase 25 new devices. Since you already have 25 machines that meet the requirements, you would have an additional 25 machines that are not needed.<br><br>You should not upgrade the Windows 7 Home Sales devices to Windows 10. Secure Boot cannot run on UEFI Class 1 devices. You should not perform a clean install on the Sales department devices for the same reason.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Secure Boot Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-8.1-and-8/hh824987(v=win.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Secure Boot Overview</a><br><br><a title="Windows 10 Hyper-V System Requirements" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/virtualization/hyper-v-on-windows/reference/hyper-v-requirements" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 Hyper-V System Requirements</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 2),
	(3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You are tasked with setting up the devices running Windows 10 for the Development department.<br><br>You need to decide on a path to meet the Windows 10 and recommend how many, if any, new devices are needed. The IT department devices running Windows 8.1 Enterprise cannot be used because they are otherwise committed.<br><br>Which two actions should you perform? Each correct answer presents part of the solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should purchase 50 new devices and perform a fresh installation of Windows 10 Enterprise on all new devices. The requirements for Windows Hyper-V state that you need a 64-bit processor platform with Second Level Address Translation (SLAT). The only devices that meet this requirement are in the IT department and you are specifically told that you cannot use those devices. This leads you to purchase 50 new devices.<br><br>You should not purchase 0 new devices. You need 50 devices that meet the requirements and no devices currently do, so you need to purchase 50.<br><br>You should not purchase 75 new devices. This is more devices than you need and would leave you with extra devices.<br><br>You should not upgrade the Windows 8 Home Development devices to Windows 10 Professional. Windows 10 Professional can run Hyper-V, but Hyper-V requires a 64-bit platform.<br><br>You should not upgrade the Windows 8 Professional Development devices to Windows 10 Professional. While the devices from the development department are 64-bit, they do not have SLAT, which is a requirement for Hyper-V.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows 10 Hyper-V System Requirements" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/virtualization/hyper-v-on-windows/reference/hyper-v-requirements" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 Hyper-V System Requirements</a></p></p>', 10, 6, 3),
	(4, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to verify Hyper-V hardware compatibility for existing devices.<br><br>Which command or cmdlet should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should run the systeminfo.exe command to check if the machine returns a YES value on all listed Hyper-V requirements, such as VM Monitor Mode Extensions, Virtualization Enabled In Firmware, Second Level Address Translation and Data Extension Prevention Available.<br><br>You should not run the Enable-WindowsOptionalFeature Windows PowerShell cmdlet. This cmdlet can install Hyper-V, but it does not perform a requirements test.<br><br>You should not run the DISM command. This command can be used to install Hyper-V, but it does not perform a requirements test.<br><br>You should not run the Enable-VMIntegrationService Windows PowerShell cmdlet. This cmdlet enables integration services on a virtual machine, but it does not perform a requirements test.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows 10 Hyper-V System Requirements" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/virtualization/hyper-v-on-windows/reference/hyper-v-requirements" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 Hyper-V System Requirements</a><br><br><a title="Hyper-V" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/hyper-v/index" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Hyper-V</a><br><br><a title="Install Hyper-V on Windows 10" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/virtualization/hyper-v-on-windows/quick-start/enable-hyper-v" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Install Hyper-V on Windows 10</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 4),
	(5, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as a single Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain with a single physical location. You have 10 network client computers running Windows 7 Professional. You do not have Internet access.<br><br>You need to perform an in-place upgrade to Windows 10 Professional.<br><br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>For an in-place upgrade, you should run setup.exe from a network share while logged into Windows. This allows you to perform an upgrade without replacing existing files and applications. You must update each computer to Windows 7 Professional SP1 before starting the upgrade. This is the minimum level supporting an upgrade to Windows 10.<br><br>You should not start the system from a bootable USB drive and install Windows. A bootable USB drive can install a clean installation of Windows 10, but not perform an in-place upgrade.<br><br>You should not apply updates by using Windows Update. You do not have access to Windows Update if you do not have Internet access.<br><br>You should not apply a Windows 10 image by using imagex.exe. ImageX was deprecated after Windows 8 and is not supported for Windows 10 deployment. With Windows versions that support ImageX, ImageX performs a clean install, not an upgrade.<br><br>You should not use Windows PE and run setup.exe from a network share. You would not be able to perform an in-place upgrade using Windows PE.<br><br>You should not run setup.exe from a network share without first applying SP1. This would only work if you had SP1 already installed.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Windows 10 deployment scenarios" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/windows-10-deployment-scenarios" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 deployment scenarios</a></p></p>', 10, 6, 5),
	(6, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as a single Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain with a single physical location. You have 10 Windows 8.1 domain client devices. The network does not have Internet access.<br><br>None of the devices has an optical drive and the devices will be offline during the installation of Windows 10.<br><br>You need to perform a clean installation of Windows 10.<br><br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should start the upgrade from a bootable USB drive. A bootable USB will allow you to perform a clean installation of Windows 10, even when devices are offline.<br><br>You should not apply updates by using Windows Update. Devices are offline, and even if they were not, you do not have access to Windows Update if you do not have Internet access.<br><br>You should not update the devices to SP1 and run setup.exe from a network share. The devices will be offline, and Windows 8.1 does not need an update before installation.<br><br>You should not apply a Windows 10 image by using imagex.exe. ImageX was deprecated after Windows 8 and is not supported for Windows 10 deployment.<br><br>You should not run setup.exe from a network share. The devices will be offline.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows 10 deployment scenarios" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/windows-10-deployment-scenarios" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 deployment scenarios</a></p></p>', 10, 6, 6),
	(7, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as a single Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain with a single physical location. You have 10 domain client computers running Windows 8.1. The computers do not have Internet access.<br><br>You need to do an in-place upgrade to Windows 10 on those Windows 8.1 computers. You should keep the administrative effort necessary to accomplish this to a minimum.<br><br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>For an in-place upgrade, you should run setup.exe from a network share while logged into Windows. This allows you to perform an upgrade without replacing existing files and applications.<br><br>You should not start the system from a bootable USB drive and install Windows. Starting the system from a bootable USB drive can install a clean installation of Windows 10, but it cannot perform an in-place upgrade.<br><br>You should not apply updates by using Windows Update. You will not have access to Windows Update if you do not have Internet access.<br><br>You should not update the devices to SP1 and run setup.exe from a network share. Windows 8.1 does not need an update before installation, so that includes an unnecessary step.<br><br>You should not apply a Windows 10 image by using imagex.exe. ImageX was deprecated after Windows 8 and is not supported for Windows 10 deployment. With Windows versions that support ImageX, ImageX performs a clean install, not an upgrade.<br><br>You should not use Windows PE and run setup.exe from a network share. You would not be able to perform an in-place upgrade using Windows PE.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows 10 deployment scenarios" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/windows-10-deployment-scenarios" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 deployment scenarios</a></p></p>', 10, 6, 7),
	(8, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as a single Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain with a single physical location. You have 10 domain client computers running Windows 8. All domain clients have Internet access through a perimeter network.<br><br>You need to instruct users about how to perform an in-place upgrade to Windows 10. The instructions should require minimal effort for the users.<br><br>What should you tell the users to do first?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should tell the users to apply updates by using Windows Update. This is the easiest deployment/upgrade solution, if you have users performing the tasks themselves. Users would first apply the update to Windows 8.1, and then perform the upgrade to Windows 10.<br><br>You should not tell the users to start the upgrade from a bootable USB drive. This would be a more difficult upgrade scenario for end-users, and it applies a clean installation of Windows 10 instead of an in-place upgrade.<br><br>You should not tell the users to update the devices to SP1 and run setup.exe from a network share. You do not need to install SP1, and this would require more effort from the users.<br><br>You should not apply a Windows 10 image by using imagex.exe. ImageX was deprecated after Windows 8 and is not supported for Windows 10 deployment. With Windows versions that support ImageX, ImageX performs a clean install, not an upgrade.<br><br>You should not tell the users to use Windows PE and run setup.exe from a network share. This would require more from the users and an in-place upgrade is not supported with Windows PE.<br><br>You should not tell the users to run setup.exe from a network share. This would require more effort from the users that using Windows Update.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows 10 deployment scenarios" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/windows-10-deployment-scenarios" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 deployment scenarios</a></p></p>', 10, 6, 8),
	(9, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your company upgrades all computers to Windows 10 and sets up Active Directory-based activation.<br><br>You need to verify that computers are receiving the license from the Volume Activation Services server.<br><br>Which slmgr.vbs command switch should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the slmgr.vbs command with the /dlv switch. This displays detailed license information for the installed operating system. By specifying the [Activation ID] parameter, it returns information that verifies that the VAS is used.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /ipk switch. This attempts to install a 5x5 product key, which is a unique series of 25 characters consisting of five sets of five alphanumeric characters. If the key is valid and applicable, the key is installed. If a key is already installed, it is silently replaced.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /ato switch. This attempts online activation of Windows. For retail editions and volume systems with a KMS host key or a Multiple Activation Key (MAK) installed, /ato prompts Windows to attempt online activation. For systems with a Generic Volume License Key (GVLK) installed, this prompts an attempt at KMS activation. Systems that have been set to suspend automatic KMS activation attempts (/stao) still attempt KMS activation when /ato is run.<br><br>You should not use the slmrg.vbs command with the /upk switch. This uninstalls the product key of the current Windows edition.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /act-type switch. This option sets a value in the registry that limits volume activation to a single type. Activation Type 1 limits activation to Active Directory only; 2 limits it to KMS activation; 3 to token-based activation. The 0 option allows any activation type and is the default value.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /stao or the /ctao switch. Both have been deprecated since Windows 8.1 and were replaced by the /act-type switch.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License" href="https://www.howtogeek.com/245445/how-to-use-slmgr-to-change-remove-or-extend-your-windows-license/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License<br></a><br><a title="Activate using Active Directory-based activation" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/volume-activation/activate-using-active-directory-based-activation-client" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Activate using Active Directory-based activation</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 7, 9),
	(10, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage the Volume Licensing environment for your domain. You have set up Active Directory-based activation and want to ensure that only Active Directory objects are used.<br><br>You need to disable KMS activation.<br><br>Which slmgr.vbs command switch should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the slmgr.vbs command with the /act-type switch. This option sets a value in the registry that limits volume activation to a single type. Activation Type 1 limits activation to Active Directory only; 2 limits it to KMS activation; 3 to token-based activation. The 0 option allows any activation type and is the default value.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /dlv switch. This displays detailed license information for the installed operating system. By specifying the [Activation ID] parameter, it returns information that verifies that the VAS is used.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /ipk switch. This attempts to install a 5x5 product key, which is a unique series of 25 characters consisting of five sets of five alphanumeric characters. If the key is valid and applicable, the key is installed. If a key is already installed, it is silently replaced.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /ato switch. This attempts online activation of Windows. For retail editions and volume systems with a KMS host key or a Multiple Activation Key (MAK) installed, /ato prompts Windows to attempt online activation. For systems with a Generic Volume License Key (GVLK) installed, this prompts an attempt at KMS activation. Systems that have been set to suspend automatic KMS activation attempts (/stao) still attempt KMS activation when /ato is run.<br><br>You should not use the slmrg.vbs command with the /upk switch. This uninstalls the product key of the current Windows edition.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /stao or the /ctao switch. Both have been deprecated since Windows 8.1 and were replace by the /act-type switch.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License" href="https://www.howtogeek.com/245445/how-to-use-slmgr-to-change-remove-or-extend-your-windows-license/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License</a><br><br><a title="Activate using Active Directory-based activation" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/volume-activation/activate-using-active-directory-based-activation-client" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Activate using Active Directory-based activation</a></p></p>', 10, 7, 10),
	(11, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are troubleshooting the license activation on a machine that has failed to automatically receive a license.<br><br>You need to attempt an online activation of Windows.<br><br>Which slmgr.vbs command switch should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the slmgr.vbs command with the /ato switch. This attempts online activation of Windows. For retail editions and volume systems with a KMS host key or a Multiple Activation Key (MAK) installed, /ato prompts Windows to attempt online activation. For systems with a Generic Volume License Key (GVLK) installed, this prompts an attempt at KMS activation. Systems that have been set to suspend automatic KMS activation attempts (/stao) still attempt KMS activation when /ato is run.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /act-type switch. This option sets a value in the registry that limits volume activation to a single type. Activation Type 1 limits activation to Active Directory only; 2 limits it to KMS activation; 3 to token-based activation. The 0 option allows any activation type and is the default value.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /dlv switch. This displays detailed license information for the installed operating system. By specifying the [Activation ID] parameter, it returns information that verifies that the VAS is used.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /ipk switch. This attempts to install a 5x5 product key, which is a unique series of 25 characters consisting of five sets of five alphanumeric characters. If the key is valid and applicable, the key is installed. If a key is already installed, it is silently replaced.<br><br>You should not use the slmrg.vbs command with the /upk switch. This uninstalls the product key of the current Windows edition.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /stao or the /ctao switch. Both have been deprecated since Windows 8.1 and were replace by the /act-type switch.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License" href="https://www.howtogeek.com/245445/how-to-use-slmgr-to-change-remove-or-extend-your-windows-license/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License</a><br><br><a title="Activate using Active Directory-based activation" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/volume-activation/activate-using-active-directory-based-activation-client" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Activate using Active Directory-based activation</a></p></p>', 10, 7, 11),
	(12, NULL, NULL, NULL, 3, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage the Volume Licensing Services for your company. A user reports that his machine is no longer activated. The user has not connected to your domain for 270 days.<br><br>You need to connect remotely to the machine and activate it without the option of connecting it to the domain.<br><br>Which slmgr.vbs command switch should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the slmgr.vbs command with the /ipk switch. This attempts to install a 5x5 product key, which is a unique series of 25 characters consisting of five sets of five alphanumeric characters. If the key is valid and applicable, the key is installed. If a key is already installed, it is silently replaced.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /act-type switch. This option sets a value in the registry that limits volume activation to a single type. Activation Type 1 limits activation to Active Directory only; 2 limits it to KMS activation; 3 to token-based activation. The 0 option allows any activation type and is the default value.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /dlv switch. This displays detailed license information for the installed operating system. By specifying the [Activation ID] parameter, it returns information that verifies that the VAS is used.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /ato switch. This attempts online activation of Windows. For retail editions and volume systems with a KMS host key or a Multiple Activation Key (MAK) installed, /ato prompts Windows to attempt online activation. For systems with a Generic Volume License Key (GVLK) installed, this prompts an attempt at KMS activation. Systems that have been set to suspend automatic KMS activation attempts (/stao) still attempt KMS activation when /ato is run.<br><br>You should not use the slmrg.vbs command with the /upk switch. This uninstalls the product key of the current Windows edition.<br><br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs command with the /stao or the /ctao switch. Both options have been deprecated since Windows 8.1 and were replace by the /act-type switch.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License" href="https://www.howtogeek.com/245445/how-to-use-slmgr-to-change-remove-or-extend-your-windows-license/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License</a><br><br><a title="Activate using Active Directory-based activation" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/volume-activation/activate-using-active-directory-based-activation-client" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Activate using Active Directory-based activation</a></p></p>', 10, 7, 12),
	(13, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the deployment administrator for your company. You have been asked to deploy a public facing Windows 10 Enterprise device, which will be used to collect sensitive personal data in a waiting room. The information is being stored on a collection server in the domain.<br> <br> You need to ensure that communication is secure, both to and from the collection server.<br> <br> Solution: You enable Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security and configure inbound and outbound rules as well as connection security rules.<br> <br> Does this solution meet the goal?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>This solution meets the goal. You should use Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security because it provides host-based, two-way network traffic filtering for a device. Windows Firewall with Advanced Security can block network traffic that is unauthorized. It provides end-to-end network communication secured with IPSec.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-firewall/windows-firewall-with-advanced-security" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security</a></p></p>', 10, 2, 13),
	(14, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the deployment administrator for your company. You have been asked to deploy a public facing Windows 10 Enterprise device, which will be used to collect sensitive personal data in a waiting room. The information is being stored on a collection server in the domain.<br><br> You need to ensure that communication is secure, both to and from the collection server.<br><br> Solution: You add an additional wireless network interface card (NIC) on the server and create a new virtual LAN (VLAN) dedicated to the public machine. You also need to ensure that all traffic from the client communicates on that VLAN.<br><br> Does this solution meet the goal?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should not use this solution because it is not secure. Creating a unique VLAN dedicated to the two machines in question does not guarantee it is secure, especially with this being a wireless VLAN. <br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-firewall/windows-firewall-with-advanced-security" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security</a><br><br><a title="VLAN Network Segmentation and Security- Chapter 5" href="http://resources.infosecinstitute.com/vlan-network-chapter-5/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">VLAN Network Segmentation and Security- Chapter 5</a></p></p>', 10, 2, 14),
	(15, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the deployment administrator for your company. You have been asked to deploy a public facing Windows 10 Enterprise device, which will be used to collect sensitive personal data in a waiting room. The information is being stored on a collection server in the domain.<br><br>You need to ensure that communication is secure, both to and from the collection server.<br><br>Solution: You add an additional network interface card (NIC) on the server and create a new virtual LAN (VLAN) dedicated to the public machine. You also need to ensure that all traffic from the client communicates on that VLAN.<br><br>Does this solution meet the goal?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should not use this solution because it is not secure. Creating a unique VLAN dedicated to the two machines in question does not guarantee it is secure, even if this is a wired network.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-firewall/windows-firewall-with-advanced-security" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security</a><br><br><a title="VLAN Network Segmentation and Security-Chapter 5" href="http://resources.infosecinstitute.com/vlan-network-chapter-5/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">VLAN Network Segmentation and Security- Chapter 5</a></p></p>', 10, 2, 15),
	(16, NULL, NULL, NULL, 4, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the deployment administrator for your company. You have been asked to deploy a public facing Windows 10 Enterprise device, which will be used to collect sensitive personal data in a waiting room. The information is being stored on a collection server in the domain.<br><br>You need to ensure that communication is secure, both to and from the collection server.<br><br>Solution: Set up the public machine to use Direct Access.<br><br>Does this solution meet the goal?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>This solution meets the goal. You should use a solution involving Direct Access because it is possible to configure internal devices to use Direct Access for additional security.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-firewall/windows-firewall-with-advanced-security" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security</a><br><br><a title="Enable DirectAccess" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2012-R2-and-2012/jj574163(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Enable DirectAccess</a></p></p>', 10, 2, 16),
	(17, NULL, NULL, NULL, 5, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage Windows 10 devices for a company. The company employs several developers who are using virtual hard drives to simulate different development environments.<br> <br> You must provide a storage solution for each developer that can tolerate one drive failure and automatically maintain data integrity, including proactive error correction.<br> <br> You need to recommend a storage solution and the required number of hard drives needed.<br> <br> Solution: Create a two-way mirror Storage Space using two disks. Format the drives with the Resilient File System (ReFS).<br> <br> Does this solution meet the goal?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>This solution meets the goal. This solution allows you to maintain data integrity due to utilizing ReFS, and it also allows for data protection that allows one drive to fail and still keep all data intact.<br> <br> ReFS provides support for automatically maintaining data integrity, which includes:<br> <br> * Validating data before reads and writes.<br> * Using checksums to detect data corruption.<br> * Automatic online data repair.<br> * Salvaging data and providing integrity after non-correctable data corruption.<br> * Proactive error correction through use of periodic scans.<br> <br> ReFS works most effectively when used with Storage Spaces.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12438/windows-10-storage-spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br>Chapter: Should I create a simple, mirror, or parity space?</p>\r\n<p><a title="Storage Spaces - Designing for Performance" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/15200.storage-spaces-designing-for-performance.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces - Designing for Performance</a><br><br><a title="Resilient File System (ReFS) overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/storage/refs/refs-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Resilient File System (ReFS) overview</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 2, 17),
	(18, NULL, NULL, NULL, 5, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage Windows 10 devices for a company. The company employs several developers who are using virtual hard drives to simulate different development environments.<br><br>You must provide a storage solution for each developer that can tolerate one drive failure and automatically maintain data integrity, including proactive error correction.<br><br>You need to recommend a storage solution and the required number of hard drives needed.<br><br>Solution: Create a three-way mirror Storage Space using five disks. Format the drives with NTFS.<br><br>Does this solution meet the goal?</p>', '<div id="explanationBody" class="scrollable">\r\n                        <p id="explanationBodyText"><p>This solution does not meet the goal. It would survive the failure of two drives, but it would not guarantee data integrity using NTFS. For data integrity with proactive error correction, ReFS is required. In order to set up a three-way mirror, five disks are required.<br><br>ReFS provides support for automatically maintaining data integrity, which includes:<br><br>* Validating data before reads and writes.<br>* Using checksums to detect data corruption.<br>* Automatic online data repair.<br>* Salvaging data and providing integrity after non-correctable data corruption.<br>* Proactive error correction through use of periodic scans.<br><br>ReFS works most effectively when used with Storage Spaces.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12438/windows-10-storage-spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br>Chapter: Should I create a simple, mirror, or parity space?</p>\r\n<p><a title="Storage Spaces - Designing for Performance" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/15200.storage-spaces-designing-for-performance.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces - Designing for Performance</a><br><br><a title="Resilient File System (ReFS) overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/storage/refs/refs-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Resilient File System (ReFS) overview</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 2, 18),
	(19, NULL, NULL, NULL, 5, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage Windows 10 devices for a company. The company employs several developers who are using virtual hard drives to simulate different development environments.<br><br>You must provide a storage solution for each developer that can tolerate one drive failure and automatically maintain data integrity, including proactive error correction.<br><br>You need to recommend a storage solution and the required number of hard drives needed.<br><br>Solution: Create a Parity Storage Space using three disks. Format the drives with NTFS.<br><br>Does this solution meet the goal?</p>', ' <p id="explanationBodyText"><p>This solution does not meet the goal. It would survive the failure of one drive, but it would not guarantee data integrity using NTFS. In order to guarantee data integrity with proactive error correction, ReFS is required.<br><br>ReFS provides support for automatically maintaining data integrity, which includes:<br><br>* Validating data before reads and writes.<br>* Using checksums to detect data corruption.<br>* Automatic online data repair.<br>* Salvaging data and providing integrity after non-correctable data corruption.<br>* Proactive error correction through use of periodic scans.<br><br>ReFS works most effectively when used with Storage Spaces.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12438/windows-10-storage-spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br>Chapter: Should I create a simple, mirror, or parity space?<br><br><a title="Resilient File System (ReFS) overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/storage/refs/refs-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Resilient File System (ReFS) overview</a><br><br><a title="Storage Spaces - Designing for Performance" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/15200.storage-spaces-designing-for-performance.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces - Designing for Performance</a></p></p>', 10, 2, 19),
	(20, NULL, NULL, NULL, 5, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage Windows 10 devices for a company. The company employs several developers who are using virtual hard drives to simulate different development environments.<br><br>You must provide a storage solution for each developer that can tolerate one drive failure and automatically maintain data integrity, including proactive error correction.<br><br>You need to recommend a storage solution and the required number of hard drives needed.<br><br>Solution: Create a Parity Storage Space using seven disks. Format the drives with the Resilient File System (ReFS).<br><br>Does this solution meet the goal?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>This solution meets the goal. This solution allows you to maintain data integrity due to utilizing ReFS, and it also allows for data protection that allows two drives to fail and still keep all data intact.<br><br>ReFS provides support for automatically maintaining data integrity, which includes:<br><br>* Validating data before reads and writes.<br>* Using checksums to detect data corruption.<br>* Automatic online data repair.<br>* Salvaging data and providing integrity after non-correctable data corruption.<br>* Proactive error correction through use of periodic scans.<br><br>ReFS works most effectively when used with Storage Spaces.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12438/windows-10-storage-spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br>Chapter: Should I create a simple, mirror, or parity space?</p>\r\n<p><a title="Storage Spaces - Designing for Performance" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/15200.storage-spaces-designing-for-performance.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces - Designing for Performance</a><br><br><a title="Resilient File System (ReFS) overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/storage/refs/refs-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Resilient File System (ReFS) overview</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 2, 20),
	(21, NULL, NULL, NULL, 6, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to set up a homegroup.<br><br>What should you do?</p>', ' <p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should enable TCP/IPv6. Homegroups in Windows 10 require IPv6 to work, and this is a common issue when troubleshooting homegroup setup.<br><br>You should not disable TCP/IPv6. This would cause you to not be able to set up homegroups at all, and it needs to be enabled.<br><br>You should not enable Microsoft Network Adapter Multiplexor Protocol. The Microsoft Network Adapter Multiplexor Protocol service is a kernel mode driver.<br><br>You should not enable File and Printer sharing. File and printer sharing does exactly what it is named, and it does not affect homegroups.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How to set up and manage Windows 10 HomeGroup on a local network" href="http://www.windowscentral.com/how-setup-and-manage-windows-10-homegroup-local-network" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to set up and manage Windows 10 HomeGroup on a local network<br></a><br><a title="HomeGroup from start to finish" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17145/windows-homegroup-from-start-to-finish" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">HomeGroup from start to finish<br></a><br><a title="&quot;Your network connection must have IPv6 enabled to create or join a homegroup&quot; error message when you try to create a homegroup in Windows 7" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/983276/your-network-connection-must-have-ipv6-enabled-to-create-or-join-a-hom" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">"Your network connection must have IPv6 enabled to create or join a homegroup" error message when you try to create a homegroup in Windows 7</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 21),
	(22, NULL, NULL, NULL, 6, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>A baseline image is saved to the NAS for each device and restore points have been created.<br><br>You need to restore a system to an earlier point.<br><br>Which two tools should you use? Each correct answer presents a complete solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use System Protection or Backup and Restore (Windows 7). System Protection is a quick way to perform a system restore without having to revert to the baseline system. Backup and Restore creates a backup of the latest version of your files on a schedule. It can also create a system image, which is a snapshot of your entire system.<br><br>You should not use File History. File History automatically saves multiple versions of a file, so you can restore a file to the way it was before it was changed or deleted. It does not provide a way to restore the entire system.<br><br>You should not use Storage Spaces. Storage Spaces are technically virtual drives that appear in File Explorer as normal local storage, and each storage space you create can be less than, equal to, or greater than the amount of the physical capacity available in the storage pool.<br><br>You should not use OneDrive. OneDrive (previously SkyDrive, Windows Live SkyDrive, and Windows Live Folders) is a file hosting service that allows users to sync files and later access them from a web browser or mobile device.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Recovery options in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12415/windows-10-recovery-options" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Recovery options in Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="How to Use File History in Windows 10" href="https://www.lifewire.com/use-file-history-in-windows-10-3891070" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Use File History in Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12438/windows-10-storage-spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="Beginner&#39;s guide to Microsoft OneDrive on Windows 10" href="https://www.windowscentral.com/how-get-started-onedrive-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Beginner\'s guide to Microsoft OneDrive on Windows 10</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 22),
	(23, NULL, NULL, NULL, 6, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to synchronize your tablet when outside of the network.<br><br>Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use OneDrive. OneDrive (previously SkyDrive, Windows Live SkyDrive, and Windows Live Folders) is a file hosting service that allows users to sync files and later access them from a web browser or mobile device.<br><br>You should not use Backup and Restore (Windows 7). Backup and Restore creates a backup of the latest version of your files on a schedule. It can also create a system image, which is a snapshot of your entire system.<br><br>You should not use File History. File History automatically saves multiple versions of a file, so you can restore a file to the way it was before it was changed or deleted.<br><br>You should not use Storage Spaces. Storage Spaces are technically virtual drives that appear in File Explorer as normal local storage, and each storage space you create can be less than, equal to, or greater than the amount of the physical capacity available in the storage pool.<br><br>You should not use System Protection. System Protection is used to restore to an earlier point without having to use a system image.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Add and sync shared folders to OneDrive" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12415/windows-10-recovery-options" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Add and sync shared folders to OneDrive</a><br><br><a title="How to Use File History in Windows 10" href="https://www.lifewire.com/use-file-history-in-windows-10-3891070" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Use File History in Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="Beginner&#39;s guide to Microsoft OneDrive on Windows 10" href="https://www.windowscentral.com/how-get-started-onedrive-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Beginner\'s guide to Microsoft OneDrive on Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="Recovery options in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12438/windows-10-storage-spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Recovery options in Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12438/windows-10-storage-spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 23),
	(24, NULL, NULL, NULL, 6, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to save older versions of Office documents.<br><br>Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use File History. File History automatically saves multiple versions of a file, so you can restore a file to the way it was before it was changed or deleted. You can configure how often a backup copy of the file in made and how long copies are retained, defaulting to "forever".<br><br>You should not use Backup and Restore (Windows 7). Backup and Restore creates a backup of the latest version of your files on a schedule. It can also create a system image, which is a snapshot of your entire system.<br><br>You should not use Storage Spaces. Storage Spaces are technically virtual drives that appear in File Explorer as normal local storage, and each storage space you create can be less than, equal to, or greater than the amount of the physical capacity available in the storage pool.<br><br>You should not use OneDrive. OneDrive (previously SkyDrive, Windows Live SkyDrive, and Windows Live Folders) is a file hosting service that allows users to sync files and later access them from a web browser or mobile device.<br><br>You should not use System Protection. System Protection is used to restore to an earlier point without having to use a system image.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows 8: File History explained" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dn448546.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 8: File History explained</a><br><br><a title="How to Back Up Your Computer Automatically with Windows 10&#39;s Built-in Tools" href="http://lifehacker.com/how-to-back-up-your-computer-automatically-with-windows-1762867473" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Back Up Your Computer Automatically with Windows 10\'s Built-in Tools</a><br><br><a title="How to Use File History in Windows 10" href="https://www.lifewire.com/use-file-history-in-windows-10-3891070" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Use File History in Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="Beginner&#39;s guide to Microsoft OneDrive on Windows 10" href="https://www.windowscentral.com/how-get-started-onedrive-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Beginner\'s guide to Microsoft OneDrive on Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="Recovery options in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12415/windows-10-recovery-options" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Recovery options in Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12438/windows-10-storage-spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 24),
	(25, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to configure the devices used in Singapore to use authentication methods other than standard passwords.<br><br>Which two authentication methods should you use? Each correct answer presents a complete solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>Picture passwords and PIN are available authentication methods. Both picture passwords and PIN numbers can be used on all Windows devices, including laptops and tablets, as authentication options.<br><br>You should not use Windows Hello with facial recognition. Facial recognition requires that your Windows device has a near-infrared (IR) camera. This is not included on the Singapore devices and a Web camera is not supported for facial recognition.<br><br>You should not use fingerprint passwords (fingerprint recognition). Fingerprint authentication requires a fingerprint scanner attached to the Windows device.<br><br>You should not use voice recognition. Windows 10 supports speech recognition as an input option but does not support voice as an authentication option.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Windows 10 authentication options leave passwords behind " href="https://searchenterprisedesktop.techtarget.com/tip/Windows-10-authentication-options-leave-passwords-behind" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 authentication options leave passwords behind</a> <br><br><a title="Windows Hello face authentication" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/design/device-experiences/windows-hello-face-authentication" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Hello face authentication<br></a><br><a title="Use speech recognition" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17208/windows-10-use-speech-recognition" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Use speech recognition<br></a><br><a title="What is Windows Hello?" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17215/windows-10-what-is-hello" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">What is Windows Hello?<br></a><br><a title="Windows 10 Tutorials 44 - How to Setup Picture Password " href="https://www.windowschimp.com/windows-10-tutorials-44-how-to-setup-picture-password/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 Tutorials 44 - How to Setup Picture Password<br></a> <br><a title="Windows 10: How to Log In without a Password" href="https://www.smallbusinesscomputing.com/biztools/windows-10-how-to-log-in-without-a-password.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10: How to Log In without a Password</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 25),
	(26, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to configure the devices in Auckland to use authentication methods other than standard passwords.<br><br>Which three authentication methods should you use? Each correct answer presents a complete solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use picture passwords, PIN numbers, or Windows Hello with facial recognition. Picture passwords and PIN numbers can be used on all Windows devices, including laptops and tablets. Facial recognition requires that your Windows device has a near-infrared camera, which is available in Auckland.<br><br>You should not use fingerprint passwords (fingerprint recognition). Fingerprint authentication requires a fingerprint scanner attached to the Windows device.<br><br>You should not use voice recognition. Windows 10 supports speech recognition as an input option but does not support voice as an authentication option.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows 10 authentication options leave passwords behind" href="https://searchenterprisedesktop.techtarget.com/tip/Windows-10-authentication-options-leave-passwords-behind" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 authentication options leave passwords behind</a><br><br><a title="Windows Hello face authentication" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/design/device-experiences/windows-hello-face-authentication" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Hello face authentication</a><br><br><a title="Use speech recognition " href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17208/windows-10-use-speech-recognition" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Use speech recognition </a><br><br><a title="What is Windows Hello?" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17215/windows-10-what-is-hello" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">What is Windows Hello?</a><br><br><a title="Windows 10 Tutorials 44 - How to Setup Picture Password" href="https://www.win