	(28, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to configure the devices in Tokyo to use authentication methods other than standard passwords.<br><br>Which two authentication methods should you use? Each correct answer presents a complete solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use picture passwords or PIN numbers. Both can be used on all Windows 10 devices, including laptops and tablets.<br><br>You should not use fingerprint passwords (fingerprint recognition). Fingerprint authentication requires a fingerprint scanner attached to the Windows device.<br><br>You should not use voice recognition. Windows 10 supports speech recognition as an input option, but it does not support voice as an authentication option.<br><br>You should not use Windows Hello with facial recognition. Facial recognition requires that your Windows device has a near-infrared (IR) camera.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows 10 authentication options leave passwords behind" href="https://searchenterprisedesktop.techtarget.com/tip/Windows-10-authentication-options-leave-passwords-behind" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 authentication options leave passwords behind</a><br><br><a title="Windows Hello face authentication" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/design/device-experiences/windows-hello-face-authentication" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Hello face authentication</a><br><br><a title="Use speech recognition " href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17208/windows-10-use-speech-recognition" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Use speech recognition </a><br><br><a title="What is Windows Hello?" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17215/windows-10-what-is-hello" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">What is Windows Hello?</a><br><br><a title="Windows 10 Tutorials 44 - How to Setup Picture Password" href="https://www.windowschimp.com/windows-10-tutorials-44-how-to-setup-picture-password/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 Tutorials 44 - How to Setup Picture Password</a><br><br><a title="Windows 10 - How to Log In without a Password" href="https://www.smallbusinesscomputing.com/biztools/windows-10-how-to-log-in-without-a-password.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 - How to Log In without a Password</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 28),
	(29, NULL, NULL, NULL, 8, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. Your company has an Azure subscription and uses Microsoft Operations Management Suite (OMS) to help manage on-premises and cloud environments. Your network uses proxy servers deployed in a perimeter network for Internet access. You have a large number of domain clients that run Windows 8.1.<br> <br> You need to migrate these domain clients from Windows 8.1 to Windows 10. You want to use Update Readiness to plan and manage the deployment process. You add Update Readiness to OMS.<br> <br> What should you do next?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>After adding Update Readiness to OMS, you should enroll the clients in Windows Analytics. The required steps to accomplish this are:<br> <br> 1. Copy your commercial ID key to map information from user computers to your OMS workspace.<br> 2. Configure your proxy sever to whitelist the required endpoints for data sharing.<br> 3. Deploy the compatibility update and related updates to scan devices and enable application usage tracking.<br> 4. Set diagnostic data levels through group policy or by using the Upgrade Readiness deployment script.<br> <br> At this point, it is recommended that you enroll a few pilot devices before enrolling all of your devices in Windows Analytics.<br> <br> You should not configure Diagnostic Health as your next step. This is an optional step and is supported for Windows 10 desktop devices only.<br> <br> You should not rank applications by importance. This is done after data collection to identify issues with applications so you can resolve any issues preventing upgrade.<br> <br> You should not initiate data collection before enrolling clients in Windows Analytics. You must enroll the devices first.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Get started with Upgrade Readiness" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/upgrade-readiness-get-started" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Get started with Upgrade Readiness</a><br><br><a title="Upgrade Readiness requirements" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/upgrade-readiness-requirements" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Upgrade Readiness requirements</a><br><br><a title="Use Upgrade Readiness to manage Windows upgrades" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/use-upgrade-readiness-to-manage-windows-upgrades" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Use Upgrade Readiness to manage Windows upgrades</a><br><br><a title="Enrolling devices in Windows Analytics" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/windows-analytics-get-started" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Enrolling devices in Windows Analytics</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 29),
	(30, NULL, NULL, NULL, 9, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You want to upgrade an existing PC to Windows 10. The PC is currently running Windows 7 Professional 64-bit.<br> <br> Your computer hardware specifications are as follows:<br> <br> Processor: 1 GHz CPU<br> RAM: 1 GB<br> Available hard disk space: 25 GB<br> Graphics card: DirectX 9 compatible with WDDM 1.0 drivers<br> <br> You need to prepare your computer for the upgrade.<br> <br> Which two actions must you take to be able to upgrade? Each correct answer presents part of the solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should update the operating system to Windows 7 SP1 because this version is required for a Windows 10 upgrade. You also need to add RAM because the minimum requirement for a 64-bit Windows 10 installation/upgrade is 2 GB. These minimum requirements must be met before attempting to upgrade the computer.<br> <br>You should not need to add hard disk space, because the minimum required for an upgrade of a 64-bit operating system is 20GB and you currently have 25GB available. The processor is within the specs of an upgrade, requiring only 1GHz. The graphics card is compatible with Windows 10, exceeding DirectX9 requirement.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Windows 10 Specifications &amp; Systems Requirements" href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/windows-10-specifications" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 Specifications &amp; Systems Requirements</a><br><br><a title="Upgrade Readiness requirements" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/upgrade-readiness-requirements" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Upgrade Readiness requirements</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 30),
	(31, NULL, NULL, NULL, 10, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You upgrade a computer from Windows 7 Professional SP1 to Windows 10 Pro.<br> <br> A user reports that some files were lost in the upgrade process.<br> <br> You need to recover the user\'s files.<br> <br> What are two possible ways to restore the user\'s files? Each correct answer presents a complete solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should either use the Windows.old folder or roll back the installation.<br> <br>The Windows.old folder is created automatically during the upgrade and can be used to recover items that were lost during migration. Windows.old expires and is automatically deleted after 30 days.<br> <br>You could also roll back the installation, which would restore the PC to its pre-migration state.<br> <br>You should not use either of the Windows PowerShell cmdlets. The Get-Content cmdlet is used to read text from a file. The Get-ChildItem cmdlet is used to read content in a folder, but it cannot be used to restore the files.<br> <br>You should not recover files from the setupact.log file. This file is created during installation and contains information about actions taken during installation. It does not contain any user files.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Windows.Old created from Clean install of Windows 10?" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/45788f58-ea5a-4f88-b623-6707a19c268f/windowsold-created-from-clean-install-of-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows.old created from clean install of Windows 10?</a><strong><br><br></strong><a title="Windows Setup Installation Process" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/manufacture/desktop/windows-setup-installation-process" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Setup Installation Process<br></a><br><a title="Deleting Windows.Old folder in windows 10 OS" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/abe24920-b2a5-4ac9-8090-b945eb1369f5/deleting-windowsold-folder-in-windows-10-os" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Deleting Windows.Old folder in windows 10 OS</a><a title="Deleting Windows.Old folder in windows 10 OS" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/abe24920-b2a5-4ac9-8090-b945eb1369f5/deleting-windowsold-folder-in-windows-10-os" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br></a><br><a title="Microsoft.PowerShell.Management" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.management" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Microsoft.PowerShell.Management<br></a><br><a title="Resolve Windows 10 upgrade errors: Technical information for IT Pros" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/resolve-windows-10-upgrade-errors" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Resolve Windows 10 upgrade errors: Technical information for IT Pros<br><br><br></a></p></p>', 10, 5, 31),
	(32, NULL, NULL, NULL, 11, 3, 0, NULL, '<p>You have a computer running Windows 7 Professional SP1.<br> <br> You need to configure a dual boot environment with Windows 7 Professional and Windows 10 Pro. You intend to use a secondary disk using a GUID Partition Table for the second operating system.<br> <br> You need to configure the system.<br> <br> Which three actions should you perform in sequence? To answer, move the appropriate actions from the list of possible actions to the answer area and arrange them in the correct order.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should perform the following steps in order:<br> <br> 1. Create an MBR-partitioned VHD on the secondary drive.<br> 2. Apply the Windows 10 installation image to the VHD.<br> 3. Set the Windows 10 environment to boot.<br> <br> You must create an MBR-partitioned VHD to configure a bootable virtual drive. You then apply the Windows 10 installation image to the virtual drive and specify it to boot.<br> <br> Formatting the drive as NTFS is not one of the three required steps. Its inclusion would leave one of the required steps out of the list. It is not necessary to format the VHD as a separate step.<br> <br> You cannot use the VHDX format. The VHDX format is not compatible with Windows 7.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Boot to a virtual hard disk: Add a VHDX or VHD to the boot menu" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/manufacture/desktop/boot-to-vhd--native-boot--add-a-virtual-hard-disk-to-the-boot-menu" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Boot to a virtual hard disk: Add a VHDX or VHD to the boot menu</a><br><a title="Windows 10 deployment scenarios" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/windows-10-deployment-scenarios" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows 10 deployment scenarios</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 7, 32),
	(33, NULL, NULL, NULL, 12, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage 20 developer computers that currently run Windows 8.1 Enterprise 64-bit edition.<br> <br>Developers frequently need to use both Windows 8.1 and Windows 10 to test applications that are being developed.<br> <br>You need to provide the developers easy access to both operating systems. You need to minimize the effort necessary to deploy a solution. You must minimize the time required to provide and use your solution.<br> <br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should enable Hyper-V features and install Windows 10 to a virtual hard disk (VHD). This would give developers the ability to test applications in Windows 10, without the need of leaving their host operating system. Hyper-V is supported on the 64-bit editions of Windows 8.1 Pro and Enterprise. This assumes the computers have at least 4 GB RAM.<br> <br> You should not create a Windows To Go workspace on a USB drive. This would require developers to reboot to switch operating systems.<br> <br> You should not create a dual boot installation. This would also require developers to reboot their machines.<br> <br> You should not perform an in-place upgrade to Windows 10, enabled Hyper-V features, and install Windows 8.1 to a virtual hard disk (VHD). This requires more effort than necessary to implement the solution.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Windows 10 deployment scenarios" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/windows-10-deployment-scenarios" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 deployment scenarios</a><br><a title="Hyper-V in Windows 8.1" href="https://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows8_1-windows_install-wininstalls/hyper-v-in-windows-81/246e99aa-a416-4a91-810c-379cf4174ece" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Hyper-V in Windows 8.1</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 33),
	(34, NULL, NULL, NULL, 13, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the systems administrator for your company. You plan to deploy Windows 10 to the entire organization. You download the Windows Assessment and Deployment Kit (Windows ADK).<br> <br> You need to add custom packaged drivers and applications in an answer file.<br> <br> Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Windows SIM to add packages to answer files. Windows SIM helps you create answer files that change Windows settings and run scripts during installation.<br> <br>You should not use DISM. DISM is used to mount offline images, add drivers to offline images, enable and disable features, add or remove packages, add language packs, add Universal Windows apps, and upgrade the Windows edition.<br> <br>You should not use Sysprep. Sysprep can prepare and generalize a Windows installation for use over multiple devices, customize the default user profile, and use answer files.<br> <br>You should not use Windows PE. Windows PE can create bootable media such as CDs/DVDs/USB/ISO/VHD.<br> <br>You should not use Windows RE. Windows RE creates a recovery environment.<br><br><strong>Reference</strong><br><br><a title="Windows ADK for Windows 10 scenarios for IT Pros" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/windows-adk-scenarios-for-it-pros" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows ADK for Windows 10 scenarios for IT Pros</a><br><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 34),
	(35, NULL, NULL, NULL, 14, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You hire several temporary workers to work on a special project. The temporary workers will bring their own laptop computers. You do not know what operating system is running on the temporary workers\' computers.<br> <br> You need to prepare a bootable USB drive for each temporary worker so they can run Windows from the bootable drive. When their computers are running Windows after booting from the USB drive, temporary workers should not have access to files on the internal hard disks of their computers. You have several Windows 10 images available on your network.<br> <br> Which image should you use to set up the bootable USB drives?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Windows 10 Enterprise .wim file.<br> <br>You need to deploy Windows To Go in your network for the guest workers. Windows To Go is a bootable Windows image installed on a bootable USB drive. Windows To Go provides support for most Windows 10 features, except:<br> <br>* Access to internal disks<br>* Trusted Platform Module (TPM)<br>* Hibernation<br>* Resetting to manufacturer\'s settings<br>* Windows Recovery environment<br>* Upgrading Windows To Go<br> <br>The recommended method for creating a Windows To Go workspace is to use the Windows To Go Creator Wizard. The wizard will prompt you for a Windows 10 image. The image must be a .wim file, which is an installation image that you can create using Sysprep and other tools. The only Windows 10 editions supported are Windows 10 Enterprise and Windows 10 Education.<br> <br>You should not use a Windows 10 Pro .wim. Windows 10 Pro cannot be used with Windows To Go.<br> <br>You should not use an .iso file image. These are installation image files provided by the manufacturer and cannot be used to set up Windows To Go.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Compare Windows 10 Editions" href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/WindowsForBusiness/Compare" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Compare Windows 10 Editions</a><br><a title="Deploy Windows To Go in your organization" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/deploy-windows-to-go" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Deploy Windows To Go in your organization</a><br><a title="Windows To Go: feature overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/planning/windows-to-go-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows To Go: feature overview</a><br><a title="Prepare your organization for Windows To Go" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/planning/prepare-your-organization-for-windows-to-go" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Prepare your organization for Windows To Go</a><br><a title="Deployment considerations for Windows To Go" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/planning/deployment-considerations-for-windows-to-go" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Deployment considerations for Windows To Go</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 35),
	(36, NULL, NULL, NULL, 15, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. Your company is deploying 10 new computers with Windows 10 Enterprise already installed.<br> <br> You need to reconfigure the systems to remove any preinstalled applications and change the manufacturer\'s configuration settings back to their defaults. You want to minimize the effort necessary to accomplish this.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should run a clean install from Windows 10 installation media. This will delete any applications already installed on the computer and run a fresh install. It is sometimes recommended to run a clean installation on new computers, especially when deploying them in a business environment. Preinstalled applications and the manufacturer\'s configuration settings often provide for less than optimal performance.<br> <br> You should not run an in-place upgrade from Windows installation media. This would install Windows 10, but without making any changes.<br> <br> You should not run a computer reset. This would return the computer to the manufacturer\'s default configuration, which is what you are trying to get away from.<br> <br> You should not set up dynamic provisioning. You can use dynamic provisioning to configure new computers, but you would use it to apply the settings needed in your network environment. When used with a service like Microsoft Intune, it can also be used to install applications. However, it does not provide an easy way to identify any default applications and the manufacturer\'s configuration settings.<br> <br> You should not set up Windows Update as a way of preparing the systems. This could be used to keep the computer\'s up-to-date, but not clear out manufacturer\'s settings and applications.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Windows 10 deployment considerations" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/planning/windows-10-deployment-considerations" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 deployment considerations</a> <br><a title="Deploy and update Windows 10" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/index" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Deploy and update Windows 10</a><br><a title="How to do a clean install of Windows 10" href="https://www.cnet.com/how-to/clean-install-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to do a clean install of Windows 10</a><br><a title="Clean Install Windows 10" href="http://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wiki/windows_10-windows_install/clean-install-windows-10/1c426bdf-79b1-4d42-be93-17378d93e587" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Clean Install Windows 10</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 36),
	(37, NULL, NULL, NULL, 16, 3, 0, NULL, '<p>A user has a laptop computer running Microsoft Windows 10 Pro. The user reports issues after a recent automatic update that included device driver updates. The user reports that the built-in graphics card does not work properly since the update. The user reports that the computer worked fine prior to the update.<br> <br>You need to correct the problem with the graphics card.<br> <br>Which three actions should you perform in sequence? To answer, move the appropriate actions from the list of possible actions to the answer area and arrange them in the correct order.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should perform the following actions in order:<br> <br>1. Open Device Manager.<br>2. Right-click and select Properties for the graphics card.<br>3. Choose Roll Back Driver.<br> <br>The correct order and way to roll back a driver is to go to Device Manager because this is the correct management interface to use when troubleshooting driver issues and hardware components. You then right-click the troubled device, and choose Roll Back Driver, which will revert the driver back to a previous version which was working with no issues.<br> <br>Updating the driver will attempt to install a new driver version or reinstall the current drive if a newer driver is not available. This will not correct the problem. Because the current driver was installed with the update, it is probably the most recent driver version.<br> <br>You should not uninstall the driver or disable the graphics card. Either action will cause the graphics hardware to not work.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="How to Roll Back a Driver in Windows " href="https://www.lifewire.com/how-to-roll-back-a-driver-in-windows-2619217" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Roll Back a Driver in Windows</a> <br><br></p></p>', 10, 8, 40),
	(38, NULL, NULL, NULL, 17, 3, 0, NULL, '<p>You install a new graphics card in a computer running Microsoft Windows 10 Pro. You attempt to install the device drivers for the card. You get an error stating that the drivers are unsigned, and that installation is not possible.<br> <br>You need to install the drivers.<br> <br>Which five actions should you perform? To answer, arrange all actions in the correct order.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should perform the steps in the following order:<br> <br>1. Run shutdown.exe /r /o /f /t 00.<br>2. Select Troubleshoot and Advanced Options.<br>3. Select Startup settings and Reboot.<br>4. Press F7 to disable driver signature enforcement.<br>5. Install the unsigned driver using Device Manager.<br> <br>First you need to reboot (/r) the machine and start the PC with the Options menu (/o). The other two switches are forcing the reboot (/f) and specifying the time remaining before the PC reboots (/t 00).<br> <br>Next, you need to navigate to the correct section of the options startup, the Troubleshoot and Advanced Options section.<br> <br>Driver signature checks are made during startup, so you should next select Startup Settings and Reboot.<br> <br>Then you disable the startup check for signed drivers to allow using an unsigned driver.<br> <br>At this point, you are ready to install the device drivers. <br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="how do I disable driver signature enforcement win W10 preview?" href="https://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/insider/forum/insider_wintp-insider_devices/how-do-i-disable-driver-signature-enforcement-win/a53ec7ca-bdd3-4f39-a3af-3bd92336d248?auth=1" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">how do I disable driver signature enforcement win W10 preview?</a><br><br><a title="How to install unsigned drivers in Windows 10" href="http://en.code-bude.net/2015/08/19/how-to-install-unsigned-drivers-in-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to install unsigned drivers in Windows 10</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 41),
	(39, NULL, NULL, NULL, 18, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You upgrade a laptop from Microsoft Windows 7 to Windows 10. During the upgrade, the graphics card does not install properly and several features you use are not available. The driver is not recognized as compatible with Windows 10.<br> <br> You use Windows Update and the manufacturer\'s website to search for updated drivers for the graphics card for Windows 10, but you cannot find any driver available.<br> <br> You need to resolve the issue so that the computer can take the most advantage of the capabilities of the card.<br> <br> What should you do next?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Program Compatibility Troubleshooter to install a Windows 7 driver. If you do not have any updated drivers available, you should use Compatibility Mode to install them. This will make the driver act as if it is installed a compatible system when it is executing by impersonating a Windows 7 session.<br> <br> You should not use Update Device Driver Software in Device Manager. This utility will perform the same checks as Windows Update, so you would not find an applicable driver.<br> <br> You should not use DISM. Using DISM to force the installation will not resolve the compatibility issues.<br> <br> You should not use Microsoft Basic Display Adapter. Even if it does work with the graphics adapter, it will not give you access to any features specific to the graphics card.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How to: Install and Update Hardware Drivers in Windows 10" href="https://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_10-hardware-winpc/how-to-install-and-update-hardware-drivers-in/a97bbbd1-9973-4d66-9a5b-291300006293" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to: Install and Update Hardware Drivers in Windows 10</a><br><a title="Program Compatibility Troubleshooter in Windows 10/8/7" href="https://www.thewindowsclub.com/programs-compatibility-wizard-in-windows-7" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Program Compatibility Troubleshooter in Windows 10/8/7</a><br><a title="How To Use 19 Built-In Troubleshooters Of Windows 10 To Fix Different Problems?" href="https://fossbytes.com/windows-10-troubleshooter-fix-problems/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How To Use 19 Built-In Troubleshooters Of Windows 10 To Fix Different Problems?</a><br><a title="DISM - Deployment Image Servicing and Management" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/manufacture/desktop/dism---deployment-image-servicing-and-management-technical-reference-for-windows" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>DISM - Deployment Image Servicing and Management</a><br><a title="Can the win 10 compatibility troubleshooter fix driver issues?" href="https://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_10-other_settings/can-the-win-10-compatibility-troubleshooter-fix/9d3c44ff-c261-4e40-9ffa-a1ee6c7154fe" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Can the win 10 compatibility troubleshooter fix driver issues?</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 42),
	(40, NULL, NULL, NULL, 19, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are a support technician for your company. You are responsible for network client support, which includes computers running Windows 8.1 and Windows 10.<br> <br>You download a driver package formatted as an .msi file. The driver is for a specialized printer that is physically connected to a client running Windows 10 Pro.<br> <br>You need to apply and test a device driver from that file on the computer hosting the printer.<br> <br>What should you do first?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You need to run the expand command. You need to expand the device driver package to extract the device driver files before they can be installed on the computer. You would use the expand command to extract the device driver files for a driver package formatted as an .msi or .exe file.<br> <br>You should not run the dism command. You could use the dism command to apply a driver to a Windows image file, but you would need to extract the drivers first.<br> <br>You should not launch Windows Explorer. This will not accomplish anything toward your goal. You cannot use Windows Explorer to extract the driver files from an .msi file. You can, however, use Windows Explorer to extract driver files from drivers formatted as a .cab file.<br> <br>You should not launch Device Manager. You can use Device Manager to install and manage device drivers, but you must extract the drivers from the .msi file first.<br><br> <strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How to download updates that include drivers and hotfixes from the Windows Update Catalog" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/323166/how-to-download-updates-that-include-drivers-and-hotfixes-from-the-win" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to download updates that include drivers and hotfixes from the Windows Update Catalog</a><br><a title="Extract and Add Driver Packages" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/dd759151(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Extract and Add Driver Packages</a><br><a title="Inject Drivers to Windows 10 Install Media" href="https://ndswanson.wordpress.com/2014/10/24/inject-drivers-to-windows-10-install-media/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Inject Drivers to Windows 10 Install Media</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 43),
	(41, NULL, NULL, NULL, 20, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are troubleshooting a computer that runs Windows 10. You installed a second video adapter to support a second display and Miracast. You suspect that the adapter might be causing a graphics application to intermittently crash.<br> <br> You need to temporarily disable the video adapter. The adapter should remain disabled if you restart the computer. You do not want to disable any other devices or services.<br> <br> Which utility should you use to disable the adapter?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Device Manager. You can use Device Manager to disable a device by disabling its device driver. This will prevent the device from initializing and prevent Windows from detecting the device as available.<br> <br>You should not use System Configuration. System Configuration lets you manage system startup but does not let you disable individual device drivers.<br> <br>You should not use System Information. System Information lets you view information about system resources and devices but does not let you make any configuration changes.<br> <br>You should not use System Settings. System Settings lets you configure display settings but does not provide a way to disable a video adapter.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How Do I Disable a Device in Device Manager in Windows?" href="https://www.lifewire.com/how-do-i-disable-a-device-in-device-manager-in-windows-2619212" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How Do I Disable a Device in Device Manager in Windows?</a><br><a title="How To Disable A Hardware Device In Windows 10?" href="http://www.ilovefreesoftware.com/21/windows-10/disable-hardware-device-windows-10.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How To Disable A Hardware Device In Windows 10?</a><br><a title="How To Re-install, Roll Back, Update Device Drivers in Windows 10/8/7" href="https://windows101tricks.com/update-device-drivers-in-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How To Re-install, Roll Back, Update Device Drivers in Windows 10/8/7</a><br><a title="How to use Miracast to mirror your device&#39;s screen wirelessly on your TV-even 4K" href="https://www.pcworld.com/article/2907520/streaming-media/how-to-use-miracast-to-mirror-your-devices-screen-wirelessly-on-your-tv.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to use Miracast to mirror your device\'s screen wirelessly on your TV-even 4K</a><br><a title="MSConfig the System Configuration Tool" href="https://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_10-update/msconfig-the-system-configuration-tool/273dea8e-4cbe-47e9-8489-f400e879ce17" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>MSConfig the System Configuration Tool.</a><br><a title="Description of Microsoft System Information (Msinfo32.exe) Tool" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/184075/description-of-microsoft-system-information-msinfo32-exe-tool" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Description of Microsoft System Information (Msinfo32.exe) Tool</a><br><a title="Windows 10 Settings menu: The System tab" href="https://www.cnet.com/how-to/windows-10-settings-menu-the-system-tab/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows 10 Settings menu: The System tab</a><br><a title="How to open and use Windows 10 Settings" href="https://www.thewindowsclub.com/windows-10-settings" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to open and use Windows 10 Settings</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 44),
	(42, NULL, NULL, NULL, 21, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage and maintain client laptops for your company\'s network. All client computers were recently upgraded to Microsoft Windows 10 Pro. Management decides that Cortana should be switched off on all computers.<br> <br> You need to turn off Cortana.<br> <br> Which application will allow you to turn off Cortana?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Notebook. Notebook lets you control Cortana, including the On/Off switch.<br> <br> You should not use the Narrator. This handles the screen reader, which is an accessibility option. <br> <br> You should not use Ease of Access Other Options. Other Options handles animations, Windows background, and Touch feedback.<br> <br> Device Manager handles devices installed on the computer. Cortana is an application, not a device, so Device Manager cannot be used to manage Cortana.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Cortana and privacy" href="https://privacy.microsoft.com/en-US/windows-10-cortana-and-privacy" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Cortana and privacy</a><br><a title="How to troubleshoot issues when you use Cortana with Office 365" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/3086254/how-to-troubleshoot-issues-when-you-use-cortana-with-office-365" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to troubleshoot issues when you use Cortana with Office 365</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 45),
	(43, NULL, NULL, NULL, 22, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the network administrator for a university. All faculty computers run Windows 10 Home or Windows 10 Pro. Students report that Action Center notifications pop up during presentations.<br> <br> You need to disable Action Center on all faculty computers.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should create a batch file that can be run individually on each machine that adds the DisableNotificationCenter D-WORD Value as 1. You would need to distribute the batch file to all faculty members and rely on them to run the batch file. In this case, you should create a batch file that adds the DisableNotificationCenter with the value of 1 to the registry.<br> <br>You should not create a batch file that can be run individually on each machine that adds the DisableNotificationCenter D-WORD Value as 0. This would enable the Action Center.<br> <br>You should not use a GPO. This would require an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain environment, which was not specified as present in the question. Even if an AD DS domain were present, this solution would not work for all faculty computers. The faculty use a mix of Windows 10 Pro and Windows 10 Home. Windows 10 Home computers cannot be managed using GPOs.<br><br><strong>References</strong></p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<p><br><a title="How to Disable the Action Center in Windows 10" href="https://www.howtogeek.com/244539/how-to-disable-the-action-center-in-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Disable the Action Center in Windows 10</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a title="How to disable Action Center Windows 10" href="http://www.windowscentral.com/how-disable-action-center-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to disable Action Center Windows 10</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a title="13 epic registry hacks" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/uktechnet/2016/07/15/13-epic-registry-hacks/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">13 epic registry hacks</a><br> <br> <br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 46),
	(44, NULL, NULL, NULL, 23, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for your company. The company employs several application developers. <br> <br> Developers\' computers run Windows 10 Enterprise. The developers need to create their code using virtual machines running Windows 10 Enterprise.<br> <br> You need to script the deployment of the Hyper-V role to all developer machines.<br> <br> Which two commands can you use for this purpose? Each correct answer presents a complete solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You can use either Enable-WindowsOptionalFeature or Dism.exe. Either can be used to enable Hyper-V support for Windows 10.<br> <br> One way to configure Hyper-V support is to run the following command:<br> <br> Enable-WindowsOptionalFeature -Online -FeatureName Microsoft-Hyper-V -All<br> <br> You can also use DISM by running the following command:<br> <br> Dism.exe /Online /Enable-Feature /All /FeatureName:Microsoft-Hyper-V <br> <br> When using DISM, you should run DISM from a Windows PowerShell session.<br> <br> You should not use the Add-VMHostAssignableDevice PowerShell cmdlet. This cmdlet assigns a device on which the virtual machine host runs.<br> <br> You should not use the Enable-VMConsoleSupport PowerShell cmdlet. This cmdlet enables keyboard, video, and mouse for virtual machines.<br> <br> You should not use the Enable-VMIntegrationService PowerShell cmdlet. This cmdlet enables an integration service on a virtual machine.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Install Hyper-V on Windows 10" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/virtualization/hyper-v-on-windows/quick-start/enable-hyper-v" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Install Hyper-V on Windows 10</a><br><a title="Hyper-V" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/hyper-v/index" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Hyper-V</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 47),
	(45, NULL, NULL, NULL, 24, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage a computer that runs Windows 10 and has Hyper-V enabled.<br> <br> You create two virtual machines (VMs) that can communicate with each other and with the host operating system. The VMs are not able to connect to the Internet.<br> <br> You need to ensure that the VMs can connect to the Internet.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should configure an external network for the virtual switch. This will allow you to pass the host\'s Internet connection through to VMs that use the switch.<br> <br>The host is already configured with an internal virtual switch. This allows the VMs to communicate with each other and the host operating system, but not the external network. You can also configure a private virtual switch that lets VMs communicate with each other, but not the host or external network.<br> <br>You should not configure NUMA Spanning. This setting allows VMs to span non-uniform memory architecture (NUMA). This gives VMs more computing resources, but it does not help with connectivity.<br> <br>You should not configure Enhanced Session Mode. This setting allows redirection of local devices and resources from computers running Virtual Machine Connections, but it does not provide Internet access to VMs.<br> <br>You should not configure the MAC Address Range. This setting defines the MAC address range that can be assigned to VMs, but it does not configure Internet connectivity.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Create a Virtual network" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/virtualization/hyper-v-on-windows/quick-start/connect-to-network" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Create a virtual network</a><br><a title="Create a virtual switch for Hyper-V virtual machines" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/virtualization/hyper-v/get-started/Create-a-virtual-switch-for-Hyper-V-virtual-machines" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Create a virtual switch for Hyper-V virtual machines</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 48),
	(46, NULL, NULL, NULL, 25, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the administrator of your company\'s Windows 10 deployment image.<br> <br> During testing, you find that users do not want Cortana to display news. No external apps have been added to the image.<br> <br> You need to ensure that news is not displayed.<br> <br> What should you configure?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should configure the Notebook for Cortana. The Cortana Notebook allows you to customize the information that is displayed about weather, traffic, travel, news, and sports.<br> <br>You should not configure the Windows Store app. This app does not provide any news and there are no settings to modify. The Windows Store app provides access to applications to install on your Windows device. It is a built-in e-commerce location for applications.<br> <br>You should not configure Cortana settings. This contains general settings, but it does not allow you to customize certain settings needed for the app push.<br> <br>You should not configure the News app. While the News app contains the news, the configuration change needs to be done in the Cortana Notebook.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Killing Cortana: How to disable Windows 10&#39;s info-hungry digital assistant" href="http://www.pcworld.com/article/2949759/windows/killing-cortana-how-to-disable-windows-10s-info-hungry-digital-assistant.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Killing Cortana: How to disable Windows 10\'s info-hungry digital assistant</a><br><a title="The complete guide to configuring Cortana in Windows 10 " href="https://www.digitalcitizen.life/how-configure-cortana-windows-10-pc-notebook-or-tablet" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>The complete guide to configuring Cortana in Windows 10</a> <br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 49),
	(47, NULL, NULL, NULL, 26, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are running Windows 10 on a laptop.<br> <br> You need to modify how hardware behaves when the laptop runs on battery.<br> <br> Which command or Windows PowerShell cmdlet should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the powercfg command. This command allows you to configure and use custom power saving modes. You can also use the Control Panel Power Options utility and Power &amp; Sleep in Windows System settings to manage power plans.<br> <br>You should not use the New-Module PowerShell cmdlet. The New-Module cmdlet creates a new dynamic module based on a script that exists only in memory. It does not provide for power management.<br> <br>You should not use the Set-Service cmdlet. This cmdlet is used to start, stop, or suspend a Windows service or configure service properties.<br> <br>You should not use the Set-ExecutionPolicy cmdlet. You can use the Set-ExecutionPolicy cmdlet to control the level of security surrounding PowerShell scripts.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Powercfg command-line options" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/design/device-experiences/powercfg-command-line-options" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Powercfg command-line options</a><br><a title="New-Module" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.core/new-module" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>New-Module</a><br><a title="Set-Service" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.management/set-service" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Set-Service</a><br><a title="Set-ExecutionPolicy" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh849812.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Set-ExecutionPolicy</a><br><a title="How to Set up Power Plans in Windows 10 – Simple Steps" href="https://www.howto-connect.com/set-up-power-plans-in-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Set up Power Plans in Windows 10 – Simple Steps</a><br><a title="How to manage custom power plans on Windows 10" href="https://www.windowscentral.com/how-manage-custom-power-plans-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to manage custom power plans on Windows 10</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 50),
	(48, NULL, NULL, NULL, 27, 3, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. Most domain clients run Windows 10 Enterprise. The remaining clients run Windows 8.1 but are scheduled for an upgrade to Windows 10.<br> <br> All computers running Windows 10 are placed in the W10 Organizational Unit (OU).<br> <br> All client computers running Windows 10 should have the same custom Start Menu configuration. Domain users should not be able to pin, unpin, or uninstall apps from the Start Menu. <br> <br> You need to apply a custom Start Menu to all clients running Windows 10 and lock the apps. You should keep the administrative effort needed to a minimum.<br> <br> Which four actions should you perform in sequence? To answer, move the appropriate actions from the list of possible actions to the answer area and arrange them in the correct order.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should perform the following actions in order:<br> <br> 1. Customize the Start Menu on one computer.<br> 2. Run the Export-StartLayout cmdlet to export the custom Start Menu.<br> 3. Share the folder containing the custom Start Menu.<br> 4. Create and link a GPO applying the custom Start Menu.<br> <br> You begin by customizing one client computer with the Start Menu configuration you want. You would then run the Export-StartLayout cmdlet to export the Start Menu and Taskbar to an XML file. The Start Menu and Taskbar are exported at the same time, and you cannot export either one by itself. You must share the folder containing the XML file you created to make it available to clients. You would then create and link a GPO that applies the customized Start Menu to the clients running Windows 10. This procedure is supported for Windows 10 Enterprise and Windows 10 Education only.<br> <br> You should not create a .wim file from the customized computer or run an in-place upgrade on each client. There is no need to complete either of these actions. A .wim file is an image made from a configured computer and is used to deploy Windows with the same configuration and settings.<br> <br> You should not configure dynamic provisioning. Dynamic provisioning is used to configure new computers running Windows 10 with settings specific to your network. Dynamic provisioning cannot be used to lock the Start Menu.<br> <br> You should not create a batch file to run the Import-StartLayout cmdlet or run the Import-StartLayout cmdlet on each client. The Import-StartLayout cmdlet can be used to apply the custom Start Menu, but it does not enforce the Start Menu configuration. Users can still pin, unpin, or uninstall apps.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Customize Windows 10 Start and taskbar with Group Policy" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/customize-windows-10-start-screens-by-using-group-policy" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Customize Windows 10 Start and taskbar with Group Policy</a><br><a title="Manage Windows 10 Start and taskbar layout" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/windows-10-start-layout-options-and-policies" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Manage Windows 10 Start and taskbar layout</a><br><a title="Windows 10 Start Layout Customization" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/deploymentguys/2016/03/07/windows-10-start-layout-customization/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows 10 Start Layout Customization</a><br><a title="Customize and export Start layout" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/customize-and-export-start-layout" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Customize and export Start layout</a><br><a title="Windows 10 deployment considerations" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/planning/windows-10-deployment-considerations" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows 10 deployment considerations</a><br><a title="Windows Imaging File Format (WIM)" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-vista/cc749478(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Imaging File Format (WIM)</a></p></p>', 10, 9, 51),
	(49, NULL, NULL, NULL, 28, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. Most domain desktop and laptop client computers run Microsoft Windows 10 and were upgraded from Windows 8 or Windows 8.1 using an in-place upgrade. The remaining clients run Windows 8 and Windows 8.1.<br> <br>Your company\'s domain includes an internal web portal used by employees. The web portal contains ActiveX Controls. Users with computers running Windows 10 report that the web portal is not rendering properly. Users with computers running Windows 8 or Windows 8.1 do not have any problems with how the web portal renders on their computers.<br> <br>You need to resolve the issue as quickly as possible.<br> <br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should create and link a GPO to use IE11 as the default browser. IE11 supports modern web standards, but is also provides backwards compatibility and emulation of earlier IE versions. <br> <br>You should not create and link a GPO to use Microsoft Edge as the default browser. The problem is that Microsoft Edge is already the default browser when you install Windows 10. Microsoft Edge does not support ActiveX controls or other older, less secure technologies.<br> <br>You should not use the Enterprise Mode Site List Manager as your solution because this would be a partial solution only. You can use Enterprise Mode Site List Manager to identify websites that need special handling, such as specifying a compatibility mode or that they must be opened in IE11. However, you also need to configure Microsoft Edge to support Enterprise Mode and use the Enterprise Mode Site List Manager, either through Group Policy or by editing the computer\'s registry to turn on Enterprise Mode.<br><br><strong>Reference<br></strong><br><a title="Interoperability and enterprise mode guidanceility" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/deploy/emie-to-improve-compatibility" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Interoperability and enterprise mode guidance</a><br><a title="Set the default browser using Group Policy" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/internet-explorer/ie11-deploy-guide/set-the-default-browser-using-group-policy" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Set the default browser using Group Policy</a><br><a title="Microsoft Edge Group Policy configuration options" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/deploy/index" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Microsoft Edge Group Policy configuration options</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 52),
	(50, NULL, NULL, NULL, 29, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>A computer named Server1 that runs Windows 10 has Hyper-V enabled and hosts multiple virtual machines (VMs).<br> <br>You need to provide human interface device (keyboard, video and mouse or KVM) support for the VMs. KVM support is currently disabled.<br> <br>Which PowerShell cmdlet should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Enable-VMConsoleSupport PowerShell cmdlet. To enable support for all VMs on the host with one command string, you could run:<br> <br> $VM = Get-VM -ComputerName "Server1"<br> Enable-VMConsoleSupport -VM $VM<br> <br> The first cmdlet retrieves the VMs on Server1 and loads them into the variable $VM. Enable-VMConsoleSupport enables keyboard, video, and mouse for the VMs.<br> <br> You should not use the Enable-VMIntegrationService cmdlet. This is used to enable integration services between the host machine and the VM or VMs and provides data flow between the host and guest services. Supported services include:<br> <br> * Data Exchange Service<br> * Guest Service Interface<br> * Guest Shutdown Service<br> * Heartbeat Service<br> * Remote Desktop Virtualization Service<br> * Time Synchronization Service<br> * Volume Shadow Copy Requestor<br> <br> You should not use the Grant-VMConnectAcess cmdlet. This cmdlet is used to give users access to connect to a VM.<br> <br> You should not use the Import-VM cmdlet. Import-VM is used to provision a VM by importing it from a file.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Enable-VMConsoleSupport" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/hyper-v/enable-vmconsolesupport" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Enable-VMConsoleSupport</a><br><a title="Enable-VMIntegrationService" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/hyper-v/enable-vmintegrationservice" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Enable-VMIntegrationService</a><br><a title="Hyper-V Integration Services - Where Are We Today?" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/askpfeplat/2018/05/21/hyper-v-integration-services-where-are-we-today/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Hyper-V Integration Services - Where Are We Today?</a><br><a title="Grant-VMConnectAccess" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/hyper-v/grant-vmconnectaccess" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Grant-VMConnectAccess</a><br><a title="Import-VM" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/hyper-v/Import-VM" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Import-VM</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 53),
	(51, NULL, NULL, NULL, 30, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You are a new administrator in your organization. The former administrator created multiple deployment images and provisioning packages using Windows Configuration Designer.<br> <br> You need to locate the files to ensure you can continue to support deployment.<br> <br> Which two types of files should you locate? Each correct answer presents part of the solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use a .wim file. Windows Configuration Designer requires a .wim file from the Windows DVD for Windows 10 deployments. The output file for configuration customizations are in .xml format, so these files are also required.<br> <br>The .iso file is the full DVD image for the operating system. It is not used with Windows Configuration Designer to create a deployment file.<br> <br>Customization files for Windows Configuration Designer cannot be in an .exe or .inf file format. .exe files are executable files. .inf files provide information for driver installation.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Windows Configuration Designer command-line interface (reference)" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-command-line" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Configuration Designer command-line interface (reference)</a><br><br><a title="Install Windows Configuration Designer" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-install-icd" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Install Windows Configuration Designer</a><br><br><a title="Create a provisioning package for Windows 10" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-create-package" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Create a provisioning package for Windows 10</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 54),
	(52, NULL, NULL, NULL, 31, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You plan on creating Windows 10 deployment images and provisioning packages using Windows Configuration Designer.<br> <br>You need to install Windows Configuration Designer.<br> <br>What should you download and install first?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should download and install the Windows 10 Assessment and Deployment Kit (ADK). It contains the Windows Configuration Designer for Windows 10, along with the other supporting tools for Windows Configuration Designer.<br> <br>You should not use the OPK or the Windows Essentials OPK. OPK is used with Windows 7 and Windows 8 and does not support Windows 10. <br> <br>The Microsoft Deployment Toolkit is intended for enterprise environments, and contains tools supporting those environments. It does not include support for Windows Configuration Designer.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Install Windows Configuration Designer" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-install-icd" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Install Windows Configuration Designer</a><br><a title="Deploy Windows 10 with the Microsoft Deployment Toolkit" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/deploy-windows-mdt/deploy-windows-10-with-the-microsoft-deployment-toolkit" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Deploy Windows 10 with the Microsoft Deployment Toolkit</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 55),
	(53, NULL, NULL, NULL, 32, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You deploy Windows 10 on several new computers for your company. The deployments were designed to install, configure, and activate Windows 10 automatically. You use volume key activation for all deployments.<br> <br> You need to create a script to verify the activation status of all computers. You only want to retrieve activation status information.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the slmgr.vbs script with the /dli parameter set. This will display license information. By default, /dli displays the license information for the installed active Windows edition.<br> <br>You should not use the slmgr.vbs script with the /ato parameter. This option is used with retail editions and volume systems with a KMS host key or a Multiple Activation Key (MAK) installed. The /ato parameter prompts Windows to attempt online activation.<br> <br>You should not use sfc.exe for this purpose. The sfc.exe utility with the /verifyonly switch scans the file system in Windows and verifies system files, not licenses. The /scanonce switch for the same tool is for Windows Server 2003 and Windows XP, and only scans the protected files in the system to look for errors.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License" href="https://www.howtogeek.com/245445/how-to-use-slmgr-to-change-remove-or-extend-your-windows-license/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License</a><br><a title="System File Checker" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/Wfp/system-file-checker" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>System File Checker</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 56),
	(54, NULL, NULL, NULL, 33, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are responsible for the deployment of Windows 10. The company has a volume license agreement with a KMS host key.<br> <br> You need to create a script using slmgr.vbs to activate all machines. You need to identify the appropriate option to use with the script to accomplish this.<br> <br> Which option should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the slmgr.vbs script with the /ato option. This is designed for retail editions and volume systems with a KMS host key or a Multiple Activation Key (MAK) installed. The /ato parameter prompts Windows to attempt online activation.<br> <br>You should not use the /dlv option. This option displays detailed license information. By default, /dlv displays the detailed license information for the installed active Windows edition.<br> <br>You should not use the /dti option. This option displays the installation ID for offline activation.<br> <br>You should not use the /xpr option. This option displays activation expiration dates.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License" href="https://www.howtogeek.com/245445/how-to-use-slmgr-to-change-remove-or-extend-your-windows-license/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Use Slmgr to Change, Remove, or Extend Your Windows License</a><br><a title="System File Checker" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/Wfp/system-file-checker" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>System File Checker</a><br><a title="Tools to manage Office 2013 volume activation" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/office/office-2013-resource-kit/ee624350(v=office.15)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Tools to manage Office 2013 volume activation</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 57),
	(55, NULL, NULL, NULL, 34, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You work for a system builder.<br> <br> You need to create a Windows 10 provisioning package that can apply third-party drivers needed by a specific hardware configuration without having to create a new image file.<br> <br> Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Windows Configuration Designer to create your provisioning package. Windows Configuration Designer is primarily designed for use by OEMs, ODMs, and system makers looking for a simple and streamlined process for automating applying configuration settings to Windows 10 devices.<br> <br>You should not use the Microsoft Deployment Toolkit (MDT). The MDT is a unified collection of tools, processes, and guidance for automating desktop and server deployment. MDT enables you to more easily manage security and ongoing configurations, but it does not provide the functionality needed by the scenario.<br> <br>You should not use the Deployment Image Servicing and Management (DISM) tool. The DISM tool is a command-line tool that is used to manage Windows image files.<br> <br>You should not use the Windows Automated Installation Toolkit (AIK). The Windows AIK is a collection of tools and documentation that is designed to help IT Professionals deploy Windows 7. Starting with Windows 8, AIK was replaced with Windows Assessment and Deployment Kit (ADK).<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Install Windows Configuration Designer" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-install-icd" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Install Windows Configuration Designer</a><br><a title="Create a provisioning package for Windows 10" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-create-package" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Create a provisioning package for Windows 10</a><br><a title="Deploy Windows 10 with the Microsoft Deployment Toolkit" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/deploy-windows-mdt/deploy-windows-10-with-the-microsoft-deployment-toolkit?ocid=tia-257833000" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Deploy Windows 10 with the Microsoft Deployment Toolkit</a><br><a title="Key features in MDT" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/deploy-windows-mdt/key-features-in-mdt" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Key features in MDT</a><br><a title="DISM Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/manufacture/desktop/what-is-dism" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>DISM Overview</a><br><a title="Windows Automated Installation Kit for Windows 7" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dd349343(v=ws.10).aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Automated Installation Kit for Windows 7</a><br><a title="How provisioning works in Windows 10" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-how-it-works" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How provisioning works in Windows 10</a><br><a title="Windows 10 deployment scenarios and tools" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/windows-deployment-scenarios-and-tools" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows 10 deployment scenarios and tools</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 58),
	(56, NULL, NULL, NULL, 35, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as a single Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. The network includes multiple geographic locations that all link to the main office through always-available site-to-site virtual private network (VPN) links.<br> <br>You are responsible for the deployment of 40 new computers. The computers were installed as bare metal machines and are being deployed throughout the domain as domain clients running Windows 10.<br> <br>You need to configure automatic activation for the new domain clients. You want to minimize the effort necessary to set up Windows 10 volume activation. The computers should be required to reactivate every 180 days.<br> <br>What type of activation should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Key Management Service (KMS) activation. KMS activation provides for automatic activation and requires computers to reactivate every 180 days. This is an appropriate solution because you can configure a KMS host in the main office that can be used to activate remote clients. KMS activation for Windows 10 requires at least 25 Windows 10 clients. A single KMS host can support an unlimited number of clients. The host registers itself with the DNS domain to which the host belongs automatically when you set it up.<br> <br>You should not use Active Directory activation. This is also an automatic activation method, but it is a persistent activation so clients are not required to reactivate.<br> <br>You should not use Multiple Activation Key (MAK). MAK is designed for volume activation when the number of computers does not meet the minimum requirement for KMS. MAK is a manual activation method for persistent activation.<br> <br>You should not use original equipment manufacturers (OEM) activation. This is limited to computers purchased through an OEM channel with Windows 10 already installed.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Activate using Key Management Service" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/volume-activation/activate-using-key-management-service-vamt" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Activate using Key Management Service</a><br><a title="Activate using Active Directory-based activation" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/volume-activation/activate-using-active-directory-based-activation-client" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Activate using Active Directory-based activation</a><br><a title="Understanding KMS" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/tn-archive/ff793434(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Understanding KMS</a><br><a title="Getting Started with KMS (Key Management Service)" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/26939.getting-started-with-kms-key-management-service.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Getting Started with KMS (Key Management Service)</a><br><a title="Deploying KMS Activation" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ff793409.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Deploying KMS Activation</a><br><a title="Plan for volume activation" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/volume-activation/plan-for-volume-activation-client" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Plan for volume activation</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 59),
	(57, NULL, NULL, NULL, 36, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You need to configure your network to support Key Management Service (KMS) activation for computers that run Windows 10.<br> <br>You use slmgr.vbs /ipk to install a KMS host key on a computer named Client1. You need to finish setting up for automatic KMS activation.<br> <br>What should you do next?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use slmgr.vbs /ato to activate Client1 online after you install the KMS host key. Optionally, you can activate by telephone. Client1 will be able to activate clients running volume license copies of Windows 10. KMS activation requires at least 25 computers running Windows 10.<br> <br> You should not install the Volume Activation Services server role on a domain controller running Windows Server 2012 R2 or later. This is used for Active Directory activation, not KMS activation.<br> <br> You should not install a MAK on Client1. A MAK is used with MAK activation, which is a manual option for activation. It is recommended in volume license scenarios when you have only a small number of computers or when KMS cannot be used.<br> <br> You should not add an SRV DNS resource record for Client1. This is done for you automatically when you install the KMS host key.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Activate using Key Management Service" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/volume-activation/activate-using-key-management-service-vamt" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Activate using Key Management Service</a><br><a title="Activate using Active Directory-based activation" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/volume-activation/activate-using-active-directory-based-activation-client" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Activate using Active Directory-based activation</a><br><a title="Understanding KMS" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/tn-archive/ff793434(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Understanding KMS</a><br><a title="Getting Started with KMS (Key Management Service)" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/26939.getting-started-with-kms-key-management-service.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Getting Started with KMS (Key Management Service)</a><br><a title="Deploying KMS Activation" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ff793409.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Deploying KMS Activation</a><br><a title="Plan for volume activation" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/volume-activation/plan-for-volume-activation-client" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Plan for volume activation</a><br><a title="Managing Activation Using the Volume Activation Management Tool (VAMT)" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/tn-archive/ff686876(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Managing Activation Using the Volume Activation Management Tool (VAMT)</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 60),
	(58, NULL, NULL, NULL, 37, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. Your network uses both wired and wireless communication connections. All network client computers run Windows 10. Several are portable devices.<br> <br> You learn from user comments that portable devices are connecting automatically to Wi-Fi hotspots, including spots outside of your company campus.<br> <br> You need to configure the devices so that they do not try to connect automatically.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>The problem is that Wi-Fi Sense is enabled on the devices, which enables the devices to connect to Wi-Fi hot spots automatically. This is a potential risk, especially when connecting to public hot spots. Because the computers are domain members, you can create a GPO that disables Wi-Fi Sense for the devices. This is configured through the Computer Configuration\\Administrative Templates\\Network\\WLAN Service\\WLAN Settings\\Allow Windows to automatically connect to suggested open hotspots, to networks shared by contacts, and to hotspots offering paid services setting.<br> <br>You should not create a script to add a registry key with a value of 1 for AutoConnectAllowedOEM to disable Wi-Fi Sense. This registry setting has been deprecated for current Windows 10 versions and is no longer supported, so it would have no effect. This would enable Wi-Fi Sense on any computer running an older version of Windows that ran the script.<br> <br>You should not disable Network Discovery. Network Discovery enables a computer to gather information about devices on your network. It is not involved with sensing or connecting to Wi-Fi hot spots.<br> <br>You should not use the netsh interface teredo set state disabled command. This command would be used to disable Teredo, which is an IPv6 over IPv4 tunneling protocol.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Manage connections from Windows operating system components to Microsoft services" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/privacy/manage-connections-from-windows-operating-system-components-to-microsoft-services" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Manage connections from Windows operating system components to Microsoft services</a><br><br><a title="Netsh Commands for Interface (IPv4 and IPv6)" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc770948(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Netsh Commands for Interface (IPv4 and IPv6)</a><br><a title="Manage Wi-Fi Sense in your company" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/manage-wifi-sense-in-enterprise" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Manage Wi-Fi Sense in your company</a><br><a title="How to Enable Network Discovery via Group Policy?" href="http://www.technig.com/enable-network-discovery-via-group-policy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Enable Network Discovery via Group Policy?</a><br><a title="How to configure Wi-Fi Sense and Paid Wi-Fi Services on Windows 10 in an enterprise" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/3085719/how-to-configure-wi-fi-sense-and-paid-wi-fi-services-on-windows-10-in" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to configure Wi-Fi Sense and Paid Wi-Fi Services on Windows 10 in an enterprise</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 62),
	(59, NULL, NULL, NULL, 38, 3, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. A computer running Microsoft Windows Server 2016 is deployed on your company\'s perimeter network. You configure the computer as a DirectAccess server to support remote users who work from home. You used the DirectAccess Getting Started Wizard to configure the DirectAccess server.<br> <br>Remote user computers run Windows 10 Enterprise. The computers are not configured as domain members. The users need to be able to connect through DirectAccess using domain authentication credentials.<br> <br>You create machine objects for the remote computers and add them to the domain DirectAccessClients security group.<br> <br>You need to configure each remote user computer to support access to domain resources through DirectAccess.<br> <br>Which five actions should you perform in sequence? To answer, move the appropriate actions from the list of possible actions to the answer area and arrange them in the correct order.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You need to perform an offline domain join for each of the remote computers that will be accessing domain resources through DirectAccess. DirectAccess is limited to domain member computers only. For each remote computer, you should perform the following steps in order:<br> <br>1. Create a provisioning package from a computer joined to the domain.<br>2. Securely transfer the provisioning package to the remote computer.<br>3. Apply the provisioning package on the remote computer.<br>4. Join the remote computer to the domain.<br>5. Reboot the remote computer.<br> <br>This process lets you join a computer to the domain even though it is not connected to or communicating with the company network.<br> <br>You start by running the djoin command from a domain member computer running Windows Server 2016, Windows Server 2012, Windows Server 2012 R2, Windows 10, Windows 8.1, Windows 8. You then need to use a secure method to transfer the provisioning package created by this process to the remote computer. At the remote computer, you would run djoin to apply the provisioning package and join the domain. You would then have to reboot the remote computer to complete the join process and connect to DirectAccess.<br> <br>You cannot create the provisioning package from a computer running Windows 10, but the package you create can be applied to a computer running Windows 10. DirectAccess supports Windows 10 Enterprise and Education only.<br> <br>You should not add the remote user accounts to the DirectAccessClients group. Access is configured through the computer account, not the user account.<br> <br>You should not create and configure a VPN on the DirectAccess server. A VPN is not required when using DirectAccess. DirectAccess provides a connection and communication alternative to using a VPN.<br> <br>You should not create and link a GPO to the DirectAccessClients group. A GPO cannot be applied to a computer that is not a domain member.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="DirectAccess" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/remote/remote-access/directaccess/DirectAccess" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">DirectAccess</a><br><a title="Prerequisites for Deploying DirectAccess" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/remote/remote-access/directaccess/Prerequisites-for-Deploying-DirectAccess" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Prerequisites for Deploying DirectAccess</a><br><a title="DirectAccess Unsupported Configurations" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/remote/remote-access/directaccess/DirectAccess-Unsupported-Configurations" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>DirectAccess Unsupported Configurations</a><br><a title="DirectAccess Offline Domain Join" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/remote/remote-access/directaccess/DirectAccess-Offline-Domain-Join" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>DirectAccess Offline Domain Join</a><br><a title="Compare Windows 10 editions" href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/WindowsForBusiness/Compare" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Compare Windows 10 editions</a><br><br><a title="DirectAccess and VPNs Working Together" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-7/dd875517(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">DirectAccess and VPNs Working Together</a><br><a title="DirectAccess Benefits" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-7/dd875522(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>DirectAccess Benefits</a><strong><br></strong></p></p>', 10, 8, 63),
	(60, NULL, NULL, NULL, 39, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the administrator for a small Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All client computers run Windows 8.1 or Windows 10. Client computer accounts are kept in an Organizational Unit (OU) named DClient. Some users have mobile computers and occasionally work outside of the office.<br> <br>You need to configure the mobile computers so that the mobile users cannot manually select the Work or Home private network types. Users need to be limited to the automatic Public and Domain settings only. <br> <br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should edit the registry on each user\'s computer. You need to turn off the computer\'s Network Location wizard to prevent users from being able to choose Home or Work network types. The computer will still configure itself for the Domain (if logged onto a domain) or Public (if not logged onto a domain) types automatically.<br> <br> To turn the Network Location wizard off for all users, add the following key and set its value to 0:<br> <br> HKLM\\System\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Network\\NewNetworkWindowOff<br> <br> To turn the Network Location wizard off for the current user only, add the following key and set its value to 0:<br> <br> HKCU\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\CurrentVersion\\Network\\NwCategoryWizard\\Show<br> <br> You should not and link a GPO to the DClient OU. You cannot disable this functionality through Group Policy.<br> <br> You should not modify the Control Panel Network and Sharing Center properties. Network and Sharing Center gives you access to Network Locations to set the location type, but it does not have an option for disabling the Network Location wizard.<br> <br> You should not run the Netsh command. Netsh provides extensive commands for network management but does not include a command for disabling the Network Location wizard.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Turn off the Network Location wizard" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/gg252535(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Turn off the Network Location wizard</a><br><a title="Network Location Types" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc725993(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Network Location Types</a><br><a title="Network Location Awareness" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc753545(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Network Location Awareness</a><br><a title="Netsh Command Reference" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc754516(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Netsh Command Reference</a><br><br> </p></p>', 10, 4, 65),
	(61, NULL, NULL, NULL, 40, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You are a network administrator for your company. The network includes multiple geographic locations. You are configuring a virtual private network (VPN) endpoint at one of the remote locations. The VPN must meet the following requirements:<br> <br> * IPSec encryption between the remote client and VPN server<br> * Support for clients not joined to a domain<br> * Certificate-based authentication<br> <br> You are deploying the VPN server on the perimeter network in front of the firewall.<br> <br> You need to identify the inbound and outbound ports that must be open on the VPN server.<br> <br> Which three ports do you need to open? Each correct answer presents part of the solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You need to open UDP ports 500, 1701, and 4500 on the VPN server. You need to use the L2TP tunneling protocol with IPSec to meet the scenario requirements. These are the ports needed to support this configuration:<br> <br> * UDP port 500 allows IKE traffic with the VPN server.<br> * UDP port 1701 allows L2TP traffic between the client and server (both ways).<br> * UDP port 4500 allows IPsec NAT-T traffic.<br> <br> If you were deploying the VPN server behind the firewall, you would need to open UDP ports 500 and 4500 and configure protocol ID 50. The protocol ID is used in the IP packet header to identify the protocol. Protocol ID 50 identifies IPsec.<br> <br> You do not need to open TCP port 443. This is the port that must be open when using the SSTP tunneling protocol. This port must be opened on the VPN server when it is deployed in front of a firewall and on the firewall when the VPN server is deployed behind a firewall.<br> <br> You would open TCP port 1723 if you are using the PPTP tunneling protocol, whether deploying in front of or behind a firewall. You would also have to configure protocol ID 47. Protocol ID 47 is for General Routing Encapsulation (PPTP data over GRE).<br> <br> You do not need to open TCP port 23. This port is used to support Telnet.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Configure L2TP/IPsec-based Remote Access" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ff687761(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Configure L2TP/IPsec-based Remote Access</a><br><a title="L2TP over IPSec VPNs" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/cc977622(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>L2TP over IPSec VPNs</a><br><a title="Appendix B: VPN Servers and Firewall Configuration" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ff687795(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Appendix B: VPN Servers and Firewall Configuration</a><br><a title="Appendix A: Computer Certificates for VPN Connections" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ff687750(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Appendix A: Computer Certificates for VPN Connections</a><br><a title="Appendix C: VPN Tunneling Protocols" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ff687723(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Appendix C: VPN Tunneling Protocols</a><br><a title="Port Assignments for Well-Known Ports" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/cc959828(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Port Assignments for Well-Known Ports</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 6, 66),
	(62, NULL, NULL, NULL, 41, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You have a computer running Windows 7 Professional SP1 32-bit on a 64-bit platform.<br> <br> You need to deploy Windows 10 Pro 64-bit on the computer. You need to minimize the changes to the computer, installed applications, and data.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should reinstall the machine with Windows 10 Pro 64-bit. There is no in-place upgrade option between 32-bit and 64-bit versions of Windows. Only a clean installation will work. You should back up all user data before running the upgrade.<br> <br> You cannot perform an in-place upgrade from a 32-bit version of Windows 7 to any edition of 64-bit Windows 10 irrespective of which version you choose. <br> <br> An in-place upgrade from 32-bit Windows 7 to 64-bit Windows 7 is not supported.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Windows 10 upgrade paths" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/windows-10-upgrade-paths" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 upgrade paths</a><br><br><a title="Windows 10 Specifications &amp; Systems Requirements" href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/windows-10-specifications" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 Specifications &amp; Systems Requirements</a><br><br><a title="Windows 10 edition upgrade" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/windows-10-edition-upgrades" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 edition upgrade</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 67),
	(63, NULL, NULL, NULL, 42, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Employees use mobile devices for off-site data collection. Data is transferred to PCs when the employees are in the office.<br> <br>You need to provide a solution for wireless data transfer between the mobile devices and PCs. The solution must provide as much bandwidth as possible through a point-to-point connection.<br> <br>Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Wi-Fi Direct. This requires a compatible wireless adapter in the PC. The mobile device is added as a new peripheral device to initiate the connection.<br> <br> You should not use Bluetooth or ad hoc networking. Both are wireless communication methods, but neither offers a bandwidth as high as Wi-Fi Direct. Bluetooth provides for a point-to-point connection between peripherals and computers or mobile devices. Ad hoc networking is a multipoint peer-to-peer networking configuration and has the lowest bandwidth.<br> <br> You should not use Direct Access. Direct Access is not a wireless communication method. Direct Access is a remote access method that is used to give remote users access to internal network resources.<br> <br> You should not use cell tethering. Cell tethering lets you configure a cell phone as a mobile hot spot. This does not provide the communication capabilities required by the scenario.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How to setup wifi direct settings and connect devices with windows 10 laptop and other mobile phones." href="https://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_10-other_settings/how-to-setup-wifi-direct-settings-and-connect/c214c04c-8f29-4eed-9d94-b187713bdf44?auth=1" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to setup wifi direct settings and connect devices with windows 10 laptop and other mobile phones.</a><br><br><a title="WiFi Direct: Windows Wireless File Transfer That&#39;s Faster Than Bluetooth" href="https://www.makeuseof.com/tag/wifi-direct-vs-bluetooth-use-sharing-data-windows-8/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">WiFi Direct: Windows Wireless File Transfer That\'s Faster Than Bluetooth</a><br><br><a title="Using WiFi Direct on your Windows 10 IoT Core device" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/iot-core/connect-your-device/setupwifidirect" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Using WiFi Direct on your Windows 10 IoT Core device</a><br><br><a title="Simple Questions: What Is WiFi Direct? How Does It Work?" href="https://www.digitalcitizen.life/simple-questions-what-wifi-direct-how-does-it-work" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Simple Questions: What Is WiFi Direct? How Does It Work?</a><br><br><a title="Wi-Fi Direct" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wi-Fi_Direct" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Wi-Fi Direct</a><br><br><a title="DirectAccess" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/mt421256.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">DirectAccess</a><br><br><a title="What Is Tethering a Cell Phone?" href="https://www.lifewire.com/what-is-tethering-2377921" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">What Is Tethering a Cell Phone?</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 68),
	(64, NULL, NULL, NULL, 43, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are asked to configure all remote clients with LockDown virtual private network (VPN) profiles for added network security.<br> <br>You need to determine technical requirements for implementing LockDown VPN.<br> <br>Which VPN connection type should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use IKEv2. This is the only connection type that meets the requirements to LockDown VPN. One of the key features required for support is the ability to automatically reestablish a network connection after a connection is lost or a computer moves between networks.<br> <br> LockDown VPN features include:<br> <br> * The computer attempts to maintain its VPN connection at all times.<br> * Users cannot disconnect the VPN connection or delete or modify the VPN profile.<br> * A computer is limited to one VPN LockDown profile.<br> * Outbound network traffic is blocked if the VPN connection is not available.<br> <br> You should not use PPTP, L2TP, or SSTP. These protocols are not supported for LockDown VPN. PPTP is considered to be essentially obsolete because of inherent security shortcomings and has been generally replaced by L2TP. L2TP is the most commonly used protocol for VPN connections over the Internet, but it requires the use of an additional security protocol, such as IPSec, to provide packet encryption. SSTP is designed to support a VPN connection over an SSL/TLS channel.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="VPN connection types" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/identity-protection/vpn/vpn-connection-type" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">VPN connection types</a><br><br><a title="VPN security features" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/identity-protection/vpn/vpn-security-features" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">VPN security features</a><br><br><a title="Step 6. Configure Windows 10 client Always On VPN connections" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/remote/remote-access/vpn/always-on-vpn/deploy/vpn-deploy-client-vpn-connections" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Step 6. Configure Windows 10 client Always On VPN connections</a><br><br><a title="Configure IKEv2-based Remote Access" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ff687731(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Configure IKEv2-based Remote Access</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 69),
	(65, NULL, NULL, NULL, 44, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>A customer purchases a new computer with Windows 10 Pro already installed. The computer has one hard disk dedicated to the operating system and applications.<br> <br> The customer will be using the computer primarily for video editing and production. You install four additional hard disks for data storage.<br> <br> The user needs to optimize disk performance and provide for data protection in case of a disk failure.<br> <br> Which storage solution should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use a two-way mirror space. This provides for optimizing performance and provides for protection in case of a disk failure. Two-way mirror space uses pairs of drives, both with the same data, and protects against loss of one hard disk. In this scenario you could create two mirrored pairs.<br><br>You should not use a simple space. Simple spaces are designed for increased performance but do not provide data protection in case of failure. They are intended for temporary data such as video rendering files. Simple spaces require at least two drives. Performance enhancements come from striping data across the hard disks with better performance as you increase the number of drives.<br> <br>You should not use a three-way mirror space. Mirror spaces are designed for increased performance and drive failure, but a three-way mirror space requires at least five data drives. A three-way mirror space protects against the failure of two hard disks.<br> <br>You should not use a parity space. They are designed for storage efficiency and protection from drive failure, but they do not provide for optimum performance compared to disk mirroring. Parity space requires at least three physical disks drives and stripes data any parity information across the drives. The parity space allows for data recovery if one physical drive is lost. Protection against the loss of two hard disks requires at least seven physical disks.<br> <br>You should not use OneDrive for Business. This is an online storage solution, which would not provide performance levels as good as a mirror space.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12438/windows-10-storage-spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br><a title="Storage Spaces - Designing for Performance" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/15200.storage-spaces-designing-for-performance.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Storage Spaces - Designing for Performance</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 72),
	(66, NULL, NULL, NULL, 45, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are reconfiguring storage on a computer running Windows 10. <br> <br> You need to add an existing disk that is already installed in the computer to an existing storage pool.<br> <br> Which Windows utility or Windows PowerShell cmdlet should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Add-PhysicalDisk cmdlet. The Add-PhysicalDisk cmdlet lets you add a physical disk to the specified storage pool. You must specify the storage pool and the physical disk you want to add.<br> <br> You should not use the Update-Disk cmdlet. This cmdlet is used to update cached information about a disk object. It is not used to manage or update a storage pool or its content.<br> <br> You should not use the Set-StoragePool cmdlet. The Set-StoragePool cmdlet modifies the properties of a specified storage pool, but not the disks assigned to the storage pool.<br> <br> You should not use the Set-StorageTier cmdlet. This cmdlet is used to increase the size of a storage tier created from a storage pool. It does not let you modify the storage pool.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Add-PhysicalDisk" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/storage/add-physicaldisk" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Add-PhysicalDisk</a><br><a title="Storage" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/storage" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Storage</a><br><a title="Set-StoragePool" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/storage/set-storagepool" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Set-StoragePool</a><br><a title="Update-Disk" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/storage/update-disk" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Update-Disk</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 73),
	(67, NULL, NULL, NULL, 46, 3, 0, NULL, '<p>You provide hardware and software support for your company. A computer running Windows 10 uses Storage Spaces with multiple hard disks configured as a storage pool. One of the drives is at risk of failing, and you need to remove it from the pool. Data in the pool must be protected from loss.<br> <br> You need to safely remove a drive from the existing storage pool.<br> <br> Which three actions should you perform in sequence? To answer, move the appropriate actions from the list of possible actions to the answer area and arrange them in the correct order.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should perform the following actions in order:<br> <br>1. View all physical drives in Storage Spaces.<br>2. Select the failing drive and choose Prepare for removal.<br>3. Select Remove drive when the drive is listed as ready.<br> <br>You need to view the physical drives to see the failing drive so that it can be prepared and removed. Choose Change Settings and then Physical Drives to view the drives in the storage pool. You choose Prepare for removal to reconfigure the storage pool and help protect against data loss. Leave the PC on until the drive is ready to be removed to minimize the risk of data loss. This process can take several hours. Once the drive is ready to be removed, you can select Remove drive and then physically remove the hard disk.<br> <br>You should not eject the drive or delete the volume. These steps would remove a physical disk from Windows and risk data corruption because data is not moved to another location in the existing storage space.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="http://windows.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-10/storage-spaces-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br><a title="Storage Spaces Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)" href="http://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/11382.storage-spaces-frequently-asked-questions-faq.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Storage Spaces Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</a></p>', 10, 6, 74),
	(68, NULL, NULL, NULL, 47, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You have a 64-bit computer running Windows 7 Professional SP1 (32-bit).<br> <br> You need to perform an in-place upgrade to upgrade the computer to Windows 10. You want to maintain personal data, settings, and applications.<br> <br> Which two versions are available? Each correct answer presents a complete solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>Only the Windows 10 Professional or Enterprise 32-bit versions will be available. You can upgrade the operating system to either Professional or Enterprise, but you must keep the same processor platform version. Therefore, you cannot perform an in-place upgrade to any 64-bit version of Windows. Upgrades to Windows 10 Professional Education and Windows 10 Education are also supported.<br> <br>Windows 10 Home (32-bit) is a downgrade, not an upgrade. Personal data is maintained, but settings and applications are lost.<br> <br>Windows 10 Professional (64-bit) and Windows 10 Enterprise (64-bit) are not available. You cannot switch processor platform version during an upgrade.<br> <br>Windows 10 Home (64-bit) is also not available/ You cannot perform an in-place upgrade to a lower edition of Windows 10, and you cannot switch processor platform version during an upgrade.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Windows 10 upgrade paths" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/windows-10-upgrade-paths" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 upgrade paths</a></p></p>', 10, 6, 75),
	(69, NULL, NULL, NULL, 48, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You attach three USB 3.0 external hard disks to a computer that runs Windows 10 and create a storage pool from the disks.<br> <br> You need to make storage space from the storage pool available for use. You run the New-VirtualDisk PowerShell cmdlet to create a thin provisioned virtual disk from the pool.<br> <br> Which cmdlet you should run next?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should run the Initialize-Disk cmdlet next. This cmdlet initializes a RAW partition style as an MBR or GPT partition, defaulting to a GPT partition. The partition must be initialized before it can be used for data storage.<br> <br> After running New-VirtualDisk, you would run the following cmdlets in order:<br> <br> 1. Initialize-Disk<br> 2. New-Partition<br> 3. Format-Volume<br> <br> You would not use the Set-VirtualDisk cmdlet as part of this process. This cmdlet is used to manage virtual disk attributes, such as the disk friendly name.<br> <br> You should not use Register-StorageSubsystem as part of the process. This cmdlet is used to connect a storage subsystem to a remote computer or cluster.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12438/windows-10-storage-spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br><a title="How to set up Storage Spaces in Windows 10" href="https://www.techrepublic.com/article/how-to-set-up-storage-spaces-in-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to set up Storage Spaces in Windows 10</a><br><a title="PowerShell tutorial: Managing Windows Storage Spaces" href="https://searchstorage.techtarget.com/tip/PowerShell-tutorial-Managing-Windows-Storage-Spaces" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>PowerShell tutorial: Managing Windows Storage Spaces</a><br><a title="New-StoragePool" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/storage/new-storagepool" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>New-StoragePool</a><br><a title="New-VirtualDisk" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/storage/new-virtualdisk" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>New-VirtualDisk</a><br><a title="Initialize-Disk" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/storage/initialize-disk" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Initialize-Disk</a><br><a title="Set-VirtualDisk" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/storage/set-virtualdisk" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Set-VirtualDisk</a><br><a title="Register-StorageSubsystem" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/storage/register-storagesubsystem" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Register-StorageSubsystem</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 76),
	(70, NULL, NULL, NULL, 49, 3, 0, NULL, '<p>You have a wireless home network configured as a workgroup. Your network includes two desktop computers and two laptop computers. All computers run Windows 10 under the Standard User context. You use a Microsoft account to log in to all machines. <br> <br> One of the desktop computers has a printer attached via a USB connection.<br> <br> You need to share the printer with the rest of the networked computers.<br> <br> Which three actions should you perform in sequence? To answer, move the appropriate actions from the list of possible actions to the answer area and arrange them in the correct order.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should perform the following actions in order:<br> <br>1. Right-click the printer and choose Printer Properties.<br>2. Select Change Sharing Options on the Sharing tab.<br>3. Check the Share this printer checkbox.<br> <br>After opening Printer Properties, select the Sharing tab. Enable sharing by selecting Change Sharing Options and then checking the Share this printer checkbox.<br> <br>You should not use the Troubleshoot menu. The Troubleshoot menu of the printer does not include options for configuring printer sharing.<br> <br>You do not need to set the printer as the default printer. Setting the printer as the default printer does not share it but instead makes the printer the default print destination unless overridden. If it is the only printer installed on the computer, it is likely already configured as the default printer for that computer.<br> <br>You do not need to modify the security settings for the printer to share the printer. You would do this if you wanted to change security settings, such as the spool settings.<br> <br>You do not need to change the settings in the Advanced tab. Specifying to start printing after the last page is spooled prevents a print job from printing until the entire job is loaded in the spooler. This can impact printer performance because of the delay to start printing but is not related to printer sharing.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="How to share a printer on Windows 10 without homegroups?" href="http://superuser.com/questions/958247/how-to-share-a-printer-on-windows-10-without-homegroups" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to share a printer on Windows 10 without homegroups?</a><br><a title="Add shared printers to the network" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-essentials-sbs/cc546031(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Add shared printers to the network</a><br><a title="Print Devices, Print Clients, Printers, and Print Servers" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/cc976770(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Print Devices, Print Clients, Printers, and Print Servers</a><strong><br></strong><br> <br> <br><br></p></p>', 10, 7, 77),
	(71, NULL, NULL, NULL, 50, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for your company\'s network. The network includes computers running Windows 10 with USB printers attached to the computers. On each of these computers, the physically attached printer is configured as the default printer.<br> <br> You need to create a script that shares the local printers with the entire network.<br> <br> Which PowerShell cmdlet should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Set-Printer PowerShell cmdlet. The Set-Printer cmdlet updates the configuration of an existing printer. You would use the -Shared option to set the share state of the printer. The script would need to run on each computer with a locally attached printer.<br> <br>You should not use the Set-PrintConfiguration cmdlet. This cmdlet sets the configuration information for the specified printer. This does not include sharing.<br> <br>You should not use the Set-PrinterProperty cmdlet. This cmdlet modifies the printer properties for the specified printer but does not include printer sharing.<br> <br>You should not use the Add-Printer cmdlet. You would use this to add a new printer to the computer, but this is not necessary because the printers have already been added. You know this because the printers are configured as default printers.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Set-Printer" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/printmanagement/set-printer" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Set-Printer</a><br><a title="Set-PrinterProperty" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/printmanagement/set-printerproperty" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Set-PrinterProperty</a><br><a title="Set-PrintConfiguration" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/printmanagement/set-printconfiguration" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Set-PrintConfiguration</a><br><a title="Print Management" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/printmanagement/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Print Management</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 79),
	(72, NULL, NULL, NULL, 51, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>D:\\Production is a folder on an NTFS partition on a computer that runs Windows 10. The Production folder contains the Graphics, Copy, and Final subfolders, which are shared to the company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain using their folder names as share names.<br> <br>Marketing and Reviewers are global security groups in the domain. Several domain users are members of both groups.<br> <br>The Marketing group has Read and Write NTFS permissions in the Production folder. The Reviewers group has the Full Control permission to the Production folder. NTFS permissions for Graphics, Copy, and Final are at their defaults.<br> <br>The Marketing group is granted the following share permissions:<br> <br>* Graphics - Change<br>* Copy - Change<br>* Final - Full Control<br> <br>The Reviewers group is granted the following share permissions:<br> <br>* Graphics - Read<br>* Copy - Change<br>* Final - Full Control<br> <br>The Marketing group accesses files in the Graphics, Copy, and Final folders through their network shares only.<br> <br>You are told that members of the Marketing group should be prevented from deleting files from the Graphics folder.<br> <br>You need to configure the folder permissions. You also need to minimize other changes to the effective folder permissions.<br> <br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should change the Marketing share permission for the Graphics folder to Read, which would result in an effective permission of Read only for the group. Graphics would inherit NTFS permissions from the Production folder. Effective permissions when accessing a folder through a share are based on the most restrictive between NTFS and share permissions. The initial share permission, Change, allows for file deletion.<br> <br> You should not deny the Write permission to the Production folder for the Marketing group. This would be inherited by the Graphics, Copy, and Review folders, preventing the Marketing group from making changes to files in any of the folders. Denied permissions take precedence over allowed permissions.<br> <br> You should not block permission inheritance from the Production folder to the Graphics folder. This would not meet the permission requirements and would change the permissions when accessing the folders locally.<br> <br> You should not share the Production folder and assign Marketing the Read share permission. This would not change the share permissions for the Graphics, Copy, and Review folders.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How IT works NTFS Permissions" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/2005.11.howitworksntfs.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How IT works NTFS Permissions</a><br><a title="How Effective Permissions Are Determined" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc772184(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How Effective Permissions Are Determined</a><br><a title="How Permissions Work" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2003/cc783530(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How Permissions Work</a><br><a title="Difference between Share Permissions and NTFS Folder Permissions" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/windowsserver/en-US/34ab8904-e43f-47e4-a0f4-1937b4e291f6/difference-between-share-permissions-and-ntfs-folder-permissions" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Difference between Share Permissions and NTFS Folder Permissions</a><br><a title="Share permissions" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2003/cc784499(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Share permissions</a><br><a title="Explicit vs. Inherited Permissions" href="http://www.ntfs.com/ntfs-permissions-explicit.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Explicit vs. Inherited Permissions</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 82),
	(73, NULL, NULL, NULL, 52, 3, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You need to configure domain support for and then install a line-of-business (LOB) app to your domain clients without publishing it and downloading it from the Windows Store. All devices are managed devices.<br> <br> Which three actions should you perform in sequence? To answer, move the appropriate actions from the list of possible actions to the answer area and arrange them in the correct order.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You need to set up sideloading to meet the scenario requirements. To do this, you should perform the following actions in order:<br> <br>1. Deploy an Enterprise policy to turn on sideloading.<br>2. Import the security certificate for the appx package.<br>3. Run the Add-AppxPackage Windows PowerShell cmdlet.<br> <br>The correct procedure to sideload apps is to turn on sideloading via an enterprise policy. You can enable sideloading for all devices because all devices are managed. Unmanaged devices would have to be enabled individually. You then need to import the appx package security certificate. You can then run the Add-AppxPackage PowerShell cmdlet to install the app. <br> <br>The settings for developers will not allow you to sideload apps.<br> <br>You should not use the Settings app under Updates &amp; Security and For developers to select Sideload apps. You would use this to set up an unmanaged device.<br> <br>You should not use the Settings app under Updates &amp; Security and For developers to select Windows Store apps. You are also not using a Windows Store to deploy.<br> <br>You should not use the DISM command. DISM is for provisioning packages to use during deployment and cannot be used for sideloading.<br> <br>The ppkg package certificate is not applicable for sideloading because ppkg packages are used for deployment.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Sideload LOB apps in Windows 10" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/application-management/sideload-apps-in-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Sideload LOB apps in Windows 10</a></p></p>', 10, 7, 84),
	(74, NULL, NULL, NULL, 53, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the administrator of your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You have recently upgraded all client machines to Windows 10 Professional and all member servers to Windows Server 2016. Domain controllers run Windows Server 2012 R2.<br> <br> You need to prevent users from downloading and installing apps from the Windows Store.<br> <br> What must you do so you can access the Windows Store Group Policy policies?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should add the Desktop Experience feature to a domain controller. This installs the necessary administrative templates needed to control the Windows Store. After the installation completes, the policies get added and can be accessed from the Group Policy Management Console (GPMC).<br> <br> You should not add the Desktop Experience feature on a client machine. This will not give you access to the policies in the GPMC and allow you to configure any settings.<br> <br> You should not install the Windows 10 administrative template on a client machine. The regular administrative templates do not include the Windows Store policy settings.<br> <br> You should not install the Windows 10 administrative template on a domain controller. The regular administrative templates do not include the Windows Store policy settings.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Desktop Experience Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2012-R2-and-2012/dn609826(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Desktop Experience Overview<br></a><br><a title="Install Desktop Experience – Windows Server 2012 R2" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/rmilne/2015/08/24/install-desktop-experience-windows-server-2012-r2/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Install Desktop Experience – Windows Server 2012 R2<br></a><br><a title="How can I block Windows Store with Group Policy" href="https://www.tenforums.com/tutorials/43118-allow-block-access-store-app-windows-10-a.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Allow or Block Access to the Store App in Windows 10</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 87),
	(75, NULL, NULL, NULL, 54, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the administrator of your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You have recently upgraded all domain client computers to Windows 10 Enterprise.<br> <br> You want to prevent users from synchronizing restricted corporate information to their private OneDrive accounts.<br> <br> Which Group Policy setting should you configure?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should enable the Block Microsoft accounts Group Policy and specify the Users can\'t add or log on with Microsoft accounts option. This option prevents users from utilizing their Microsoft account on the device, which in turn ensures that they are not able to synchronize information to their private OneDrive account.<br> <br> You should not use the Block Microsoft accounts Group Policy and specify the Users can\'t add Microsoft accounts option. This option solves part of the problem. The remaining issue is that users can still save information to their local computer, and as long as they can log in to the Microsoft account, they can synchronize.<br> <br> You should not enable the Turn off the Store application Group Policy setting. This setting does not prevent access to OneDrive. It only controls access to the store and its applications. This policy removes the ability to make changes or access settings in the store.<br> <br> You should not enable the Turn off Automatic Download and Install of updates Group Policy setting. This setting does not prevent access to OneDrive. It only controls the store behavior. The store does not automatically download and install updates once this policy is enabled.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Accounts: Block Microsoft accounts" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/security-policy-settings/accounts-block-microsoft-accounts" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Accounts: Block Microsoft accounts</a><br><a title="Use Group Policy to control Windows 8 Store access" href="http://searchenterprisedesktop.techtarget.com/tip/Use-Group-Policy-to-control-Windows-8-Store-access" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Use Group Policy to control Windows 8 Store access</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 88),
	(76, NULL, NULL, NULL, 55, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the administrator of your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You have recently upgraded all domain client computers to Windows 10 Enterprise.<br> <br> You want to utilize Windows Store for Business to deploy internal applications for users. Users should not be able to add apps outside of your Windows Store for Business.<br> <br> What type of account do users need?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Azure AD accounts. Employees must use an Azure AD account when accessing Microsoft Store for Business. The employee must use a PC or other device running Windows 10 for access.<br> <br>You should not use a Microsoft account, domain account or local account. Neither type of account is supported for access to Windows Store for Business.<br>The requirements are the same for access Microsoft Store for Education.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Prerequisites for Microsoft Store for Business and Education" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-store/prerequisites-microsoft-store-for-business" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Prerequisites for Microsoft Store for Business and Education</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 89),
	(77, NULL, NULL, NULL, 56, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the administrator of your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You have recently upgraded all domain client computers to Windows 10 Enterprise.<br> <br> You have deployed an application to your Windows Store for Business that allows for in-app purchases.<br> <br> You need to instruct end users how in-app purchasing is handled. All users have Azure Active Directory (AD) accounts and Microsoft accounts.<br> <br> What should you tell them?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should tell the users to make purchases with their Microsoft accounts, paid by the employee at the time of purchase. To deal with in-app purchases, the extra purchase must be tied to a Microsoft account and paid by the purchaser. There is no way to accumulate payments or bundle them on a corporate basis.<br> <br> You should not tell the users to make purchases with their Azure AD accounts, paid by the company or the employee on a monthly schedule: There is no method to accumulate in-app purchases, and purchases must be tied to a Microsoft account.<br> <br> You should not tell the users to make purchases with their Microsoft accounts, paid by the company on a monthly schedule: There is no method to accumulate in-app purchases.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-store/apps-in-microsoft-store-for-business" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-store/apps-in-microsoft-store-for-business" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Apps in Windows Store for Business and Education</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 90),
	(78, NULL, NULL, NULL, 57, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the Windows administrator for your organization. You have recently deployed Windows 10 to all desktop computers. Users are complaining that Universal Windows apps are not being used and take up a lot of space on their machines.<br> <br> You need to ensure that Universal Windows apps are not installed when provisioning new user profiles.<br> <br> Which Windows PowerShell command string should you use on each computer?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Get-AppXProvisionedPackage -online | Remove-AppxProvisionedPackage -online. The Get-AppxProvisionedPackage cmdlet gets information about app packages in an image. The Remove-AppxProvisionedPackage cmdlet allows you to remove app packages from Windows image files that have been created for deployment. With this command, new users created on the machine will not receive the packages. Packages will not be removed from existing user accounts.<br> <br> You should not use Get-AppxPackage -AllUsers | Remove-AppxPackage. The Get-AppxPackage cmdlet gets a list of the app packages that are installed in a user profile. The Remove-AppxPackage cmdlet removes an app package from a user account. This command removes all Universal Windows apps for all user accounts.<br> <br> You should not use Get-AppXPackage | Remove-AppxPackage. The Get-AppxPackage cmdlet gets a list of the app packages that are installed in a user profile. The Remove-AppxPackage cmdlet removes an app package from a user account. This command removes all Universal Windows apps from your current user account.<br> <br> You should not use Get-AppXPackage -User &lt;username&gt; | Remove-AppxPackage. The Get-AppxPackage cmdlet gets a list of the app packages that are installed in a user profile. The Remove-AppxPackage cmdlet removes an app package from a user account. This command removes all Universal Windows apps from a specific user account.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Get-AppxPackage" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh856044.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Get-AppxPackage</a><br><a title="Remove-AppxPackage" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh856038.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Remove-AppxPackage</a><br><a title="Get-AppxProvisionedPackage" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/dism/get-appxprovisionedpackage" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-AppxProvisionedPackage</a><br><a title="Remove-AppxProvisionedPackage" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/dism/remove-appxprovisionedpackage" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Remove-AppxProvisionedPackage</a><br><a title="How to remove all bundled apps in Windows 10" href="http://winaero.com/blog/how-to-remove-all-bundled-apps-in-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to remove all bundled apps in Windows 10</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 91),
	(79, NULL, NULL, NULL, 58, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are configuring startup options for a computer running Windows 10 Pro. The computer is currently configured to launch several Windows apps at startup.<br> <br> You need to disable some of the apps that launch at startup.<br> <br> Which tool or command should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Task Manager. You can access the Task Manager by right-clicking the taskbar and clicking Task Manager or by pressing the &lt;CTRL&gt;+&lt;SHIFT&gt;+&lt;ESC&gt; keys. From the initial dialog, click More Details. This will display a list of start-up applications. For each app you want to disable, select the app and click Disable.<br> <br>You should not use Advanced Startup Options. Advanced Startup Options lets you specify a device to use to boot the computer, launch the troubleshooting utility, or turn off the computer. It does not let you manage startup apps.<br> <br>You should not use msconfig. This is the option you would have used with earlier Windows versions, but not with Windows 10.<br> <br>You should not use BCDEdit. BCDEdit lets you configure boot options, such as the setting default boot drive for the computer, adding a new boot entry, or configuring options for a boot entry, such as launching the kernel debugger when you boot.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><a title="How do you add new Startup programs in Windows 10?" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/f0005629-0377-4e4b-82cc-26aff7b95884/how-do-you-add-new-startup-programs-in-wndows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How do you add new Startup programs in Windows 10?</a><br><a title="Bootsect Command-Line Options" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-vista/cc749177(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Bootsect Command-Line Options</a><br><a title="How To Access Advanced Startup Options in Windows 10 or 8" href="https://www.lifewire.com/how-to-access-advanced-startup-options-in-windows-10-or-8-2626229" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How To Access Advanced Startup Options in Windows 10 or 8</a><br><a title="Editing Boot Options" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/drivers/devtest/editing-boot-options" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Editing Boot Options</a><br><a title="Manage Startup Programs" href="http://www.windows10forums.com/articles/manage-startup-programs.1/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Manage Startup Programs</a><br><a title="MSConfig the System Configuration Tool." href="http://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wiki/windows_10-update/msconfig-the-system-configuration-tool/273dea8e-4cbe-47e9-8489-f400e879ce17" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>MSConfig the System Configuration Tool.</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 92),
	(80, NULL, NULL, NULL, 59, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>Your school is setting up Microsoft Store for Education to manage and distribute apps to teachers and students. You enable the Make everyone a Basic Purchaser setting. You configure self-service sign up for Azure Active Directory (Azure AD).<br> <br>You need to ensure that teachers and students will have access to apps.<br> <br>Which two requirements must be met for them to be able to use Microsoft Store for Education? Each correct answer presents part of the solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>All client devices must run Windows 10 or Windows 10 mobile. These are the only operating system options currently supported. In addition, an Azure AD account is required to access online-licensed apps. This is true for both teachers and students.<br> <br> Students can be assigned Minecraft: Education Edition even if they do not have a school account. This is possible because self-service sign in is enabled. Students will receive an email that steps them through the sign in process.<br> <br> An Azure AD account is not required to use offline-licensed apps. This is only required for online-licensed apps.<br> <br> Teachers do not need to be made administrators before they can distribute any apps to students. This can be done as Basic Purchasers. This includes apps configured as free apps, such as Minecraft.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Microsoft Store for Business and Microsoft Store for Education overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-store/microsoft-store-for-business-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Microsoft Store for Business and Microsoft Store for Education overview</a><br><a title="Working with Microsoft Store for Education" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/education/windows/education-scenarios-store-for-business" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Working with Microsoft Store for Education</a><br><a title="Prerequisites for Microsoft Store for Business and Education" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-store/prerequisites-microsoft-store-for-business" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Prerequisites for Microsoft Store for Business and Education</a><br><a title="Settings reference: Microsoft Store for Business and Education" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-store/settings-reference-microsoft-store-for-business" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Settings reference: Microsoft Store for Business and Education</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 93),
	(81, NULL, NULL, NULL, 60, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as a single Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You deploy several computers with Windows 10 already installed for using single-application kiosks.<br> <br> You need to configure the computers with the Universal Windows app to run in kiosk mode. You want to minimize the effort necessary to accomplish this and ensure consistent configuration for each kiosk.<br> <br> Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Windows Configuration Designer, which installs as part of the Windows Assessment and Deployment Kit (ADK). Windows Configuration Designer includes wizards to help you quickly and easily prepare provisioning packages to meet different scenarios, including a wizard for provisioning kiosk devices. This includes the ability to specify the app to run in kiosk mode.<br> <br> You should not use DISM. This is a command line-based tool that can be used to prepare and modify Windows images for installation or to service an image or virtual hard disk (VHD). It does not provide the functionality needed in this scenario.<br> <br> You should not use Task Manager. Task Manager includes the ability to manage the apps launched at startup but does not give you a way to specify the app to be used specifically for kiosk mode.<br> <br> You should not use Advanced Startup Options. Advanced Startup Options lets you specify a device to boot the computer, launch the troubleshooting utility, or turn off the computer. It does not let you manage apps.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Create a provisioning package for Windows 10" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-create-package" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Create a provisioning package for Windows 10</a><br><a title="Provisioning packages for Windows 10" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-packages" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Provisioning packages for Windows 10</a><br><a title="Set up a single-app kiosk" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/kiosk-single-app" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Set up a single-app kiosk</a><br><a title="How To Access Advanced Startup Options in Windows 10 or 8" href="https://www.lifewire.com/how-to-access-advanced-startup-options-in-windows-10-or-8-2626229" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How To Access Advanced Startup Options in Windows 10 or 8</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 94),
	(82, NULL, NULL, NULL, 61, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as a single Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All network client computers run Windows 10. You are the administrator responsible for client management.<br> <br>You need to configure clients remotely to be able to support remote management using Windows PowerShell.<br> <br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should configure the WinRM service to start automatically and start the service on the computers. The service is installed by default on all currently supported Windows versions. You can reboot the computers, restart from the Control Panel Services utility, or use the net start command. By default, the service is set to manual and it needs to run for remote management via PowerShell to work. WinRM must be started for a computer to support Windows PowerShell remoting.<br> <br>You should not use the Get-Service Windows PowerShell command with the -ComputerName switch. This command lists the services on a computer. By using the -ComputerName parameter with the Get-Service cmdlet, you can obtain a listing of the status of the services that are defined on a remote computer.<br> <br>You should not use the Set-Service Windows PowerShell command with the -ComputerName switch. This command starts, stops, and suspends a service and changes its properties. The Set-Service cmdlet also has been updated to include the -ComputerName parameter.<br> <br>You should not add the computers to the trusted hosts list. The trusted host list enables you to work with remote computers in other domains. If the remote computer is not in a trusted domain, the remote computer might not be able to authenticate your credentials. To enable authentication, you need to add the remote computer to the list of trusted hosts for the local computer in WinRM.<br> <br>Trusted hosts configuration is also required when working in a workgroup environment instead of an AD domain.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Tip: Enable and Use Remote Commands in Windows PowerShell" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ff700227.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Tip: Enable and Use Remote Commands in Windows PowerShell</a><br><a title="Windows Remote Management" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/WinRM/portal" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Remote Management</a><br><a title="Installation and Configuration for Windows Remote Management" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/WinRM/installation-and-configuration-for-windows-remote-management" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Installation and Configuration for Windows Remote Management</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 95),
	(83, NULL, NULL, NULL, 62, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All domain clients run Windows 10.<br> <br>You need to enable client computers in a remote office to receive commands sent by using the WS-Management technology.<br> <br>Which Windows PowerShell cmdlet should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Enable-PSRemoting. The Enable-PSRemoting cmdlet configures a computer to receive Windows PowerShell commands. When run locally on the computer, you do not need to specify any additional parameters.<br> <br>You should not use Connect-PSSession. This cmdlet reconnects to disconnected remote session, but the sessions must have been established, and settings must have been applied prior to using it.<br> <br>You should not use Enable-PSSessionConfiguration. The Enable-PSSessionConfiguration cmdlet allows a system administrator to re-enable disabled configurations that have been disabled. <br> <br>You should not use New-PSSession. The New-PSSession cmdlet starts a remote session on a remote computer. You must enable PowerShell remoting on a target computer prior to starting a remote session with the computer.<br> <br>You should not use New-PSSessionOption. The New-PSSessionOption cmdlet contains advanced options for a user-managed session. Commands can be sent to the session by using various parameters.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Enable-PSRemoting" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Core/Enable-PSRemoting" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Enable-PSRemoting</a><br><a title="Connect-PSSession" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Core/Connect-PSSession" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Connect-PSSession</a><br><a title="Enable-PSSessionConfiguration" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Core/Enable-PSSessionConfiguration" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Enable-PSSessionConfiguration</a><br><a title="New-PSSession" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Core/New-PSSession" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>New-PSSession</a><br><a title="New-PSSessionOption" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Core/New-PSSessionOption" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>New-PSSessionOption</a><br><a title="How to enable PowerShell remoting" href="https://searchwindowsserver.techtarget.com/feature/How-to-enable-PowerShell-remoting" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to enable PowerShell remoting</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 96),
	(84, NULL, NULL, NULL, 63, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are having a problem on a computer running Windows 10. You contact support to get assistance on a technical issue, and they ask you to set up an Easy Connect session with them. You have worked with the support technician through Easy Connect before.<br> <br>What should you do first?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>Easy Connect is a connection option for Windows Remote Assistance. You are prompted with options to send an invitation or use Each Connect when requesting assistance. If you have worked with someone through Easy Connect before, that person will be in the Easy Connect contact list. Click the contact to start a secure session without having to use an invitation or password.<br><br>You should not launch the WinRM service. This is not necessary when using remote assistance. This would be necessary if the technician were using PowerShell remoting to manage your computer.<br> <br>Easy Connect does not use Windows Hello. This uses facial recognition, iris scanner, or finger print scanner to provide login capabilities for Windows 10 devices. It is not used for Easy Connect.<br> <br>An invitation and password are not necessary when you have worked with someone through Easy Connect in the past. This is, however, an option for requesting assistance from a remote computer.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Windows 10: How to Send Remote Assistance Invitation" href="http://www.technipages.com/windows-send-remote-assistance-invitation" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10: How to Send Remote Assistance Invitation</a><br><a title="Use Remote Assistance to let someone fix your PC" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/instantanswers/018e0e28-050c-0f1b-1562-b15aaad6ab7d/use-remote-assistance-to-let-someone-fix-your-pc" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Use Remote Assistance to let someone fix your PC</a><br><a title="How To Provide Remote Support With Windows Remote Assistance" href="https://www.digitalcitizen.life/how-provide-remote-support-windows-remote-assistance" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How To Provide Remote Support With Windows Remote Assistance</a><br><a title="Windows Remote Management" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/WinRM/portal" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Remote Management</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 97),
	(85, NULL, NULL, NULL, 64, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain administrator. All domain client computers run Windows 10.<br> <br>Your company reorganizes its support department. Users should no longer be able to request remote assistance from Support. Only Support should be able to initiate a remote access connection.<br> <br>You need to disable the ability to make Remote Desktop Assistance on all domain clients. Administrative effort should be kept to a minimum. <br> <br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should create and link a GPO that disables the Solicited Remote Assistance Group Policy setting. This will prevent users from asking for a Remote Desktop connection, but Support can still offer a connection.<br> <br> You should not create and link a GPO that disables the Offer Remote Assistance Group Policy setting. This would leave users able to request a connection but would prevent Support from offering a connection.<br> <br> You should not add fDenyTSConnections to the HKLM\\Software\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\Terminal Services registry key. This requires a change individually to each computer. Also, it would prevent both solicited and offered connections.<br> <br> You should also not select the Remote tab and remove the check from Allow Remote Assistance connections to this computer in the Control Panel. This would require you to reconfigure each computer individually and would prevent both solicited and offered connections.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><a title="Remote Assistance" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-xp/bb457177(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Remote Assistance</a><br><a title="fDenyTSConnections" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-8.1-and-8/ff716079(v=win.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>fDenyTSConnections</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 98),
	(86, NULL, NULL, NULL, 65, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. Your domain includes a member sever running Windows Server 2016 named AppHost. AppHost is configured to support Hyper-V.<br> <br>You configure multiple virtual machines (VMs) on AppHost to host applications that will be made available to member computers running Windows 10. The applications will run on the VM but will be displayed and controlled from the client computer.<br> <br>You need to provide domain users with instructions for using the virtual applications. Users should be prompted for the VM to which they are connecting and their domain user name. The user needs to be able to choose whether local resources, such as printers and the Clipboard, are available while connected.<br> <br>Which tool or utility should domain users use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>Users should use Remote Desktop Connection to connect to a VM hosting the application. Remote Desktop connection prompts for the host machine\'s Fully Qualified Domain Name (FQDN) and a valid user account name. The remote application screens will be displayed on the user\'s computer, and user input is passed to the remote VM. You can run the mstsc command or the Remote Desktop Connection app to launch Remote Desktop Connection.<br> <br>You should not have users launch Remote Assistance, Easy Connect, or Quick Assist. These are all utilities that let you request or offer help to a remote user.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Set up &amp; use Windows Remote Assistance in Windows 10/8.1" href="http://www.thewindowsclub.com/windows-remote-assistance-in-windows-8" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Set up &amp; use Windows Remote Assistance in Windows 10/8.1</a><br><a title="Remote Assistance for Windows 10" href="http://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_10-networking/remote-assistance-for-windows-10/eaaa3047-4a5b-4bc6-b2b3-b1facf7e4011" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Remote Assistance for Windows 10</a><br><a title="Give or take Tech Support using Quick Assist in Windows 10" href="http://www.thewindowsclub.com/quick-assist-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Give or take Tech Support using Quick Assist in Windows 10</a><br><a title="Overview of RemoteApp and Desktop Connection" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ee216745(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Overview of RemoteApp and Desktop Connection</a><br><a title="Remote Desktop Connection Manager" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ee221120(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Remote Desktop Connection Manager</a><br><a title="About Virtual Desktop Pools" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ee216741(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>About Virtual Desktop Pools</a><br><br><a title="Hyper-V Technology Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/virtualization/hyper-v/Hyper-V-Technology-Overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Hyper-V Technology Overview</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 99),
	(87, NULL, NULL, NULL, 66, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You provide end-user support for a small company. All company client computers run Windows 10 Pro or Windows 10 Enterprise.<br> <br> You are on the phone with a user. You need to talk the user through the process of initiating an Easy Connect session.<br> <br> Which command should you have the user run?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should have the user run the msra command. Easy Connect is one of the Windows remote assistance options. When you run msra, you are prompted to either invite someone to help you or respond to an invitation. Click Invite someone you trust to help you to display the invitation options. The invitation options are:<br> <br>* Save this invitation as a file.<br>* Use email to send an invitation.<br>* Use Easy Connect.<br> <br>The user can then click Use Easy Connect to send you an invitation and initiate an Easy Connect support session.<br> <br>You should not run the mstsc command. This is used to launch Remote Desktop Connection, which lets you connect to a remote computer to run an application virtualized on that remote host. Remote Desktop requires an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain environment.<br> <br>You should not run the mmc command. This launches the Microsoft Management Console (MMC), which is a management tool that lets you create a custom console with different management utilities. MMC can be used to manage a remote computer through these utilities.<br> <br>You should not run the winrm command. This is a remote management utility that lets you execute scripts and management commands on a remote computer.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Set up &amp; use Windows Remote Assistance in Windows 10/8.1" href="http://www.thewindowsclub.com/windows-remote-assistance-in-windows-8" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Set up &amp; use Windows Remote Assistance in Windows 10/8.1</a><br><a title="Remote Assistance for Windows 10" href="http://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_10-networking/remote-assistance-for-windows-10/eaaa3047-4a5b-4bc6-b2b3-b1facf7e4011" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Remote Assistance for Windows 10</a><br><a title="Remote Assistance" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-xp/bb457177(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Remote Assistance</a><br><a title="Mstsc" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2012-R2-and-2012/cc753907(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Mstsc</a><br><a title="Windows Remote Management (WinRM) Overview" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/mt703305.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Remote Management (WinRM) Overview</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 100),
	(88, NULL, NULL, NULL, 67, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for your company. Your network includes multiple geographic locations. Network servers run Windows Server 2012 R2 or Windows Server 2016. Network clients run Windows 8.1 or Windows 10.<br> <br> You are investigating the use of PowerShell scripts in management. You are going to use a computer running Windows 10 as the test destination.<br> <br> You need to configure the computer to act as a remote PowerShell management destination.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You need to run the Enable-PSRemoting cmdlet on the destination computer. The cmdlet needs to be run locally on the destination system to configure the computer to support remote management through PowerShell cmdlets. You would run this from a PowerShell prompt on the local machine. You can open a PowerShell prompt from the Accessories menu in the Start menu or by running PowerShell from a standard command prompt.<br> <br> Configuring the WinRM service and configuring Windows Firewall exceptions are both necessary, but by themselves, each is only a partial solution. The Enable-PSRemoting cmdlet performs these actions for you through a single command.<br> <br> You should not run the Receive-PSSession cmdlet. This cmdlet is used to get the results of any commands that were running in a disconnected PowerShell remote session.<br> <br> You should not enable Remote Assistance. Remote Assistance is used to request or offer help by connecting to and controlling another computer.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Tip: Enable and Use Remote Commands in Windows PowerShell" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ff700227.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Tip: Enable and Use Remote Commands in Windows PowerShell</a><br><a title="Using Windows PowerShell" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/tn-archive/cc482986(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Using Windows PowerShell</a><br><a title="Enable-PSRemoting" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Core/Enable-PSRemoting" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Enable-PSRemoting</a><br><a title="Microsoft.PowerShell.Core" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Core" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Microsoft.PowerShell.Core</a><br><a title="about_Remote" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dd347744.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>about_Remote</a><br><a title="PowerShell Basics: Remote Management" href="http://windowsitpro.com/powershell/powershell-basics-remote-management" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>PowerShell Basics: Remote Management</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 102),
	(89, NULL, NULL, NULL, 68, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You network is configured as an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All domain clients run Windows 10 Professional or Windows 10 Enterprise. Your computer runs Windows 10 Enterprise.<br> <br>You need to log onto your computer as a domain administrator and perform disk and device management, task scheduling, and service management on remote clients. The solution you choose should not require any special setup or configuration on the remote clients.<br> <br>What should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use MMC. MMC includes snap-ins for all of the management tasks that you need to support. You can add a snap-in and choose to connect to a remote computer with that snap-in. You will be able to connect with the remote clients because you will be logged on as a domain administrator.<br> <br> You should not use PowerShell cmdlets. You would need to run the Enable-PSRemoting cmdlet on the remote clients before they would be able to accept the remote commands.<br> <br> You should not use Remote Access or Easy Connect, which is a connection option for Remote Access. You would need to enable Remote Access at each of the remote clients before you could use this management method.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Using Microsoft Management Console to Access Remote Devices" href="https://www.interfacett.com/blogs/using-microsoft-management-console-to-access-remote-devices/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Using Microsoft Management Console to Access Remote Devices</a><br><a title="Use MMC Remotely" href="https://www.devopsonwindows.com/use-mmc-remotely/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Use MMC Remotely</a><br><a title="Guide To Remote Desktop Connection on Windows 10" href="https://www.guidingtech.com/51111/guide-remote-desktop-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Guide To Remote Desktop Connection on Windows 10</a><br><a title="How To Provide Remote Support With Windows Remote Assistance" href="https://www.digitalcitizen.life/how-provide-remote-support-windows-remote-assistance" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How To Provide Remote Support With Windows Remote Assistance</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 103),
	(90, NULL, NULL, NULL, 69, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are a domain administrator for your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You are directed to remove all Universal apps for all users with domain client computers running Windows 10. Computers running Windows 10 are grouped in an Organizational Unit (OU) named W10.<br> <br> You need to remove all Universal apps.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should run the Get-AppxPackage -AllUsers | Remove-AppxPackage cmdlet. The Get-AppxPackage cmdlet returns a list of existing Universal apps installed on the machine. The command string then pipes the result through the Remove-AppxPackage cmdlet to remove them from the machine. This command string must be run separately on each domain client computer.<br> <br> You should not use Deployment Image Servicing and Management (DISM) or Windows Configuration Designer (the icd.exe command). DISM and Windows Configuration Designer are used for provisioning Windows images. Neither can be used to remove Universal apps.<br> <br> You should not create and link a Group Policy object (GPO) to the W10 OU to remove Universal apps. You cannot use Group Policy to remove all Universal apps.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Packaging and deployment tools and PowerShell cmdlets" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/desktop/appxpkg/appx-packaging-tools" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Packaging and deployment tools and PowerShell cmdlets</a><br><a title="How to remove all bundled apps in Windows 10" href="http://winaero.com/blog/how-to-remove-all-bundled-apps-in-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to remove all bundled apps in Windows 10</a><br><a title="DISM Provisioning Package (.ppkg) Command-Line Options" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/manufacture/desktop/dism-provisioning-package-command-line-options" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>DISM Provisioning Package (.ppkg) Command-Line Options</a><br><a title="Windows Configuration Designer command-line interface (reference)" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-command-line" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Configuration Designer command-line interface (reference)</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 105),
	(91, NULL, NULL, NULL, 70, 3, 0, NULL, '<p>You are a domain administrator for your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All domain clients run Windows 8.1 or Windows 10. <br> <br> You remove the Windows Store from a client computer running Windows 10.<br> <br> You need to restore the Windows Store to the computer. You launch a PowerShell administrator command prompt.<br> <br> Which three actions should you perform in sequence? To answer, move the appropriate actions from the list of possible actions to the answer area and arrange them in the correct order.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should perform the following actions in order:<br> <br> 1. Run Get-AppxPackage.<br> 2. Find the [PackageFullName] entry for the Microsoft.WindowsStore entry and note.<br> 3. Run Add-AppxPackage.<br> <br> The Get-AppxPackage cmdlet lists the app packages that are installed in a user profile. You need to note the Full Name of the package, which is then used when you run Add-AppxPackage to register the package back to the user profile.<br> <br> The PackageFamilyName is not used when restoring the Windows Store.<br> <br> You should not use Get-AppxProvisionedPackage or Add-AppxProvisioned Package. The Windows Store is not a provisioned package.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How to restore Windows Store in Windows 10 after removing it with PowerShell" href="http://winaero.com/blog/how-to-restore-windows-store-in-windows-10-after-removing-it-with-powershell/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to restore Windows Store in Windows 10 after removing it with PowerShell</a><br><a title="Add-AppxPackage" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh856048.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Add-AppxPackage</a><br><a title="Appx" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/appx/index" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Appx</a><br><a title="DISM" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/dism/index" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>DISM</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 6, 106),
	(92, NULL, NULL, NULL, 71, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage Windows 10 devices for travelling sales people in your organization.<br> <br>All sales devices have SIM cards installed and data plans with a mobile operator. Cellular connections are used to access the Internet when travelling. Users report that they often go over their data plan limits when travelling.<br> <br>You need to minimize Internet data requirements and use for travelling users.<br> <br>Which two settings should you configure? Each correct answer presents part of the solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should disable Windows Update Delivery Optimization. This feature allows Windows to both download updates and updates to apps, as well as share updates to other machines over the Internet. This can cause extra traffic, which can cause data overage charges.<br> <br>You should also set the cellular connection as metered. Some connections are not automatically set up as metered connections, and you must manually configure them. Metered connections automatically limit downloads and other activity based on configured data limits to save bandwidth and data costs.<br> <br>You should not turn off network discovery. Network discovery allows a computer to view visible networks and devices, and vice versa. There is no need to disable this to limit data use.<br> <br>You should not disable the QoS Packet Scheduler. The scheduler is designed to control the flow of network traffic for various network services, including Real Time Communications traffic. It does not affect the control of update downloads.<br> <br>You should not enable the Microsoft Network Adapter Multiplexor Protocol. Microsoft Network Adapter Multiplexor Protocol is a kernel device driver. In Windows 10 it is starting only if the user, an application, or another service starts it.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Cellular settings in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/10739/windows-10-cellular-settings" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Cellular settings in Windows 10</a><br><a title="How to set metered connections and disable Windows 10 Update Delivery Optimization" href="http://www.windowscentral.com/how-disable-windows-10-update-delivery-optimization" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to set metered connections and disable Windows 10 Update Delivery Optimization</a><br><a title="Metered connections in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/4028458/windows-metered-connections-in-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Metered connections in Windows 10</a><br><a title="Microsoft Network Adapter Multiplexor Protocol (NdisImPlatform) Service Defaults in Windows 10" href="http://servicedefaults.com/10/ndisimplatform/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Microsoft Network Adapter Multiplexor Protocol (NdisImPlatform) Service Defaults in Windows 10</a><br><a title="Network Discovery" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/cc181373.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Network Discovery</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 107),
	(93, NULL, NULL, NULL, 72, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are a Windows administrator for your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. The company uses Windows Server Update Services (WSUS) for all domain computers.<br> <br> Microsoft releases an update that has been downloaded but not yet been approved in WSUS.<br> <br> You need to install the update on a client computer in your domain for testing purposes.<br> <br> What should you do on the computer?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Microsoft Update. Microsoft Update will allow you to install updates, even if the computer normally receives updates from WSUS.<br> <br>You should not run the gpupdate /force command. This updates group policies applied to the computer, not updates from Windows update.<br> <br>You should not run the Get-WindowsUpdateLog Windows PowerShell cmdlet. This cmdlet merges all Windows Update files into a log file.<br> <br>You should not run the Update-Module Windows PowerShell cmdlet. This cmdlet downloads and installs the latest version of the specified modules.<br> <br>You should not clear the Defer upgrades checkbox. This option delays feature upgrades for several months while allowing security updates through. This allows business users or administrators to delay updates until they have been tested and verified to work properly with installed hardware and software.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Get-WindowsUpdateLog" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/windowsupdate/get-windowsupdatelog" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Get-WindowsUpdateLog</a><br><br><a title="Update-Module" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/PowershellGet/Update-Module" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Update-Module</a><br><br><a title="Defer upgrades in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/4026834/windows-10-defer-upgrades" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Defer upgrades in Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="How to Check for and Install Windows Updates" href="https://www.lifewire.com/how-to-check-for-install-windows-updates-2624596" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Check for and Install Windows Updates</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 108),
	(94, NULL, NULL, NULL, 73, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You manage 20 Windows 10 computers in the engineering department. A recent Windows update has caused a critical third-party application running on one of the computers to crash.<br> <br> You need to roll back the update.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should go to View your update history and uninstall the update. This location (Select the Start button, then select Settings &gt; Update &amp; security &gt; Windows Update &gt; Advanced options &gt; View your update history &gt; Uninstall updates) provides the option of uninstalling updates.<br> <br> You should not use the Remove-Item Windows PowerShell cmdlet: The Remove-Item cmdlet allows you to delete any content. It can remove locked or protected files in the filesystem. It does not uninstall updates.<br> <br> You should not use the Clear-Content Windows PowerShell cmdlet: The Clear-Content cmdlet lets you erase the contents of a file without deleting the file itself. It has nothing to do with updates.<br> <br> You should not go to the Control Panel and uninstall the application by using Programs and Features. Uninstalling the application will not remove the Windows update. This would make the application unavailable and so does not bring you any closer to a solution.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><strong><br></strong><a title="Using the Remove-Item Cmdlet" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-powershell-1.0/ee176938(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Using the Remove-Item Cmdlet</a><br><br><a title="Using the Clear-Content Cmdlet" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-powershell-1.0/ee156808(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Using the Clear-Content Cmdlet</a><br><br><a title="Windows Update: FAQ" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12373/windows-update-faq" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Update: FAQ<br></a>Chapter: How do I remove an installed update?<br><br><a title="Repair or remove programs in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/4028054/windows-10-repair-or-remove-programs" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Repair or remove programs in Windows 10</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 109),
	(95, NULL, NULL, NULL, 74, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You have removed the Windows Store app from a computer running Windows 8 by using Windows PowerShell. You want to apply a Windows 8.1 update to the computer before upgrading to Windows 10. The update is available in the Windows Store.<br> <br> You need to restore the Windows Store app.<br> <br> Which Windows PowerShell cmdlet should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Add-AppxPackage -register "C:\\Program Files\\WindowsApps\\[PackageFullName]\\AppxManifest.xml" -DisableDevelopmentMode. The Add-AppxPackage cmdlet allows you to include a signed app package to any user. The -Register switch registers an application in development mode. Development mode can be used to install applications from a folder of unpackaged files. The -Register parameter allows you to test apps before deploying them. To register an existing app package installation, you must specify -DisableDevelopmentMode as well as -Register.<br> <br>You should not use Add-AppxPackage -update "C:\\Program Files\\WindowsApps\\[PackageFullName]\\AppxManifest.xml" -DisableDevelopmentMode. The -Update switch attaches the update package to an existing app package, and is dependent on the parent package. If a parent package is removed from a user account, all dependent packages are removed as well. <br> <br>You should not use Get-AppxPackage -Name [PackageFullName] -AllUsers. The Get-AppxPackage cmdlet presents a list of all packages installed. You can select to see only the current user profile, a specified user profile, or all profiles from a computer. To use this parameter, you must run the command by using administrator permissions.<br> <br>You should not use Get-AppxPackage -Name [PackageFullName] -User domain\\username. The Get-AppxPackage cmdlet gets a list of the app packages that are installed in a user profile.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Add-AppxPackage" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh856048.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Add-AppxPackage</a><br><a title="Get-AppxPackage" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh856044.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-AppxPackage</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 110),
	(96, NULL, NULL, NULL, 75, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. Your domain is organized as a main office and one small remote office. Each location is configured as a domain site. All network clients run Windows 8.1 or Windows 10.<br> <br>Your main office network includes a Windows Server Update Services (WSUS) server that is used to manage updates for servers and clients that are deployed in the main network. The remote office network only includes client computers that download updates directly from Windows Update.<br> <br>You discover that an update is causing a problem with an application running on some of the clients on the remote network.<br> <br>You need to remove the update from the affected clients.<br> <br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Windows Update utility or Programs and Features utility in the Control Panel. With either utility, you can click View Installed Updates to view a list of installed updates. From there, you can right-click the update you want to remove and choose Uninstall.<br> <br>You should not create and link a GPO to the remote site. There is not GPO option for uninstalling an update.<br> <br>You should not deploy a WSUS downstream server in the remote site. This will not have any effect because the clients manage their own updates.<br> <br>You should not use System Information. System Information provides information about system hardware, resources, and settings, but it does not provide a way to manage installed updates.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Windows Server Update Services Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2012-R2-and-2012/hh852345(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Server Update Services Overview</a><br><a title="How to Rollback installed update from client." href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/windowsserver/en-US/ae7a3a52-3345-486c-b0e0-b12b4f89a414/how-to-rollback-installed-update-from-client" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Rollback installed update from client</a><a title="How to Rollback installed update from client." href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/windowsserver/en-US/ae7a3a52-3345-486c-b0e0-b12b4f89a414/how-to-rollback-installed-update-from-client" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">.</a><br><a title="How to install and uninstall updates in Windows 8" href="http://windows.mercenie.com/windows-8/how-to-install-and-uninstall-updates-in-windows-8/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to install and uninstall updates in Windows 8</a><br><a title="Windows Update: FAQ" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12373/windows-update-faq" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Update: FAQ</a><br><a title="Description of Microsoft System Information (Msinfo32.exe) Tool" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/184075/description-of-microsoft-system-information-msinfo32-exe-tool" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Description of Microsoft System Information (Msinfo32.exe) Tool</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 111),
	(97, NULL, NULL, NULL, 76, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. Your domain includes many small remote sites in different geographic locations, most of which are retail outlets. Some links to remote sites have limited bandwidth support. All domain clients run Windows 10 Pro or Windows 10 Enterprise.<br> <br> All updates are managed from your main office. Clients are configured to receive Windows Quality Updates using Windows Updates for Business. You disable using Windows Updates for Microsoft Updates. You use Windows Server Update Services (WSUS) for Microsoft Updates and third-party device driver updates. All update servers are physically deployed in your main office.<br> <br> You need to reduce the traffic generated by updating clients in remote offices. You need to keep the infrastructure changes and the effort necessary to deploy the solution to a minimum.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Delivery Optimization for all updates. Delivery Optimization is a self-organizing delivery optimization method. After one computer receives an update in a remote office, the remaining computers will receive their updates from that computer. Delivery Optimization can be used with updates received through Windows Update or WSUS.<br> <br>You should not use a solution relying on BranchCache only. BranchCache does not support updates received through Windows Update. Distributed Cache mode is similar to Delivery Optimization in that the first computer to receive the update will redistribute the update to other computers. With Hosted Cache mode, a server is designated to receive the updates and provide them to clients.<br> <br>You should not use Delivery Optimization with BranchCache because this would require additional administrative effort to set up and would not supply any benefits over Delivery Optimization. When computers running Windows 10 are configured for both Delivery Optimization and BranchCache, they will use Delivery Optimization only.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Update Windows 10 in enterprise deployments" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/index" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Update Windows 10 in enterprise deployments</a><br><a title="Overview of Windows as a service" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/waas-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Overview of Windows as a service</a><br><a title="Optimize Windows 10 update delivery" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/waas-optimize-windows-10-updates" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Optimize Windows 10 update delivery</a><br><a title="Assign devices to servicing channels for Windows 10 updates" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/waas-servicing-channels-windows-10-updates" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Assign devices to servicing channels for Windows 10 updates</a><br><a title="Build deployment rings for Windows 10 updates" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/waas-deployment-rings-windows-10-updates" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Build deployment rings for Windows 10 updates</a><br><a title="Configure Delivery Optimization for Windows 10 updates" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/waas-delivery-optimization" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Configure Delivery Optimization for Windows 10 updates</a><br><a title="Deploy updates using Windows Update for Business" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/waas-manage-updates-wufb" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Deploy updates using Windows Update for Business</a><br><a title="Integrate Windows Update for Business with management solutions" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/waas-integrate-wufb" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Integrate Windows Update for Business with management solutions</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 112),
	(98, NULL, NULL, NULL, 77, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All domain clients run Windows 10 Pro or Enterprise. The domain is organized by department with an organizational unit (OU) for each department that contains that department\'s computers and users.<br> <br>You need to assign devices to servicing channels for Windows updates. You identify a small number of clients in each department that will receive and apply updates as soon as they are released by Microsoft. They will act as pilot tests for the departments before releasing the updates to the remaining clients.<br> <br>Which service channel should you use for this purpose?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Semi-Annual (Targeted) servicing channel. Microsoft recommends assigning a small number of computers to this channel, formerly known as the Current Branch service branch. You should use this channel when you want updates made available for pilot testing to computers as soon as they are released. You have the option of using Windows Server Update Services (WSUS), Microsoft System Center Configuration Manager, or Windows Update for Business to delay updates or choose when updates should apply.<br> <br> For specialized applications, such as point-of-sale (POS), and when you want computers to only receive updates relating to device security, you should choose the Long-Term Servicing Channel (formerly Long-Term Servicing Branch). Long-Term Servicing Channel is a different installation image than standard Windows 10, and the only way to implement Long-Term Servicing Channel is by reinstalling Windows 10. Appropriate quality updates are immediately available but can be managed through update methods such as WSUS.<br> <br> You should configure the Windows Insider Program on computers on which you want an early preview of feature updates. This gives you access to preproduction code for early testing and provides feedback to Microsoft for any issues they discover. Each Insider Program computer must be configured individually using the Settings Update &amp; security utility. You have the option of using Group Policy to block access to the Insider Program.<br> <br> You will typically assign the majority of your network devices to the Semi-Annual servicing channel (formerly Current Branch for Business), which is also Microsoft\'s recommendation for most support scenarios. This channel provides an option to delay the availability of updates to computers until after the updates have been thoroughly tested.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Overview of Windows as a service" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/waas-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Overview of Windows as a service</a><br><a title="Windows 10 Servicing Branches (CB, CBB, and LTSB), Semi-Annual Channel" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/33703.windows-10-servicing-branches-cb-cbb-and-ltsb-semi-annual-channel.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows 10 Servicing Branches (CB, CBB, and LTSB), Semi-Annual Channel</a><br><a title="Assign devices to servicing channels for Windows 10 updates" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/waas-servicing-channels-windows-10-updates" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Assign devices to servicing channels for Windows 10 updates</a><br><a title="Build deployment rings for Windows 10 updates" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/waas-deployment-rings-windows-10-updates" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Build deployment rings for Windows 10 updates</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 114),
	(99, NULL, NULL, NULL, 78, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for your company\'s network. The network includes several satellite offices. Links to remote locations have a relatively low bandwidth. You collect events from all computers running Windows 10 to a central location in your main office.<br> <br> You suspect security problems in some remote offices. You need to be notified about a security audit event as quickly as possible. You need to configure the advanced subscription setting to support this.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Minimize Latency option. This setting has a batch timeout of 30 seconds and will be the option that will notify the administrator the fastest. This setting impacts how all collected events are delivered and cannot be limited to a single type of event.<br> <br> You should not use the Minimize Bandwidth option. This setting has a batch timeout of 6 hours.<br> <br> You should not configure normal delivery optimization. Normal delivery optimization has a timeout of 15 minutes.<br> <br> You cannot up all machines to log and email audit events automatically. The Event Viewer cannot be configured to send emails. Emailing log events requires intervention by the individual using the machine, which would require users to manually monitor events.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Configure Advanced Subscription Settings" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc749167(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Configure Advanced Subscription Settings</a><br><a title="Event Subscriptions" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc749183(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Event Subscriptions</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 115),
	(100, NULL, NULL, NULL, 79, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All domain client computers run Windows 10 Pro.<br> <br> You use Windows Defender to protect computers from malware. A user reports that his machine is behaving oddly.<br> <br> You need to get the status of Windows Defender from the user\'s computer.<br> <br> Which PowerShell cmdlet should you run on the computer?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should run Get-MpComputerStatus. This cmdlet will return the status of the antimalware software on the computer. The cmdlet is run without options to check the status of the local computer. You can specify the -CimSession parameter to run the cmdlet on a remote computer to return information from that computer.<br> <br>You should not use Get-MpThreatDetection. This cmdlet retrieves a list of active and past malware threats that Windows Defender detected.<br> <br>You should not use Get-MpThreat. This cmdlet retrieves the history of threats detected on the computer.<br> <br>You should not use Start-MpWDOScan. This cmdlet starts a Windows Defender offline scan.<br><br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Get-MpComputerStatus" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/get-mpcomputerstatus%20" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Get-MpComputerStatus</a><br><br><a title="Get-MpThreat" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/get-mpthreat" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Get-MpThreat</a><br><a title="Get-MpThreatDetection" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/get-mpthreatdetection" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-MpThreatDetection<br></a><br><a title="Start-MpWDOScan" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/start-mpwdoscan" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Start-MpWDOScan</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 116),
	(101, NULL, NULL, NULL, 80, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your company is using Windows Defender to protect computers running Windows 10 from malware.<br> <br> You suspect that a computer has been infected.<br> <br> You need to start a scan of the computer remotely. The computer must remain online during the scan.<br> <br> Which cmdlet should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Start-MpScan cmdlet. The Start-MpScan cmdlet starts a scan on a computer. The scan runs as an online scan. You can specify the -CimSession parameter to run the cmdlet on a remote computer<br> <br>You should not use the Set-MpPreference cmdlet. The Set-MpPreference cmdlet configures preferences for Windows Defender scans and updates. You can modify exclusion file name extensions, paths, or processes, and specify the default action for high, moderate, and low threat levels.<br> <br>You should not use the Start-MPWDOScan cmdlet. This cmdlet starts a Windows Defender offline scan on a computer.<br> <br>You should not run the Get-MpComputerStatus cmdlet. This cmdlet retrieves the status of the antimalware software installed on the computer on which it is run.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Start-MpScan" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/start-mpscan" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Start-MpScan</a><br><a title="Start-MpWDOScan" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/start-mpwdoscan" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Start-MpWDOScan</a><br><a title="Set-MpPreference" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/set-mppreference" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Set-MpPreference</a><br><a title="Get-MpComputerStatus" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/get-mpcomputerstatus" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-MpComputerStatus</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 117),
	(102, NULL, NULL, NULL, 81, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain administrator. All domain member client computers run Windows 10.<br> <br>A small number of client computers are deployed on their own subnet to test a software package the company is considering deploying. You are asked to provide a summary evaluation of test computer performance.<br> <br>You need to view a summary evaluation of performance and application crashes over the test period. You need to keep the administrative effort necessary to collect this information to a minimum.<br> <br>Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Reliability Monitor. Reliability Monitor is designed to show performance against a baseline over time and provide details on issues. The information is displayed in an easy-to-read summary formation.<br> <br>Depending on the information you want to collect, Performance Monitor might be an additional or more appropriate solution. You can define a custom Data Collector Set so that you can collect information about specific performance counters. You can also use Performance Monitor to display and compare real-time performance information.<br> <br>You should not use Event Viewer. Event Viewer has all the details, but it does not provide a dashboard view, just the raw data. The information you need might be in the event logs, but you would need to find and evaluation the information manually.<br> <br>You should not use Network Monitor. Network Monitor is used to collect and analyze network traffic.<br> <br>You should not use Computer Management. Computer Management is used to access different parts of the management interface, but it does not provide the summary information you need.<br> <br> <br><strong>References<br><br></strong><a title="Reliability Monitor is the Best Windows Troubleshooting Tool You Aren&#39;t Using" href="http://www.howtogeek.com/166911/reliability-monitor-is-the-best-windows-troubleshooting-tool-you-arent-using/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Reliability Monitor is the Best Windows Troubleshooting Tool You Aren\'t Using</a><br><br><a title="How to use Windows 10&#39;s Reliability Monitor to fix and fine-tune your PC" href="http://www.pcworld.com/article/2999237/windows/how-to-use-windows-10s-reliability-monitor-to-fix-and-fine-tune-your-pc.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to use Windows 10\'s Reliability Monitor to fix and fine-tune your PC</a><br><br><a title="Network Monitor" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/cc938655(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Network Monitor<br></a><br><a title="Event Viewer" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/cc938674(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Event Viewer<br></a><br><a title="Computer Management" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/dd391958(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Computer Management</a><br><a title="How to use Performance Monitor on Windows 10" href="https://www.windowscentral.com/how-use-performance-monitor-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to use Performance Monitor on Windows 10<br></a><br><a title="Taming Perfmon: Data Collector Sets" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/askpfeplat/2012/02/27/taming-perfmon-data-collector-sets/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Taming Perfmon: Data Collector Sets<strong><br></strong></a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 118),
	(103, NULL, NULL, NULL, 82, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator responsible for Windows clients in your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. You want to collect information from the logs on the client computers in your network.<br> <br>You run the following on each source computer:<br> <br>winrm quickconfig<br> <br>You run the following on the collector (destination) computer:<br> <br>wecutil qc<br> <br>You need to configure source computers with the correct permissions to support this activity.<br> <br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should add the computer account of the collector computer to the Event Log Readers Group on each of the source computers. Before creating a subscription, both the collecting and source computer must be configured. The computer account of the collector computer must be added to the Event Log Readers Group on each of the source computers.<br> <br>The process has additional requirements in a workgroup environment than in an AD DS domain. For a workgroup, you must configure a trusted hosts list on the collector computer that includes all source computers and you must add an account with administrator privileges to the Event Log Readers Group on each source computer.<br> <br>You should not add the computer account of the source computers to the Event Log Readers Group on the collector computer. This is not required and does nothing to meet the configuration requirements.<br> <br>You should not add your domain user account as a local administrator on each of the source computers. You want the computer account to be used for collections, because logs should be collected from one location. No domain user accounts are involved in the collection process.<br> <br>You should not add the Enterprise Administrator account as a local administrator on each of the source computers. You want the computer account to be used for collections, because logs should be collected from one location.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Configure Computers to Forward and Collect Events" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc748890(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Configure Computers to Forward and Collect Events</a></p>', 10, 4, 119),
	(104, NULL, NULL, NULL, 83, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to receive an alert when the local data drive on a computer running Windows 10 has less than 10 GB of available space.<br> <br> Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Performance Monitor. You can configure Data Collector Sets in Performance Monitor to monitor disk utilization and send a notification when a disk has less than configured free space. You have the option or creating either a data log or a performance counter alert when you create a new Data Collector Set. You would create the Data Collector Set as a performance counter alert and monitor for free disk space.<br> <br>You should not use Resource Monitor. You can use Resource Monitor to monitor real time processor, disk, network, and memory utilization. You cannot use Resource Monitor to set utilization thresholds or alerts when those thresholds are met.<br> <br>You should not use Event Viewer. You can use Event Viewer to monitor events that happened on the computer. Although an event will be written in the Event Viewer when you are low on disk space and you can configure Event Viewer to trigger action when such events occur, you cannot set a utilization threshold for when you are low on disk space.<br> <br>You should not use Disk Cleanup. You can use Disk Cleanup to periodically remove files that are no longer needed. You cannot use Disk Cleanup to set utilization thresholds and notifications when those thresholds are met.<br> <br>You should not use System Configuration. You can view and configure some of the system settings by using System Configuration. You cannot use System Configuration to set utilization thresholds and notifications when those thresholds are met.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Using Performance Monitor" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc749115(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Using Performance Monitor</a><br><a title="Using Windows System Resource Manager" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc754150(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Using Windows System Resource Manager</a><br><a title="Using Resource Monitor to Troubleshoot Windows Performance Issues" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/askperf/2012/02/01/using-resource-monitor-to-troubleshoot-windows-performance-issues-part-1/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Using Resource Monitor to Troubleshoot Windows Performance Issues Part 1</a><br><a title="How to Use Event Viewer in Windows 10" href="https://www.dummies.com/computers/operating-systems/windows-10/how-to-use-event-viewer-in-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Use Event Viewer in Windows 10</a><br><a title="MSConfig the System Configuration Tool." href="https://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_10-update/msconfig-the-system-configuration-tool/273dea8e-4cbe-47e9-8489-f400e879ce17" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>MSConfig the System Configuration Tool.</a><br><a title="9 things you can do with System Configuration, in Windows" href="https://www.digitalcitizen.life/how-use-system-configuration-tool-all-its-awesomeness" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>9 things you can do with System Configuration, in Windows</a><br><a title="Disk Cleanup – Guide for Windows XP, Vista, 7, 8, 8.1, 10" href="https://neosmart.net/wiki/disk-cleanup/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Disk Cleanup – Guide for Windows XP, Vista, 7, 8, 8.1, 10</a><br><a title="How to use Performance Monitor on Windows 10" href="https://www.windowscentral.com/how-use-performance-monitor-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to use Performance Monitor on Windows 10</a><br><br><a title="Windows Server Performance Monitor - Data Collector Sets and Alerts" href="https://www.computerperformance.co.uk/HealthCheck/Alerts.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Server Performance Monitor - Data Collector Sets and Alerts</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 120),
	(105, NULL, NULL, NULL, 84, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You want to monitor real time resource usage statistics on your Windows 10 computer.<br> <br>Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Resource Monitor or Performance Monitor. You can use Resource Monitor to monitor real time processor, disk, network and memory utilization. Performance Monitor also provides for real-time display of the performance counters you choose.<br> <br>You should not use Event Viewer. You can use Event Viewer to monitor events that happened on the computer. Although events will be written in the Event Viewer, it is not used as a real-time monitoring tool. Event Viewer is used for monitoring events historically.<br> <br>You should not use System Configuration. You can view and configure some of the system settings by using System Configuration. System Configuration cannot be used to monitor resources in real-time.<br> <br>You should not use System Information. System Information provides information about system resources and environment but does not provide for the type or real-time monitoring needed.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Using Performance Monitor" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc749115(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Using Performance Monitor</a><br><a title="Using Windows System Resource Manager" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc754150(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Using Windows System Resource Manager</a><br><a title="Using Resource Monitor to Troubleshoot Windows Performance Issues Part 1" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/askperf/2012/02/01/using-resource-monitor-to-troubleshoot-windows-performance-issues-part-1/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Using Resource Monitor to Troubleshoot Windows Performance Issues Part 1</a><br><a title="MSConfig the System Configuration Tool." href="https://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_10-update/msconfig-the-system-configuration-tool/273dea8e-4cbe-47e9-8489-f400e879ce17" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>MSConfig the System Configuration Tool.</a><br><a title="How to Use Event Viewer in Windows 10" href="https://www.dummies.com/computers/operating-systems/windows-10/how-to-use-event-viewer-in-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Use Event Viewer in Windows 10</a><br><a title="System Information" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/cc957818(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>System Information</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 121),
	(106, NULL, NULL, NULL, 85, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to configure the settings for a printer connected to a remote computer running Windows 10.<br> <br> Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Print Management. The Print Management administrative tool allows you to remotely manage printers.<br> <br>You should not use Devices and Printers. Devices and Printers does not have an interface which would allow for remote administration.<br> <br>You should not use Printers and Scanners. Printers and Scanners does not have an interface which would allow for remote administration.<br> <br>You should not use Device Manager. Device Manager does not have an interface which would allow for remote administration. It allows users to view and control the hardware attached to the local computer.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Print Management Step-by-Step Guide" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc753109(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Print Management Step-by-Step Guide</a><br><a title="What Is Device Manager?" href="https://www.lifewire.com/device-manager-2625860" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>What Is Device Manager?</a><br><a title="How to Open and Use Print Management in Windows 10" href="https://www.howto-connect.com/print-management-tool-in-windows-10/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Open and Use Print Management in Windows 10</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 122),
	(107, NULL, NULL, NULL, 86, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain Windows clients. All client computers run Windows 10. You have configured all client computers in the domain to support remote administration via Windows PowerShell.<br> <br> You suspect an issue with malware infecting domain clients and want to explore how serious the issue is.<br> <br> You need to inspect the domain computers for active malware infections.<br> <br> Which Windows PowerShell cmdlet should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Get-MpThreatDetection cmdlet. The Get-MpThreatDetection cmdlet presents active and historical malware threats detected on the computer.<br> <br> You should not use the Get-MpComputerStatus cmdlet. The Get-MpComputerStatus cmdlet presents the status of the antimalware software installed.<br> <br> You should not use the Get-MpThreatCatalog cmdlet. The Get-MpThreatCatalog cmdlet presents a catalog of known threats. The definitions catalog gives information about all known threats.<br> <br> You should not use the Update-MpSignature cmdlet. The Update-MpSignature cmdlet updates the definitions and keeps antimalware software up to date with the latest threat information.<br> <br> <strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Update-MpSignature" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/update-mpsignature" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Update-MpSignature</a><br><a title="Get-MpThreatCatalog" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/get-mpthreatcatalog" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-MpThreatCatalog</a><br><a title="Get-MpThreatDetection" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/get-mpthreatdetection" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-MpThreatDetection</a><br><a title="Get-MpComputerStatus" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/defender/get-mpcomputerstatus" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-MpComputerStatus</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 123),
	(108, NULL, NULL, NULL, 87, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your company network is configured as a single Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All domain clients run Windows 10.<br> <br>You are responsible for troubleshooting domain client computers. You want to set up event subscriptions, so you can be notified when computers are experiencing issues.<br> <br>You need to configure the client computers to support acting as event subscription sources.<br> <br>What should you do on each client computer?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should run winrm quickconfig on each client computer. This configures the computer so that it can be used as a source for event subscriptions. Event logs are an excellent source of information about computers and provide an aid in troubleshooting. Event subscriptions let you collect event log information for multiple computers in a central location. WinRM provides a way to support hardware management in a network environment. It can be used in scripts or as a command line tool. It supports various configuration options, such as setting firewall exceptions.<br> <br>You should not run wecutil qc on the client computers. You run this command on the collector computer, which is the one that will be collecting the events.<br> <br>You should not create and link a GPO that enables the Solicited Remote Assistance Group Policy setting. You would enable this setting if you want client computers to be able issue invitations to request remote assistance.<br> <br>You should not use the Advanced Remote properties in System Properties. These are used to configure Remote Assistance by enabling or disabling remote control and setting the maximum time that Remote Assistance invitations can remain open.<br> <br>You should not use Event Viewer Subscriptions. This is not used to configure a computer to forward events. It is used on the collector computer to set up collection subscriptions.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Event Subscriptions" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc749183(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Event Subscriptions</a><br><a title="Configure Computers to Forward and Collect Events" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc748890(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Configure Computers to Forward and Collect Events</a><br><a title="Wecutil" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2012-R2-and-2012/cc753183(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Wecutil</a><br><a title="Create a New Subscription" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc722010(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Create a New Subscription</a><br><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 124),
	(109, NULL, NULL, NULL, 88, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are testing virtual machine (VM) configurations to find the best configuration for hosting a new application. You configure three VMs on a computer running Windows 10 Enterprise.<br> <br> You need to make real-time comparisons of CPU and memory activity and use between the VMs.<br> <br> Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Performance Monitor. Performance Monitor lets you display real-time performance counter information for multiple computers for side-by-side comparison. This gives you a way to view the detailed performance information you need.<br> <br> You should not use Task Manager or Resource Monitor. Both can report performance information, but as summary information only. In addition, you would need to run separate instances on each VM to collect data.<br> <br> You should not use Reliability Monitor. Reliability Monitor collects information about running applications over time to help identify reliability problems. It does not provide for detailed performance monitoring.<br> <br> You should not use Hyper-V Manager. Hyper-V Manager is used to configure VMs and provides summary information about CPU and memory use but does not provide detailed performance counters.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How to use Performance Monitor on Windows 10" href="https://www.windowscentral.com/how-use-performance-monitor-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to use Performance Monitor on Windows 10</a><br><a title="Using Performance Monitor" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc749115(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Using Performance Monitor</a><br><a title="How to Setup and Use Hyper-V in Windows 10 for OS Virtualization" href="https://www.tenforums.com/tutorials/2087-hyper-v-virtualization-setup-use-windows-10-a.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Setup and Use Hyper-V in Windows 10 for OS Virtualization</a><br><a title="Using Windows System Resource Manager" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc754150(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Using Windows System Resource Manager</a><br><a title="Using Resource Monitor to Troubleshoot Windows Performance Issues Part 1" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/askperf/2012/02/01/using-resource-monitor-to-troubleshoot-windows-performance-issues-part-1/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Using Resource Monitor to Troubleshoot Windows Performance Issues Part 1</a><br><a title="Reliability Monitor is the Best Windows Troubleshooting Tool You Aren&#39;t Using" href="https://www.howtogeek.com/166911/reliability-monitor-is-the-best-windows-troubleshooting-tool-you-arent-using/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Reliability Monitor is the Best Windows Troubleshooting Tool You Aren\'t Using</a><br><a title="Task Manager" href="https://www.lifewire.com/task-manager-2626025" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Task Manager</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 5, 126),
	(110, NULL, NULL, NULL, 89, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are using a computer that runs Windows 10 Pro to test applications and collect performance data.<br> <br> You want to install a new application version. You need to be able to revert to the configuration and system state from before the installation as quickly as possible. The solution should not result in the loss of any user-created data.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should create a system restore point. This gives you a quick and easy way to revert to the system configuration and system state at the point when the restore point is created. Reverting to a restore point does not change user data.<br> <br> You should not run a system image backup. This would provide a way to recover the system, but any changes made to user data after the image is made would be lost.<br> <br> You should not configure File History. File History is used to create multiple generations of copies of files in protected folders. It does not provide recovery for files not in the protected folders and does not provide a path for reverting the computer to any earlier configuration.<br> <br> You should not make a differential backup. A differential backup backs up those files identified as changed since the last full backup. Recovery would require both a full backup and the differential backup, and any file changes made after the backup would be lost.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Windows 10 system restore to earlier time - Restore from a system restore point" href="https://www.ieenews.com/windows-10-system-restore-to-earlier-time-restore-from-a-system-restore-point/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10 system restore to earlier time - Restore from a system restore point</a><br><a title="Recovery options in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12415/windows-10-recovery-options" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Recovery options in Windows 10</a><br><a title="How to Use All of Windows 10&#39;s Backup and Recovery Tools" href="https://www.howtogeek.com/220986/how-to-use-all-of-windows-10%E2%80%99s-backup-and-recovery-tools/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Use All of Windows 10\'s Backup and Recovery Tools</a><br><a title="File History in Windows" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17128/windows-8-file-history" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>File History in Windows</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 127),
	(111, NULL, NULL, NULL, 90, 3, 0, NULL, '<p>You are asked to back up the entire system, including boot sector, programs, and data files on a computer running Windows 10.<br> <br> The user wants to able to use the backup to restore the computer to its current state, if necessary. The user wants the backup to be easily accessible and stored offline.<br> <br> You need to create and configure the backup.<br> <br> Which five actions should you perform in sequence? To answer, move the appropriate actions from the list of possible actions to the answer area and arrange them in the correct order.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should perform the following actions in order:<br> <br> 1. Open Control Panel System and Security.<br> 2. Choose Backup and Restore (Windows 7).<br> 3. Select Create a system image.<br> 4. Select the location for your backup files.<br> 5. Create a recovery drive on a USB drive.<br> <br> You should launch the System and Security Control Panel app. Then select Backup and Restore (Windows 7) to be able to create the type of backup you need. You should then click Create a system image to copy all the information from the system to a recovery image on the backup drive, which is then compressed. The amount of time required to complete the backup depends on the amount of data being backed up. The last step is to create a recovery drive on a USB drive. This meets the requirements for offline storage and ready availability.<br> <br> You should not choose File History. There is a path to creating an image backup through File History, but after choosing File History you must choose System Image Backup, which is not available as a step from the list provided.<br> <br> You should not choose Security and Maintenance. This would let you manage maintenance and security settings, but the available settings do not include an image backup.<br> <br> You are not required to add a drive or create a system repair disc because you are creating an image to be stored offline.<br> <br> You should not copy the backup to cloud-based storage. Depending on the computer\'s condition when you need to recover, cloud-based storage might not be readily accessible.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Back up and restore your PC" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17127/windows-back-up-restore#1TC=windows-7" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Back up and restore your PC</a><br><a title="How to create an image backup in Windows 10 and restore it, if need be" href="http://www.pcworld.com/article/3011736/windows/how-to-create-an-image-backup-in-windows-10-and-restore-it-if-need-be.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to create an image backup in Windows 10 and restore it, if need be</a><br><a title="System Image Backup in Windows 10" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/ff0acd04-c9a4-4d60-b960-10567ad8a262/system-image-backup-in-windows-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>System Image Backup in Windows 10</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 9, 128),
	(112, NULL, NULL, NULL, 91, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are configuring a computer running Windows 10. You are concerned about personal data loss. You also need to provide for access to multiple versions of files as they are modified.<br> <br> You need to automatically backup user files to a Network Attached Storage (NAS) device. You want to make sure you can access all versions of the files.<br> <br> Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use File History. File History can be configured to automatically back up files to a separate hard drive or network location. Files are backed up automatically. File History also lets you retrieve earlier versions of a file, so that if you make a change to a document or other file, you can return to any earlier versions.<br> <br>You should not use PC Reset. This is a utility lets you return your PC to the condition it was in the day you first bought it. You can optionally do so non-destructively, so you retain all of your documents and other data. However, this does nothing to meet the requirements for data protection or access to multiple file versions.<br> <br>You should not use Windows Backup. Windows Backup lets you to back up and restore files. An automated backup would overwrite previous versions of the back, so only the version of the file most recently backed up is available to be restored. Previous file versions are not available.<br> <br>You should not use Windows Recovery Environment. This is used to access tools that let you repair and recover a computer. It provides access to tools such as System Restore, System Image Recovery, Startup Repair, a command prompt, and selective startup. It does not provide backup capabilities or any way to access multiple file versions.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Back up and restore your files" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17143/windows-10-back-up-your-files" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Back up and restore your files</a><br><a title="Windows 10 Feature Focus: Backup and Recovery" href="https://www.thurrott.com/windows/windows-10/4279/windows-10-feature-focus-backup-and-recovery" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows 10 Feature Focus: Backup and Recovery</a><br><a title="How to use Windows 10&#39;s File History backup feature" href="https://www.pcworld.com/article/2974385/windows/how-to-use-windows-10s-file-history-backup-feature.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to use Windows 10\'s File History backup feature</a><br><a title="Windows 8: File History explained" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dn448546.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows 8: File History explained</a><br><a title="What is Windows RE?" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-vista/cc765966(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>What is Windows RE?</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 129),
	(113, NULL, NULL, NULL, 92, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are decommissioning an older computer that contains critical information. You are replacing the computer with a new computer. The new computer is already running Windows 10.<br> <br> You need to back up to a USB hard disk the data files from the old computer in a format that allows the files to be restored on the new computer. The backup destination does not contain any data and is formatted as NTFS. You want to back up only a select subset of available data files. After restoring the files, you need to be able to wipe any copies from the backup media. You need to keep the administrative effort to accomplish this to a minimum.<br> <br> Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use WBadmin. WBadmin will let you back up selected files and folders and restore them to a different computer. You could then wipe the backup drive after restoring the files.<br> <br> You should not use System Image Backup. This backup will let you restore the system as it was on the same hardware. It does not let you choose the data backed up or restore to a different platform.<br> <br> You should not use DISM. You can use DISM to create a Recovery Environment, but it will not allow you to back up your files, or restore the system to what it was.<br> <br> You should not use File History. File History will back up selected folders, including different file versions. There is no need to go through the effort of setting up File History in this scenario.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Wbadmin" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2012-R2-and-2012/cc754015(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Wbadmin</a><br><a title="How to create an image backup in Windows 10 and restore it, if need be" href="http://www.pcworld.com/article/3011736/windows/how-to-create-an-image-backup-in-windows-10-and-restore-it-if-need-be.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to create an image backup in Windows 10 and restore it, if need be</a><br><a title="How to use Windows 10&#39;s File History backup feature" href="https://www.pcworld.com/article/2974385/windows/how-to-use-windows-10s-file-history-backup-feature.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to use Windows 10\'s File History backup feature</a><br><a title="Deployment Image Servicing and Management Technical Reference" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-7/dd744256(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Deployment Image Servicing and Management Technical Reference</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 130),
	(114, NULL, NULL, NULL, 93, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to restart a computer running Windows 10 Pro and boot to the advanced startup options page.<br> <br> Which two actions should you take? Each correct answer presents a complete solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should run shutdown.exe /r /o from a command prompt. Shutdown with the r and o switches restarts Windows and boots to the advanced startup options page.<br> <br>You could also click restart on the Power options on the start menu while holding the Shift key. This produces a reboot to the advanced startup options page.<br> <br>You should not use the Restart-Computer Windows PowerShell cmdlet. This cmdlet restarts the computer, but it does not boot to the advanced startup options page.<br> <br>You should not use the Restart-Service Windows PowerShell cmdlet. This cmdlet restarts a service, not the computer.<br> <br>You should not click restart on the Power options on the start menu while holding the Esc key. This produces a reboot but it bypasses the advanced startup options page.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Shutdown" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-xp/bb491003(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Shutdown</a><br><a title="How to Boot to Advanced Startup Options in Windows 10" href="http://www.tenforums.com/tutorials/2294-advanced-startup-options-boot-windows-10-a.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Boot to Advanced Startup Options in Windows 10</a><br><a title="Restart-Computer" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.management/restart-computer" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Restart-Computer</a><br><a title="Restart-Service" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.management/restart-service" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Restart-Service</a></p></p>', 10, 5, 131),
	(115, NULL, NULL, NULL, 94, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your organization has a shared OneDrive for Business location that contains video files used for self-paced training. During training, they synchronize files from the OneDrive for Business location to their computers.<br> <br>A user named User1 is fired from the company and maliciously deleted all files that were synchronized to the local machine, causing all files on OneDrive for Business and synchronized to all users\' computers to be deleted. User1 also emptied the recycle bin on the local machine.<br> <br>You need to restore the video files.<br> <br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should restore the files from the OneDrive for Business recycle bin. When synchronized files are deleted locally, it also triggers a delete operation on OneDrive for Business and on all machines connected to the same share. When files are deleted from OneDrive for Business, they are maintained in the OneDrive recycle bin for 90. As long as recovered within that time and the files are not manually removed from the recycle bin, the files are available for recovery.<br> <br>You should not restore the files by using the Clear-RecycleBin Windows PowerShell cmdlet. This cmdlet would attempt to empty the local recycle bin again.<br> <br>You should not restore the files from another computer\'s recycle bin. When the delete operation is triggered from OneDrive for Business, files are not placed in the recycle bin of the local machines.<br> <br>You should not restore the files from the second stage OneDrive for Business recycle bin. The user never cleared the recycle bin in OneDrive for Business, so the files would not have ended up in the second stage recycle bin.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How do I recover a deleted item in OneDrive for Business? " href="https://faq.oit.gatech.edu/content/how-do-i-recover-deleted-item-onedrive-business" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How do I recover a deleted item in OneDrive for Business?</a> <br><a title="PowerTip: Use PowerShell 5 to Clear Recycle Bin" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/heyscriptingguy/2015/08/04/powertip-use-powershell-5-to-clear-recycle-bin/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>PowerTip: Use PowerShell 5 to Clear Recycle Bin</a><br><a title="OneDrive retention and deletion" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/onedrive/retention-and-deletion" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>OneDrive retention and deletion</a><br><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 132),
	(116, NULL, NULL, NULL, 95, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are a network administrator for your company. All network clients run Windows 10. Network clients use the OneDrive for Business Next Generation Sync Client for file backup and synchronization.<br> <br> A user reports that his library contains corrupted files that will not open. The user has not tried to use the files for over a month. The user needs to recover a working version of the files as quickly as possible.<br> <br> What should you do first?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>The first thing you should try is to:<br> <br>1. Open the Office 365 portal.<br>2. Browse the library containing the corrupted file.<br>3. Open Version History.<br>4. Select an earlier version and click restore.<br> <br>That procedure will let you recover an earlier version that is hopefully not corrupted.<br> <br>You should not open the OneDrive Recycle Bin. Unless the user deleted the file recently, it is unlikely that there is a copy in the Recycle Bin. File are typically held up to 30 days after deletion.<br> <br>You should not restore a system restore to the most recent restore point. This would restore apps, drivers, and system settings to an earlier point in time, but it does not affect user data files.<br> <br>You should not run the Get-WBBackupSet cmdlet. You would use this cmdlet to get a list of backups created for a computer.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="How to recover missing, deleted or corrupted items in SharePoint Online and OneDrive for Business" href="https://support.office.com/en-us/article/how-to-recover-missing-deleted-or-corrupted-items-in-sharepoint-online-and-onedrive-for-business-3d748edf-c072-46c9-81a4-4989056ebc87" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to recover missing, deleted or corrupted items in SharePoint Online and OneDrive for Business<br></a><br><a title="Invalid file names and file types in OneDrive, OneDrive for Business, and SharePoint" href="https://support.office.com/en-us/article/invalid-file-names-and-file-types-in-onedrive-onedrive-for-business-and-sharepoint-64883a5d-228e-48f5-b3d2-eb39e07630fa" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Invalid file names and file types in OneDrive, OneDrive for Business, and SharePoint</a><br><a title="Delete items or empty the Recycle Bin of a SharePoint site" href="https://support.office.com/en-us/article/delete-items-or-empty-the-recycle-bin-of-a-sharepoint-site-2e713599-d13e-40d6-96dc-66f0a366f74e" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Delete items or empty the Recycle Bin of a SharePoint site</a><br><a title="Recovery options in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12415/windows-10-recovery-options" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Recovery options in Windows 10</a><br><a title="Windows Server Backup Cmdlets in Windows PowerShell" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ee706683(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Server Backup Cmdlets in Windows PowerShell</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 133),
	(117, NULL, NULL, NULL, 96, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You provide end-user support for your company. A user installs a new device driver on a computer running Windows 10. The computer appears to start up normally but locks up after displaying the login screen. The computer displays the advanced boot menu when it is restarted.<br> <br> You need to recover the computer to an operational state. You want to complete this as quickly as possible. and without removing installed apps or user data files. You have a Windows 10 recovery drive and a set of installation files on a removable drive available.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should boot from the recovery drive and run a System Restore. Recovery to a system restore point returns the computer to an earlier point in time, removing recently installed applications and drivers. This process does not affect user data files.<br> <br> You should not hold the Shift key down when you restart and choose the option to reset the PC. This would leave you with three available options:<br> <br> * Reinstall Windows, delete all installed apps, and leave data files in place.<br> * Reinstall Windows, delete all installed apps (including preinstalled apps), and leave data files in place.<br> * Reinstall Windows and return the computer to factory settings.<br> <br> You should not run a full installation from the installation media. This would cause you to lose all data, installed apps, and customizations on the computer.<br> <br> If you do not have a system recovery disk available, you can run a system restore after booting from installation media.<br> <br> You should not select the Last Known Good Configuration from the advanced startup menu. Because the computer has successfully started up, even though it fails after startup, this would not make any change. Last Know Good Configuration can sometimes be used to recover a computer if it will not reboot after changes.<br> <br> <strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Recovery options in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12415/windows-10-recovery-options" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Recovery options in Windows 10</a><br><a title="Data recovery" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/835840/data-recovery" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Data recovery</a><br><a title="Create a system restore point" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/4027538/windows-create-a-system-restore-point" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Create a system restore point</a><br><a title="Windows 10 Restore Point - overview, where can I find it" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/0ac1cd54-f480-4c7d-8da7-0e97aa5577b2/windows-10-restore-point-overview-where-can-i-find-it" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows 10 Restore Point - overview, where can I find it</a><br><a title="Windows Recovery Environment (Windows RE) Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-8.1-and-8/hh825173(v=win.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Recovery Environment (Windows RE) Overview</a><br><a title="Backing Up System State Data" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/cc938537(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Backing Up System State Data</a><br><a title="Using the Last Known Good Configuration Boot Option" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/tn-archive/aa998494(v=exchg.65)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Using the Last Known Good Configuration Boot Option</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 134),
	(118, NULL, NULL, NULL, 97, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You have a custom data collection device installed on a computer that runs Windows 10. The device causes intermittent problems with the computer. The device driver is an unsigned driver.<br> <br> You contact the device manufacturer. The manufacturer has an updated driver available that has not been publicly released but is available for download from its FTP site. You download and install the device driver on your computer. After installing the driver, Windows no longer recognizes the device as installed.<br> <br> You need to go back to the original driver as quickly as possible. Any other changes should be kept to a minimum.<br> <br> Which utility should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Device Manager. Device Manager lets you manage device drivers for installed devices. You should use Device Manager to install the driver after downloading it from the manufacturer and to rollback the driver. This will revert to the original driver.<br> <br> You should not use Devices and Printers. The Devices and Printers utility lets you search for and install devices, including the device drivers for those devices, but it does not provide a means for rolling back a device driver.<br> <br> You should not use Windows Update. Windows Update can be used to reverse updates installed through the Windows Update process, but not manually installed device drivers.<br> <br> You should not use System properties. You can use System properties to restore to the most recent restore point, which can roll back changes, but it can also reverse other changes that have been made to the computer, depending on when the most recent restore point was created.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="How to Roll Back a Driver in Windows" href="https://www.lifewire.com/how-to-roll-back-a-driver-in-windows-2619217" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Roll Back a Driver in Windows</a><br><a title="Recovery options in Windows 10" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12415/windows-10-recovery-options" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Recovery options in Windows 10</a><br><a title="How to Use All of Windows 10&#39;s Backup and Recovery Tools" href="https://www.howtogeek.com/220986/how-to-use-all-of-windows-10%E2%80%99s-backup-and-recovery-tools/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Use All of Windows 10\'s Backup and Recovery Tools</a><br><a title="Wbadmin backup tips for backing up Windows" href="https://searchdatabackup.techtarget.com/tip/Wbadmin-backup-tips-for-backing-up-Windows" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Wbadmin backup tips for backing up Windows</a><br><a title="Windows Update: FAQ" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/12373/windows-update-faq" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Update: FAQ</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 135),
	(119, NULL, NULL, NULL, 98, 2, 0, NULL, '<p>You use a computer that runs Windows 10 Pro for graphics design and editing. File History is enabled on the computer with an external USB hard disk as the destination drive.<br> <br> Graphics files are stored in subfolders of the D:\\GWork folder.<br> <br> You need to configure a way to access previous versions of the graphics files. The effort necessary to configure and maintain the solution should be minimized. <br> <br> What are three ways to achieve your goal? Each correct answer presents a complete solution.</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should copy the D:\\GWork folder and subfolders to the Documents library, mirror the folder to OneDrive, or add D:\\GWork to the protected folders in File History Settings. File History automatically copies the files in the Documents, Music, Pictures, Videos, and Desktop libraries and OneDrive files and makes them available offline on your computer. <br> <br> Copying D:\\GWork folder and subfolders to the Documents makes them managed automatically by File History. The folders could be copied to any supported library.<br> <br> Mirroring the files to OneDrive makes them available offline on your computer and copied by File History. <br> <br> You also have the option to configure additional folders through File History Settings as protected through File History. This will make them part of File History.<br> <br> You should not copy the D:\\GWork folder and subfolders to the C:\\Windows folder, the C:\\Program Files folder, or any other location that is not one of the libraries supported by File History.<br> <br> You should not move the D:\\GWork folder and subfolders or add a folder to a USB external hard disk. This does nothing to protect the files.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="File History in Windows" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/17128/windows-8-file-history" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">File History in Windows</a><br><a title="How to Backup Files Using File History In Windows 10" href="https://www.techbout.com/backup-files-using-file-history-windows-10-25386/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Backup Files Using File History In Windows 10</a></p></p>', 10, 7, 136),
	(120, NULL, NULL, NULL, 99, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are troubleshooting an issue with an application on a computer running Windows 10 Pro. There are security restrictions on the user account you are using for troubleshooting.<br> <br> You need to temporarily disable User Account Control (UAC) for the domain account you are using.<br> <br> Which Windows PowerShell cmdlet should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Set-ADAccountControl cmdlet. This cmdlet lets you modify UAC values for an AD DS user account. You would use the same cmdlet to enable UAC when finished troubleshooting.<br> <br>You should not run the Set-ADServiceAccount cmdlet. This cmdlet is used to modify properties of an AD service account. Service accounts are used provide a security context for running services for applications.<br> <br>You should not run the Set-ADUser cmdlet. This cmdlet is used to modify domain user properties, but it does not control UAC values.<br> <br>You should not run the Enable-ADOptionalFeature cmdlet. This cmdlet enables an Active Directory optional feature.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Set-ADAccountControl" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ee617249(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Set-ADAccountControl</a><br><a title="Enable-ADOptionalFeature" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ee617209(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Enable-ADOptionalFeature</a><br><a title="Active Directory Cmdlets in Windows PowerShell" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ee617195(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Active Directory Cmdlets in Windows PowerShell</a><br><a title="How User Account Control works" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/identity-protection/user-account-control/how-user-account-control-works" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How User Account Control works</a><br><a title="User Account Control" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/dd834802(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>User Account Control</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 137),
	(121, NULL, NULL, NULL, 100, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are the security administrator for your company\'s Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain.<br> <br> You need to ensure that all domain client computers use Kerberos V5 when authenticating to the domain.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should create a GPO under IPSec Settings to require Computer authentication. This GPO requires the connecting computer to always authenticate using Kerberos V5 in the domain. Link the GPO to the domain or other domain object where it will apply to all domain client computers.<br> <br>You should not create a GPO under IPSec Settings to require User authentication. This would require only the user to authenticate using Kerberos V5.<br> <br>There are additional authentication options available for configuration through Group Policy, including forcing Kerberos authentication for both the computer and user, certificate-based authentication, or using NTLM authentication.<br> <br>You should not use the Get-Credential Windows PowerShell cmdlet. The Get-Credential cmdlet allows you to store a user name and password in an object that can be used for any operations requiring security.<br> <br>You should not use the Get-Acl Windows PowerShell cmdlet. The Get-Acl cmdlet allows you to get information regarding access control from a specific object. The command returns a security descriptor for a file or other resource that contains all access control lists (ACLs) for the file or resource.<br> <br>You should not use the Get-AuthenticodeSignature Windows PowerShell cmdlet. The Get-AuthenticodeSignature cmdlet looks for the Authenticode signature for a file. This command can allow you to pass the information along to another command that needs authentication.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Configure Authentication Methods" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-firewall/configure-authentication-methods" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Configure Authentication Methods</a><br><a title="Get-AuthenticodeSignature" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Security/Get-AuthenticodeSignature" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-AuthenticodeSignature</a><br><a title="Get-Acl" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Security/Get-Acl" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-Acl</a><br><a title="Get-Credential" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Security/Get-Credential" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-Credential</a><br><br> </p></p>', 10, 5, 138),
	(122, NULL, NULL, NULL, 101, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. The domain controllers run Windows Server 2016 and the domain is configured at the Windows Server 2016 functional level. Your organization has a subscription to Azure Active Directory (Azure AD). All domain clients run Windows 10 Enterprise.<br> <br> The domain has several security breaches related to domain user accounts and passwords. These include inadvertently disclosed passwords and brute force attacks. You change password policies to require greater password complexity, but this is considered an interim solution.<br> <br> You need to implement multifactor authentication throughout your domain that includes biometric authentication. Users should authenticate to their Active Directory domain user account.<br> <br> What should you use for authentication?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Windows Hello for Business. You can use Group Policy or mobile device management (MDM) policy to implement Windows Hello on client devices running Windows 10. Windows Hello provides for multifactor authentication, including biometric authentication. Windows Hello authentication can authenticate to the following:<br> <br> * AD user account<br> * Azure AD account<br> * Microsoft Account<br> * Intune joined devices<br> <br> You should not use a Microsoft Account. A Microsoft Account is based on an email address and password and does not support multifactor authentication. A Microsoft Account can authenticate to local machine accounts only.<br> <br> You should not use Credential Manager. This is a way of securing storing and managing authentication credentials to automatic logon to applications and web sites.<br> <br> You should not use Trusted Platform Module (TPM). TPM is a technology that provides hardware-based security functions, such as encryption, cryptographic keys, and other strong security measures. It is not an authentication technology, but it supports secure authentication technologies.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Windows Hello" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/uwp/security/microsoft-passport" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows Hello</a><br><a title="Windows Hello for Business" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/identity-protection/hello-for-business/hello-identity-verification" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Hello for Business</a><br><a title="Manage Windows Hello for Business in your organization" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/identity-protection/hello-for-business/hello-manage-in-organization" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Manage Windows Hello for Business in your organization</a><br><a title="Cached and Stored Credentials Technical Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2012-R2-and-2012/hh994565(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Cached and Stored Credentials Technical Overview</a><br><a title="Trusted Platform Module Technology Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/information-protection/tpm/trusted-platform-module-overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Trusted Platform Module Technology Overview<br></a><br><a title="Implementing strong user authentication with Windows Hello for Business" href="https://www.microsoft.com/itshowcase/Article/Content/756/Implementing-strong-user-authentication-with-Windows-Hello-for-Business" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Implementing strong user authentication with Windows Hello for Business</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 139),
	(123, NULL, NULL, NULL, 102, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are a support technician for a computer retailer. A customer purchases a computer running Windows 10 Pro and adds it to his home office. The office is set up as a Wi-Fi network with one access point (AP).<br> <br>The customer creates a HomeGroup from the computer running Windows 10 and joins the other devices in the office to the HomeGroup. The customer has a computer running Windows 8.1 with an attached printer that is shared to the network.<br> <br>The customer is unable to see the Windows 8.1 computer or any shared devices from the computer running Windows 10.<br> <br>You need to provide a solution so the customer can use the computer running Windows 10 to access resources shared to the network.<br> <br>What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You need to enable network discovery on the computer running Windows 10. This should be enabled under the private network profile. Network discovery must be enabled to view other computers and resources shared to the HomeGroup.<br> <br> You should not enable file and printer sharing on the computer running Windows 10. This is not necessary in this scenario. This would only be necessary if you wanted to share resources from the computer running Windows 10 to the HomeGroup.<br> <br> You do not need to enable network discovery on the computer running Windows 8.1 to meet the scenario requirements. This would only be necessary if you wanted to enable the Windows 8.1 computer to access shared resources.<br> <br> You do not need to upgrade the computer running Windows 8.1 to Windows 10. A computer running Windows 8.1 is compatible with a HomeGroup created by a computer running Windows 10.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="How to Create a Homegroup in Windows 10 Quick and Easy" href="http://www.howto-connect.com/create-a-homegroup-in-windows-10-quick-easy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to Create a Homegroup in Windows 10 Quick and Easy</a><br><a title="How to set up and manage Windows 10 HomeGroup on a local network" href="http://www.windowscentral.com/how-setup-and-manage-windows-10-homegroup-local-network" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to set up and manage Windows 10 HomeGroup on a local network</a><br><a title="How to join Homegroup from Windows 10 and share files and printers" href="http://www.techulator.com/resources/13462-How-to-join-Homegroup-from-Windows-10-and-share-files-and-printers.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to join Homegroup from Windows 10 and share files and printers</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 140),
	(124, NULL, NULL, NULL, 103, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All domain clients run Windows 10 Enterprise. All domain controllers run Widows Server 2012 R2 or Windows Server 2016. You are tasked with improving network security.<br> <br>You need to ensure that client computers can run only those applications that are identified as approved for your enterprise and that you have signed as their only qualification. <br> <br>What should you implement?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should implement Device Guard. Device Guard is designed to help provide protection from malware by allowing only those applications that are approved by your organization to run. Device Guard leverages the Hyper-V Hypervisor to provide virtualization-based security. To implement Device Guard, you must enable Virtualization Based Security (VBS), which can be done through Group Policy or individually on computers.<br> <br> You should not implement Credential Guard. Credential Guard is also a type of virtualization-based security, but it is not part of or directly related to Device Guard. Credential Guard is used to protect user authorization criteria and protect against compromise.<br> <br> You should not use AppLocker to provide security based on signed applications. AppLocker allows or prevents applications based on rules that you define. It can be implemented in parallel with Device Guard to fine-tune the protections put in place by Device Guard. For example, you can limit users to signed applications by the publisher, but not based on just whether the application is signed.<br> <br> You should not use Microsoft Passport. Microsoft Passport is a way of improving access security by implementing multifactor authentication.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Device Guard: Windows Defender Application Control and virtualization-based protection of code integrity" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/device-guard/introduction-to-device-guard-virtualization-based-security-and-windows-defender-application-control" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Device Guard: Windows Defender Application Control and virtualization-based protection of code integrity</a><br><a title="AppLocker: Frequently Asked Questions" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/ee619725(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>AppLocker: Frequently Asked Questions</a><br><a title="AppLocker Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2012-R2-and-2012/hh831440(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>AppLocker Overview</a><br><a title="Windows 10 Device Guard and Credential Guard Demystified" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/ash/2016/03/02/windows-10-device-guard-and-credential-guard-demystified/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows 10 Device Guard and Credential Guard Demystified</a><br><a title="Baseline protections and additional qualifications for virtualization-based protection of code integrity" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/threat-protection/windows-defender-exploit-guard/requirements-and-deployment-planning-guidelines-for-virtualization-based-protection-of-code-integrity" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Baseline protections and additional qualifications for virtualization-based protection of code integrity</a><br><a title="Windows Hello" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/uwp/security/microsoft-passport" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Hello</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 141),
	(125, NULL, NULL, NULL, 104, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All domain clients are desktop computers that run Windows 10 Pro or Enterprise. There have been problems with unauthorized access through client computers when people are away from their desks.<br> <br> You need to implement Dynamic Lock on desktop computers.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You link the phone and the computer when you configure Dynamic Lock. When the Bluetooth signal strength falls below the threshold level based on a drop in signal strength, the desktop will be locked in about one minute. Dynamic Lock is currently supported for phones only. Bluetooth is the only communication technology supported for Dynamic Lock.<br> <br> Dynamic Lock does not use near-field communication (NFC). NFC is a very short range (approximately 4 cm) communication technology used in contactless payment systems and similar implementations.<br> <br> You should not use a specialized fob. A phone with Bluetooth is the only device currently supported for Dynamic Lock.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="How to use Windows 10 Dynamic Lock -- and just walk away" href="https://www.cnet.com/how-to/windows-10-dynamic-lock-bluetooth-range/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">How to use Windows 10 Dynamic Lock -- and just walk away</a><br><br><a title="Lock your Windows 10 PC automatically when you step away from it" href="https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/4028111/windows-lock-your-windows-10-pc-automatically-when-you-step-away-from" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Lock your Windows 10 PC automatically when you step away from it</a><br><br><a title="Windows 10: What is Dynamic Lock and How To Enable and Use it" href="https://www.nextofwindows.com/windows-10-what-is-dynamic-lock-and-how-to-turn-it-on" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows 10: What is Dynamic Lock and How To Enable and Use it</a><br><br><a title="Near-field communication" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Near-field_communication" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Near-field communication</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 142),
	(126, NULL, NULL, NULL, 105, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to modify a cached credential stored in Credential Manager on a computer than runs Windows 10.<br> <br>Which command should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the cmdkey utility. Cmdkey is the command-line utility for managing stored user names and passwords or credentials. Cmdkey does not have an option for modifying a credential, so you would run cmdkey /delete and then run cmdkey /add.<br> <br> You should not use mstsc. The mstsc utility is not used to manage cached credentials. This utility is used to create connections with a Remote Desktop Host server.<br> <br> You should not use bcdedit. The bcedit utility is used to modify the boot configuration and boot application configurations.<br> <br> You should not use the net use utility. Net use has an option to store a credential but not remove or modify a credential.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Clear cached credentials with the cmdkey and PowerShell" href="https://searchenterprisedesktop.techtarget.com/tip/Clear-cached-credentials-with-the-cmdkey-and-PowerShell" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Clear cached credentials with the cmdkey and PowerShell</a><br><a title="command line for credential manager" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/windows/en-US/268cb72e-0916-4219-8543-219092d2fb39/command-line-for-credential-manager" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>command line for credential manager</a><br><a title="Net use" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-xp/bb490717(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Net use</a><br><a title="cmdkey" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/cmdkey" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>cmdkey</a><br><a title="Managing Usernames and Passwords with CmdKey" href="http://sourcedaddy.com/windows-7/managing-usernames-and-passwords-cmdkey.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Managing Usernames and Passwords with CmdKey</a><br><a title="bcdedit" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/bcdedit" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>bcdedit<br></a><br><a title="mstsc" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/mstsc" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">mstsc</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 143),
	(127, NULL, NULL, NULL, 106, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You lead a team responsible for upgrading a very large number of client computers that run Windows 7 SP1 and Windows 8.1 to Windows 10. <br> <br> You must collect information about the client computers and the applications they currently support. You suspect some applications will have issues that require resolution before deploying upgrades.<br> <br> You need to identify a tool to help you plan and manage the upgrade process.<br> <br> Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Update Readiness. Update Readiness provides the tools to plan and manage the update process. It lets you collect a detailed inventory and provides a visual workflow to help you manage the process. After collecting your inventory, you identify the applications involved in the upgrade, resolve any issues, and then deploy the upgrade.<br> <br>You should not use Update Compliance. Update Compliance is used to monitor updates applied through Windows as a Service and Windows Defender Antivirus data. It is not used when upgrading to Windows 10 from earlier Windows versions.<br> <br>You should not use Windows Configuration Designer. Windows Configuration Designer provides tools to create provisioning packages and manage devices that run Windows 10. It is primarily designed for use with bring-your-own-device (BYOD) and business-supplied mobile devices.<br> <br>You should not use Deployment Image Servicing and Management (DISM). DISM is used to prepare and service Windows images but does not provide the tools needed for end-to-end management of the deployment process.<br> <br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Get started with Upgrade Readiness" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/upgrade-readiness-get-started" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Get started with Upgrade Readiness</a><br><br><a title="Manage Windows upgrades with Upgrade Readiness" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/manage-windows-upgrades-with-upgrade-readiness" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Manage Windows upgrades with Upgrade Readiness</a><br><br><a title="Use Upgrade Readiness to manage Windows upgrades" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/upgrade/use-upgrade-readiness-to-manage-windows-upgrades" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Use Upgrade Readiness to manage Windows upgrades</a><br><br><a title="Get started with Update Compliance" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/update-compliance-get-started" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Get started with Update Compliance</a><br><br><a title="Monitor Windows Updates and Windows Defender Antivirus with Update Compliance" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/deployment/update/update-compliance-monitor" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Monitor Windows Updates and Windows Defender Antivirus with Update Compliance</a><br><br><a title="Install Windows Configuration Designer" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/configuration/provisioning-packages/provisioning-install-icd" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Install Windows Configuration Designer</a><br><br><a title="DISM Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/manufacture/desktop/what-is-dism" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">DISM Overview</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 144),
	(128, NULL, NULL, NULL, 107, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You create a new Microsoft Management Console (MMC) with custom settings. You save the MMC as CustomMMC. Every time you use CustomMMC, you are prompted to save it.<br> <br> You need to ensure that you are not getting prompted to save CustomMMC every time it is used.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should set the console to User mode. The reason you get prompted is that the console is set in Author mode. By changing to User mode, the prompts no longer happen. <br> <br>You should not modify the permissions. That controls who can use the MMC, not whether you are prompted to save changes to the console.<br> <br>You should not edit the console extensions. Editing the extensions is used to add or remove console functionality.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Microsoft Management Console - Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/bb742441(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Microsoft Management Console - Overview</a><br><a title="Step-by-Step Guide to the Microsoft Management Console" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/bb742442(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Step-by-Step Guide to the Microsoft Management Console</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 145),
	(129, NULL, NULL, NULL, 108, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You provide client support for network users. Network client computers run Windows 8.1 and Windows 10. You use a computer running Windows 10 Enterprise on an x64-bit platform.<br> <br> You want to create a Microsoft Management Console (MMC) that will let you manage 32-bit Windows 10 devices.<br> <br> Which command should you run?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should run mmc /a /32.<br> <br>You need to open the MMC in Author mode to be able to save any changes you make to the console. This requires the /a switch. The /32 switch opens the 32-bit version of MMC (MMC32). <br> <br>You should not run mmc. Windows 10 Enterprise is a 64-bit only Windows version. Because you are using Windows 10 on a 64-bit platform, would open the 64-bit version of MMC in User mode. This is the wrong version and does not save changes to the console.<br> <br>You should not run mmc /a or mmc /a /64. Either would open the 64-bit version of the console in Author mode.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="MMC 3.0 Command-Line Options" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc749428(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">MMC 3.0 Command-Line Options</a><br><a title="Mmc" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2012-R2-and-2012/hh875587(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Mmc</a><br><a title="Step-by-Step Guide to the Microsoft Management Console" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/bb742442(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Step-by-Step Guide to the Microsoft Management Console</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 146),
	(130, NULL, NULL, NULL, 109, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are an administrator for your company. You have set up remote management with PowerShell for all Windows 10 devices.<br> <br> You want to change the Background Intelligent Transfer Service (BITS) and the Windows Update Services on a remote computer to require the users to start the services themselves if they are going to use them or enable other applications or services to start the service if needed.<br> <br> You need to change the startup type for the services.<br> <br> Which Windows PowerShell command string should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Get-Service bits,wuauserv | Set-Service -startuptype "manual" command. This command will retrieve the two services in question, pipe the output to Set-Service, and set the services to manual startup. If already started, the services will continue running until the computer is reset or until manually stopped.<br> <br>You should not use the Set-Service -startuptype "automatic" command. This command sets the two services to automatically start, which will cause the services to start any time the computer restarts.<br> <br>You should not use the Get-Service | Set-Service -startuptype "manual" command. This command gets all services running on the computer and sets all services to manual startup.<br> <br>You should not use the Get-Service | Set-Service -startuptype "manual" -WhatIf command. This command performs a test run of what you are trying to achieve but does not actually make any changes.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Set-Service" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Management/Set-Service" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Set-Service</a><br><a title="Three Cool PowerShell Service Tricks" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/heyscriptingguy/2012/08/27/three-cool-powershell-service-tricks/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Three Cool PowerShell Service Tricks</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 147),
	(131, NULL, NULL, NULL, 110, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are troubleshooting a user\'s Windows 10 Professional computer. The computer has multiple USB printers connected. The user reports issues trying to install new printer drivers.<br> <br> You need to identify all printer drivers in Device Manager.<br> <br> What should you do?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Device Manager and show hidden devices. In Windows 8 this option was removed, but it was re-introduced in Windows 10. When multiple USB printers are installed, but not attached, the unattached drivers are hidden and need to be shown using the steps described.<br> <br> You should not run set devmgr_show_nonpresent_devices=1 and start Device Manager. This command was used in Windows 8 to view hidden devices.<br> <br> You should not use the Get-VMHostNumaNodeStatus Windows PowerShell cmdlet. The Get-VMHostNumaNodeStatus cmdlet shows the status of NUMA virtual machines attached to a host. <br> <br> You should not use the Get-WindowsDriver Windows PowerShell cmdlet. The Get-WindowsDriver cmdlet shows the driver packages that are installed in a Windows image. <br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Get-VMHostNumaNodeStatus" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/hyper-v/get-vmhostnumanodestatus" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Get-VMHostNumaNodeStatus</a><br><a title="How to Use the Windows Device Manager for Troubleshooting" href="http://www.howtogeek.com/167094/how-to-use-the-windows-device-manager-for-troubleshooting/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Use the Windows Device Manager for Troubleshooting</a><br><a title="Get-WindowsDriver" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/dism/get-windowsdriver" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Get-WindowsDriver</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 148),
	(132, NULL, NULL, NULL, 111, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You need to create a task that can be imported into the Task Scheduler.<br> <br> Which format should you use for the task file?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use .xml files. XML files are used in the Task Scheduler import wizard to create tasks on Windows 10 computers.<br> <br>You should not use .txt files. The import wizard for Task Scheduler cannot process txt files.<br> <br>You should not use .ini files. The import wizard for Task Scheduler cannot process ini files.<br> <br>You should not use .dll files. The import wizard for Task Scheduler cannot process dll files.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Import a Task" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc722156(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Import a Task</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 149),
	(133, NULL, NULL, NULL, 112, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You create a custom Microsoft Management Console (MMC) snap-in and distribute it to the IT department in your company.<br> <br> When your colleagues close the snap-in, they are prompted to save it with a new name.<br> <br> You need to stop the snap-in from prompting the users when they close it.<br> <br> What should you modify in the custom snap-in configuration?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should modify the console mode. Console mode controls if console will prompt you to save changed settings or not. If console is in Author mode (default value), it will prompt you. If console is in one of the User modes, console will not prompt you.<br> <br>You should not modify the author property of the snap-in. Details settings contain file details and metadata about the file. We can modify the details, for example who is author of the file, but details are not related to whether console will ask to save changed settings or not.<br> <br>You should not modify the snap-in extensions. By performing this task, you control which snap-ins and their extensions will be available in the console. These settings are not related to whether console will ask to save changed settings or not.<br> <br>You should not modify the snap-in permissions. File permissions control who can access the console file and who can write into the console file. Those security settings are not related to whether console will ask to save changed settings or not.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="MMC 3.0 in Author Mode" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc749526(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">MMC 3.0 in Author Mode</a><br><br><a title="Microsoft Management Console - Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-2000-server/bb742441(v=technet.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Microsoft Management Console - Overview</a><br> </p></p>', 10, 4, 150),
	(134, NULL, NULL, NULL, 113, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You provide support for a small business network that is configured as a workgroup. The network has two geographic locations several miles from each other. You work in the main office.<br> <br> A computer running Windows 10 Enterprise in the remote office runs a custom data collection application. Remote assistance is not configured on the remote computer.<br> <br> You need to ensure that a utility to clear out data that has been logged and processed runs each Sunday on the remote computer. <br> <br> Which tool should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Task Scheduler. The Task Scheduler Microsoft Management Console (MMC) snap-in lets you schedule programs to run based on a set schedule, on user logon, or in response to an event. Because it is an MMC snap-in, you can connect to a remote computer and schedule the task on that computer. MMC does not require Remote Assistance to manage a remote computer. You can also use the schtasks command to schedule tasks from the command line.<br> <br> You should not use Task Manager. The Task Manager utility lets you view summary performance statistics, view and manage running processes, and configure programs that run at startup. Task Manager can be used to manage the local computer only.<br> <br> You should not use Computer Management. Computer Management provides system management utilities and does not provide for scheduling applications to run at a specific time.<br> <br> You should not use Windows Remote Management, which is launched through the winrm command. This is a remote management utility that lets you execute scripts and management commands on a remote computer, but it does not provide for scheduling tasks.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Task Scheduler Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc721871(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Task Scheduler Overview</a><br><a title="Configure a Scheduled Task Item" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc725745(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Configure a Scheduled Task Item</a><br><a title="Schedule a Task" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc748993(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Schedule a Task</a><br><a title="How to Manage Startup Applications in Windows 8 or 10" href="http://www.howtogeek.com/162446/how-to-manage-startup-applications-in-windows-8/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>How to Manage Startup Applications in Windows 8 or 10</a><br><a title="Windows Remote Management (WinRM) Overview" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/mt703305.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Windows Remote Management (WinRM) Overview</a><br><br></p></p>', 10, 4, 151),
	(135, NULL, NULL, NULL, 114, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are responsible for maintaining client computers on your company\'s network. All client computers run Windows 10 Pro or Windows 10 Enterprise.<br> <br> You are troubleshooting an intermittent problem on a client computer.<br> <br> You need to see the USB power and bandwidth allocations for a USB hub that is connected to the computer.<br> <br> What should you use?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use Device Manager. Device Manager lets you view and manage installed devices and device drivers. To view information about USB power and bandwidth allocation, you would open Device Manager, right-click the USB hub, and click Properties. If you open Device Manager through the Microsoft Management Console (MMC), you have the option of viewing device information on remote computers, but you cannot make changes to a remote computer.<br> <br> You should not use Task Manager. Task Manager lets you view summary performance information, but it does not provide specific allocation details.<br> <br> You should not use the Control Panel Power utility. The Power utility lets you configure system power settings, such as Sleep and Hibernation settings, but it does not control USB power usage.<br> <br> You should not use PowerShell cmdlets. PowerShell cmdlets provide an extensive array of management commands and utilities, but there are no cmdlets to display USB power allocation information.<br><br><strong>References</strong><br><br><a title="Open Device Manager" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc754081(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Open Device Manager</a><br><br><a title="Device Manager" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc754610(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Device Manager</a><br><br><a title="Overview of Device Manager" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc725876(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Overview of Device Manager</a><br><br><a title="View USB Power and Bandwidth Allocations for a Device" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc772242(v=ws.11)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">View USB Power and Bandwidth Allocations for a Device</a><br><br><a title="Windows PowerShell Overview" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/windows/it-pro/windows-server-2008-R2-and-2008/cc732114(v=ws.10)" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Windows PowerShell Overview</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 152),
	(136, NULL, NULL, NULL, 115, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>You are troubleshooting an audio issue on a computer running Windows 10 Pro. You import the TroubleshootingPack module to the computer.<br> <br> You need to use Windows PowerShell to troubleshoot the issue.<br> <br> Which command should you run?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use the Get-TroubleshootingPack -Path "C:\\Windows\\Diagnostics\\System\\Audio" -AnswerFile "AudioAnswerFile.xml" command. This command starts the audio troubleshooting pack.<br> <br> You should not use the Get-Command -Module TroubleshootingPack command. This command lists all the cmdlets that are available.<br> <br> You should not use the Invoke-TroubleshootingPack command. The command needs to specify the pack to use. The Get-TroubleshootingPack command is used to specify the pack, which can then be piped through the Invoke-TroubleshootingPack command. This could be a second troubleshooting step, but it would be used with the Get-TroubleshootingPack cmdlet.<br> <br> You should not use the dir C:\\Windows\\diagnostics\\system command. This command lists available troubleshooting packs.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="Use PowerShell Troubleshooting Packs to Diagnose Remote Problems" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/heyscriptingguy/2011/02/09/use-powershell-troubleshooting-packs-to-diagnose-remote-problems/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Use PowerShell Troubleshooting Packs to Diagnose Remote Problems</a><br><a title="Invoke-TroubleshootingPack" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/troubleshootingpack/invoke-troubleshootingpack" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>Invoke-TroubleshootingPack</a><br><a title="TP Cmdlets in Windows PowerShell" href="https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/jj590831(v=wps.630).aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br>TP Cmdlets in Windows PowerShell</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 153),
	(137, NULL, NULL, NULL, 116, 1, 0, NULL, '<p>Your network is configured as a single Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain. All domain client devices run Windows 10. Your company wants to transition from using Group Policy objects (GPOs) to mobile device management (MDM) policies to manage client devices.<br> <br> You need to map GPOs to MDM policies.<br> <br> What should you use first?</p>', '<p id="explanationBodyText"><p>You should use MMAT. MMAT can analyze your GPOs and generate a report of equivalent MDM policies, where equivalents exist.<br> <br>You should not use GPMC. GPMC lets you create and manage GPOs, including GPO links and filtering, but it does not provide tools for transition to MDM policies.<br> <br>You should not use the Copy-GPO PowerShell cmdlet. This command is used to copy GPOs in a domain and between trusted domains.<br> <br>You should not use the Intune console. Intune can be used for device management using MDM, but it does not provide transition tools.<br><br><strong>References<br></strong><br><a title="New tool translates Windows 10 Group Policy Objects into MDM policies" href="https://searchenterprisedesktop.techtarget.com/news/450413881/New-tool-translates-Windows-10-Group-Policy-Objects-into-MDM-policies" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">New tool translates Windows 10 Group Policy Objects into MDM policies</a><a title="Windows 10 Group Policy vs. Intune MDM Policy who wins?" href="https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/cbernier/2018/04/02/windows-10-group-policy-vs-intune-mdm-policy-who-wins/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190"><br><br>Windows 10 Group Policy vs. Intune MDM Policy who wins?<br><br></a><a title="MDM Migration Analysis Tool" href="https://www.petervanderwoude.nl/post/mdm-migration-analysis-tool/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">MDM Migration Analysis Tool<br><br></a><a title="Export a GPO to a File" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-desktop-optimization-pack/agpm/export-a-gpo-to-a-file" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Export a GPO to a File<br><br></a><a title="Active Directory: How to Export Group Policy Settings using PowerShell" href="https://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/37584.active-directory-how-to-export-group-policy-settings-using-powershell.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Active Directory: How to Export Group Policy Settings using PowerShell</a><br><br><a title="GroupPolicy" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/grouppolicy" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">GroupPolicy</a><br><br><a title="Set up Intune" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/intune/setup-steps" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Set up Intune</a><br><br><a title="Set the mobile device management authority" href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/intune/mdm-authority-set" target="_blank" rel="noopener" tabindex="190">Set the mobile device management authority</a></p></p>', 10, 4, 154);
